@node "THEREPLACEMENT" "Buffy.guide: The Replacement"

@{b}The Replacement@{ub}
5ABB03

"Mr. Harris?! Yeah, right!!" - Xander

Xander, Anya, Riley and Buffy are at Xander's when his parents come home, screaming at each other. Xander decides it's time to find a new place to live. Meanwhile a tall, dark, not-so-handsome demon performs a ritual in preparation for his mission: to kill the Slayer. Geez, it's almost as if the undead have nothing better to do.

The Scoobies accompany Xander and Anya to view an expensive modern flat. Anya wants the flat but Xander seriously doubts he can afford it and the two argue in front of the bemused estate agent. At the magic shop, Giles sorts through old inventory when the demon we saw earlier appears, looking for Buffy. Giles attempts to fight the demon but is pushed to the floor. The demon leaves, uninterested in anything but the Slayer. Later Giles recounts the events for the gang, who reach a general consensus that the magic shop is a dangerous place to run. Willow hands Giles a book and he soon finds the demon's name: Toth, a demon who will fight only with weapons and who is very focussed on his goal - in this case the death of the Slayer. Riley, ever the meathead GI Joe, can't wait to kill, kill, kill.

Giles recalls Toth's "distinctive" smell and soon the gang are at the city dump, and run into Spike. Giles asks if he's seen Toth and gives a description - yes Giles, he's right behind you! Toth points his staff in the direction of Buffy and the gang dive out of the way. Toth misses again and then hits Xander as he pushes Buffy out of the way of the beam, before disappearing. The gang help Xander up and they make their way back home, but in amongst the rubbish we see... another Xander. This other, more unfortunate, Xander wakes up next morning and goes home to find himself locked out, the other Xander getting changed inside. He runs to call Buffy, but just as she answers, Suave Xander walks past and Loser Xander hangs up to pursue the imposter. Buffy replaces her handset and talks to Riley about hunting Toth. They kiss, and Dawn appears at the door, making retching noises. The two sisters argue, giving poor Joyce a headache, before Buffy closes the door. Meanwhile, Spike dresses up a mannequin, kicks the head off and then holds it gently in his hands. "Oh, Slayer... One of these days..."

Suave Xander goes to work at the construction site, and is called into the boss's office. Loser Xander watches on through a window, sure that Suave Xander is about to get fired. To his shock, Suave Xander is offered a promotion. As the boss speaks, we see a light playing over his face - its source is a shiny nickel-like disc of metal in Suave Xander's hand. Suave Xander celebrates by renting out the nice apartment he and Anya fought over, and the estate agent comes onto him in the most obvious fashion as Loser Xander listens from the other side of the door. Mister Suave calls Anya to invite her over, leaving a message to meet her at the apartment at 9pm, and then leaves the appartment, and Loser Xander decides now is the time to confront himself, and gets a punch for his troubles. Xander reverts to his original plan of finding Buffy but finds himself thwarted yet again as he approaches Giles' house and hears Suave Xander giving the Scoobies the exact same story he woud have - something stole his face, we have to find it and kill it. In her room, Willow is confronted by Loser Xander, and he proves himself to be the real one by doing the Snoopy Dance. Willow is confused and Xander explains that there's a double out there hypnotising people and that he has even fooled Giles, Buffy and Riley.

Meanwhile, Giles researches while Suave Xander insists they simply kill it quickly. Buffy suggests Toth is responsible and Giles seems satisfied that it's a reasonable explanation. Loser Xander, meanwhile, has decided his double is an evil robot. When Willow suggests it's Toth, Xander becomes depressed that a demon has taken his life from him and can live it better than he does. Meanwhile, Suave Xander plans to accompany Buffy on her hunt for Loser Xander. Willow looks for a spell but gets no help from Xander, who says that if Suave Xander lives his life this much better, maybe he should have it. When Xander remembers Anya and the fact that she doesn't know he has an "evil twin" his tune soon changes and he goes to look for her. Over at Anya's, Xander finds his double's message on the answerphone and then starts searching through the drawers for something. Meanwhile Suave Xander and Anya are together at the apartment, celebrating. Anya is excited about the apartment and wants more - a car, a baby... Suave Xander says there is no rush to do all those things, but Anya, having once been immortal, now feels like she is running out of time. Xander attempts to cheer her up and they kiss, just as Loser Xander bursts through the door.

Each Xander attempts to convince Anya that he is the real Xander. Willow arrives at Giles' and they soon realise they have no idea which one is the real Xander. Giles finally finds what he was looking for and explains that Toth's "stick thingy" splits people's personality traits into two seperate bodies - hence Loser Xander and Suave Xander. Toth's plan had apparently been to split Buffy the vampire slayer from Buffy Summers the college student and slay the weakest of the two - the two halves cannot exists without each other, and the Slayer would be dead. Meanwhile, Loser Xander pulls a gun on Suave Xander. Anya runs forward and attempts to take the gun, and soon all three are wrestling over it while Riley and Buffy speed over in the hope of avoiding a tragedy. When they arrive, Buffy takes the gun and attempts to prove to the two that they are both Xander. The shiny disc turns out to be a flattened nickel. Just as they head for Giles', Toth bursts in. He fires at Buffy, misses yet again, before being jumped by Riley. The pair fight and then Buffy takes over, killing him. Back at Giles', the girls scrutinise the two Xanders' faces and notice everything is exactly the same, while Giles prepares for re-integration. Anya seems interested in bedding the two of them at once, and is disappointed when he's finally re-integrated.

Later, the guys help Xander move his stuff out of the basement. As Riley and Xander pack things away, Riley confides in Xander. He feels like the luckiest guy in the world, "lottery lucky." She is the one. But she doesn't love him. Before Xander can respond, Buffy walks in and they continue shifting Xander's gear around.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

This episode is in the fine tradition of previous "fun" Buffy episodes like @{"Band Candy" LINK "BANDCANDY"} and @{"Halloween" LINK "HALLOWEEN"}. I'll let you in here on my little secret - Buffy probably isn't really my favorite character in the show. That prestigious title goes to the duo of Willow and Xander - the show really wouldn't be half as good without them. Hence, any episode with a lot of Xander in is a sure fave of mine. And this one's double trouble! There's been a disappointing lack of Willow so far this season so her scenes with Xander are great, and there's more Willow-action to see later in this season.

The structure of the episode is interesting - we essentially think of Xander as an underachiever, and therefore we assume that the Xander who suffers the most is indeed the real Xander. Tellingly, at the re-integration, both Xanders are wearing Loser Xander's clothes and making Star Trek jokes. The shiny nickel (what's that, 10˘?) is an annoying plot device of "thank god it was all just a dream" proportions though.

As for Buffy not truly being in love with Riley - observant (over-analytical?) viewers will already have had some idea Riley feels this way. Their relationship has been so... well, normal and safe. On a personal level of course - battling demons isn't exactly what I'd call safe!

@{b}Trivia@{ub}

The "Kill us both Spock" line at the end of the episode paraphrases a line in the classic Star Trek episode 'Whom the Gods Destroy'. Steve Inhat plays the insane, shape-shifting Captain Garth who, at the climax of the story, takes on the form of Captain Kirk. When Spock fails to determine the difference between the two Kirks standing before him, the real Captain Kirk actually says, "Shoot us both, Spock!"

Xander convinces Willow he is the genuine article by performing the Snoopy dance - some scary jumping and pawing first mentioned in @{"Passion" LINK "PASSION"}. Nick Brendon was a little unfamiliar with the cartoon canine's moves but managed to improvise something suitably memorable in his trailer just before the scene. It's now become a much-requested party piece when Nick attends conventions.

Spike has a visible tan line on his arms in some shots. How did he manage that then?

Nicholas Brendon's twin brother Kelly goes by the last name Donovan. The actors' real surname is actually Schultz but they both use their middle names as surnames when working.

