@node "NOPLACELIKEHOME" "Buffy.guide: No Place Like Home"

@{b}No Place Like Home@{ub}
5ABB05

"Out, For, A, Walk... Bitch!" - Spike

Two months ago, two monks were pursued by an unseen evil through the corridors of a church. Finally reaching refuge in a room with their leader, they barricaded themselves in to perform a ritual to protect their "key." As they chanted, the demon or monster they were hiding from attempted to break down the barricaded door. It succeeded, but not before the ritual was finished. The key was safe.

Out patrolling, Buffy strays onto private property, the forecourt of a dissused factory, while fighting a vamp. Soon after the vamp is dusted, a security guard appears to tell Buffy that if she's looking for a rave, she's late as he chased a load of kids out of there the previous night. Buffy feigns disappointment and is about to leave when the guard stops her and hands her a glowing globe about five inches in diameter. The guard has assumed it belongs to Buffy but the vamp must have dropped it. Buffy thanks the guard and leaves.

The next morning, Buffy cooks breakfast for her mum. Dawn comes down, knocks over a vase and manages to take most of the credit when Joyce gets up. Joyce's headaches still haven't gone away and Buffy says they should get down to see a doctor right away. Joyce says she's still the mother and she should be the one worrying, Buffy becoming more irritated by Dawn's presence every second, feeling left out when Dawn an Joyce talk about a book club and the fact that Joyce never had a pet name for Buffy. Buffy decides to go to the opening of Giles' Magic Box, and takes Dawn along with her.

When Buffy walks in, Giles is standing still wearing a magician's cloak and hat. The pair stare at each other for what seems like forever until Giles takes them off. The grand opening isn't so grand - the shop has been open since 9am and still there hasn't been a single customer. When Willow and Riley arrive, Willow is disappointed the Giles isn't wearing his hat and cloak. Buffy presents the globe to the group and Riley suggests they patrol tonight. Dawn says Riley can't patrol, seemingly oblivious that Buffy had said these things in confidence. "She just said you look even cuter when you're all weak and kitteny and she'd better go solo or you'll get hurt."

Riley goes out back to do some "physical re-hab" while Giles assigns Willow to research the globe Buffy found. Buffy decides it's time for her and Dawn to leave. Willow stops her and tells her not to be so hard on Dawn, but Buffy tells her she wishes she was an only child. Buffy and Dawn get home to find Joyce in pain and Buffy wants to take her to hospital. Instead Joyce has her pick up some more painkillers from the hospital pharmacy. While there, Buffy runs into Ben again, who's having trouble dealing with a violent patient - he's the security guard from the previous night. Buffy effortlessly holds down the security guard while Ben straps him to his bed.

The security guard spies Joyce's prescription and says that they "don't make a damn bit of difference." Buffy is confused to see the guy in such a state having seen him a day ago in perfect mental health. He speaks again as he's wheeled away: "Don't think you're above it, missy! They come for your family! They get to your family!!!" Buffy believes she has an idea what's causing her mother's pain.

At the factory, one of the monks we saw earlier is busy writing on a map and praying for God's help when the "Beast" who he has hidden the key from blasts open the large metal door an walks in. The Beast turns out to be a tall, blonde woman. She walks towards the monk and tells him she's been looking all over for him... At the Magic Box, Giles celebrates his first customer with an excited little dance before Buffy comes in.

She believes what's hurting Joyce is supernatural, that the mad security guard saw things that they can't see and someone is trying to get to Buffy by hurting her mother. At the factory, The Beast trys to get the key from the monk, who resists heroically. She then takes a security guard by the head and pushes her fingers into his skull, somehow sucking the life from him.

The Magic Box is bustling with customers and Giles is suddenly unsure if he can cope. They guys all discuss the spell on Joyce and Anya recalls a sorceror who once had a spell which reveals other spells. Giles explains that all spells leave a trace - they're just not susceptible to humans. Buffy decides to try it and gathers the ingredients she needs for the spell. Riley comes over to Buffy's to help her with the spell and soon realises she really invited him over to make him feel less "kitteny". They make a deal to look after each other as opposed to Buffy looking after Riley, and shake on it. Riley kisses her, wishes her good luck, then leaves.

Buffy's trying to start her spell when Dawn interrupts and Buffy shouts at her to leave. Finally alone, Buffy allows herself to fall into a trance and then goes in search of her mother to see if she can see a trace of the spell. She finds Joyce but there's no trace of a spell and Joyce becomes worried because Buffy is acting so strangely. She leaves to go out for a couple of hours. Buffy notices the picture of herself, Joyce and Dawn on the wall. While the images of Joyce and Buffy apppear solid, Dawn's flickers; Sometimes it's there, and sometimes it's not.

Buffy walks into Dawn's room and the entire room flashes - part of the time, the room is empty, a spare room, as it would be if Dawn didn't exist. Dawn appears, asking Buffy what she's doing in her room, and when Buffy looks at her, Dawn is flashing too. Buffy has found a spell, but not what she expected at all. "You're not my sister." Buffy snaps out of her trance and grabs Dawn, suspecting her to be a demon, throws her against the wall and tells her to stay away from her mother. Dawn's hurt beyond words and before either says anything, Giles calls with the result of more research on the glowing globe. It's a protection device called a Dagon Sphere, used to ward off an evil, "that which cannot be named".

Giles warns Buffy that anything unnamed is often something of great fear and worship. Buffy heads back to the factory, also finding Spike lurking outside the house. The numerous fag-ends on the floor suggest he's been spying on her. Buffy enters the factory through the blown-apart metal door at the same time Joyce gets home - she's called off her night out because she feels ill. Dawn offers her some tea. Meanwhile, Buffy finds the monk and is untying him when the Beast creeps up behind her. Buffy turns around and grabs her by the neck. The Beast punches Buffy and the blow sends her flying across the room, hitting the wall at the other side and leaving a large dent in it. Buffy picks herself up, stunned by the strength of this demon.

At the Magic Box, the Scooby Gang are tired from a day's trading - except Anya, who tirelessly talks stock and prices, complaining about the mess in the cash register. Giles offers her a job, provided she shuts up. The Beast continues to beat Buffy - when she tries to punch and misses, her strength knocks chunks out of the concrete pillars. Buffy decides escape is the best plan of action, grabs the monk and dives through a window with him. As they get away, the Beast takes off her broken shoe and stamps on the floor, shattering a pillar and bringing the roof down on herself.

The Monk, weak from his ordeal, sits down to rest by the fence and Buffy tries to keep him moving. With his final breath, the monk tells her she must protect the key, because many more people will die if she fails to keep it safe. The key is energy, for centuries it existed without form, the monks its safekeepers. When the Beast found them, they had to hide the key - made it human in form and sent it for Buffy to protect: Dawn is the key. She's not Buffy's sister, but as far as she knows, she is. The brothers built all the memories so that Buffy would protect the key with her life. At home, Buffy apologises to Dawn for hurting her. Confused by everything, the pair can't decide who'll be the president of the "I Had A Bad Day" club.

The day has been eventful and revelatory, but still they have no idea: "What's wrong with mum?"

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Here we have the first signs of Buffy taking charge, as she has to do because of events later in the season. While Joyce is sick, Buffy, as the oldest, has to shoulder a lot of responsibility. This is nothing new to her, of course, but Joyce has still always been there for Buffy, more important to her emotionally than anyone else.

I can't help feeling sorry for Dawn though, personally. I spend a lot of time wondering about what, if anything, the writers do to try and make you empathise with a certain character or not. It can be a close up on someone's face if they look upset, carefully engineered plots so that you realise things at the exact time a particular character does, certain musical themes, or even something as subtle as cutting between scenes a few frames later. So I don't know if other viewers see Dawn as the annoying little brat that Buffy sees, of if like me they feel for her and hate seeing Buffy say some of the things she does. Buffy's irrationality could be put down to stress. More stress follows, however...

Dawn's comment, "Who died and made you the Iron Chef?" refers to a Japanese cooking show - sort of Ready Steady Cook meets Grandstand. The show's unofficial web site explains that it centres around a battle between two prominent chefs, one being the finest of a specific cuisine and one being a challenger. The contestants have one hour to whip up a multi-course menu that utilises a "theme" ingredient. Commentators discuss the dishes being made during the hour. There's also a sidelines reporter, interviewing the chefs in the Kitchen Stadium and instant replays of cool culinary manoeuvres.

Emma Caulfield told us that she wasn't a natural shopkeeper in her pre-acting days, but soon figured out in one waitressing job that if she told customers the food was rubbish but the drinks were great, she got far bigger tips at the end of each evening. Smart girl.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "FAMILY" "Buffy.guide: Family"

@{b}Family@{ub}
5ABB06

"Are you happy now?" - Beth

Tara tells Willow a bedtime story about their kitten. Tara asks if she can keep the light on when Willow wants to sleep, to look up some spells, so she'll be useful to the group. Willow finds herself again assuring Tara that she is a useful and valued member of the Scooby Gang. Tara wonders aloud whether Buffy found anything at the factory, but Willow reasons that if she had found something, she would have called to say so. At Buffy's house, Buffy and Giles discuss the situation. Buffy can't tell Dawn that she's not really her sister - she recalls her crying about their parents' divorce and cares for her as if she were her real sister - or any of the rest of the group. Buffy is sure the Beast will come after them soon, and sure enough the demon is right now crawling her way out of the rubble of the collapsed roof at the factory.

Buffy's moving her stuff out of her college room - she's spending so much time at home because of Joyce's illness that she's decied she may as well save herself the cash and live at home. Tara embarrasses herself with a joke that goes over everybody's heads and she leaves the room, cursing herself. While she's gone, Willow reminds everyone it's Tara's birthday tomorrow and they must be at the Bronze at 8, and the guys all say they'll be there. At the hospital, Ben sees another patient - with no history of mental problems - apparently gone mad. He finishes for the day and goes to change. Little does he know, there's a demon in the changing room. The demon stalks along in the shadows, showing off its splendid forked tongue. Suddenly the Beast appears from nowhere and grabs the demon, one hand over its mouth. She's going to ask a favor.

Xander and Buffy walk into the Magic Box discussing Tara's party. They had both forgotten but still plan to attend. Giles has had trouble with the research; since she looks human, there's not much to go on. Xander and Buffy sit at the table and start reading. Xander admits that he hasn't got Tara a present yet and the two agree that Tara's "super-nice" but that they don't know her that well. They have no idea what to get her. Giles laughs - they're in a magic shop and don't know what to buy for a friend who's a witch. Meanwhile, while Spike has sex with Harmony, he's thinking about Buffy...

At the Magic Box, a young man with an interesting goatee approaches the table and asks if these are magic books. Giles explains that it's a private collection but he takes no notice. He asks if the guys are all witches. "Hey - don't do any spells on me now, heh heh!" The uncomfortable situation is broken up when Tara and Willow enter the shop. "Well, what do you know?!" Mr. Goatee asks Tara. Tara freezes in shock. "What's the matter, you don't have a hug for your big brother?!" Tara introduces a shocked Willow to Donny, her brother. Donny has come to see her for her birthday - and brought along some family. Tara's father, and cousin Beth. Tara's dad suggests they meet at 6 to have dinner and catch up, then they leave.

Buffy gets home and meets Riley. Dawn appears and announces she's going to her friend Melinda's house for dinner. Buffy forbids her from leaving the house and Dawn storms up to her room. Riley is shocked by this over-reaction and asks Buffy what the problem is but she doesn't tell him anything. He leaves, annoyed that Buffy won't confide in him. In the evening, Tara arrives at her room to find her father standing inside. The door wasn't locked so he let himself in. He says he had hoped letting Tara go would have stopped her obsession with witchcraft. He has come because Tara is turning twenty - the same age her mother was when something happened to her. He believes there is evil in Tara that will come out and asks what her friends will think if they see her true face. He says she must come home with them. They will leave town next morning.

The Beast sends her captive demon out on a mission to hunt Buffy, disgusted with herself for fighting with a Slayer ("how unbelievably common!"). Tara sits alone, staring into space when Willow comes to tell Tara there's a Scooby meeting but she doesn't want to go, apparently worried because her family are in town. After Willow has left, Tara grabs a spell book, and soon finds what she's looking for. At the Magic Box, Tara creeps in while the meeting is in full swing and casts a spell on the gang. Riley's drinking at Willy's Place and buys a drink for a pretty girl called Sandy who we've seen before. She invites him some place more private but Riley declines - he loves Buffy, and he doesn't go out with vampires. At Spike's Harmony comes home at tells Spike the word: the Laoff demon has sent his brethren to kill the Slayer. Spike heads out.

Tara meets Beth, apologises for missing dinner and tells her she's not going back home with them. Beth calls her a selfish bitch for leaving her father and brother alone with a house that needs taking care of, and says she can't wait until Tara's friends find out who she really is. Tara says they won't find out, and Beth realises she has cursed the gang. Tara says it's just to hide the demon side of herself, that it's harmless, and begs Beth not to tell her father. At the Magic Box, Willow hears a knock at the door, and answers it. We see there are brethren of the Laoff demon at the door but Willow doesn't see them - the curse has blinded them to all demons, not just Tara's demon side.

While Beth berates Tara for being dishonest, the demons walk around the magic shop, undetected. When they walk into the training room, Buffy thinks she senses a presense in the room, but isn't quite sure until one jumps her and she screams for Giles. Xander, nearest to the room, runs to help but feels himself blocked as he tried to get through the door. The demon then punches him and tries to strangle him. Willow grabs a chair and hits the invisible demon with it. The demon knocks Willow aside and Giles hides Dawn under a table. In the training room, Spike appears to see Buffy struggling with the demons. He takes one while Buffy "accidentally" slays the other. Spike can't understand why Buffy doesn't thank him.

Giles stands looking around when he's suddenly punched, as Buffy comes through into the shop. Everyone's panicked and Buffy tells them to be quiet so she can concentrate. Tara walks in just in time to alert Buffy to the demon behind her. Buffy turns around and the demon grabs her, throwing her across the table. Spike, still in the training room, manages to slay the demon he had held down before. Tara reverses the spell so Buffy can see the demons and Tara's family arrive in time to see Buffy slay the last of the three demons. Tara's father explains that the women in his family have demonic qualities and the Scoobies realise that Tara put a spell on them to hide her demon side.

Tara's father says the camper is outside, she should be with us where she belongs. Willow protests but he says it is no concern or hers, so she asks Tara. She doesn't want to leave, but her father doesn't appear to take this into consideration. "Go ahead," says Buffy. "You want her? Take her." Tara's eyes drop to the floor. "You just gotta go through me." Dawn moves to Buffy's side, arms folded (it seems that pose is genetic, not just a Slayer thing) "And me." The gang all take Tara's side... with the exception of Spike, who doesn't give a rat's ass either way. Her family insist she goes with them until Spike gets fed up and decides the best way to solve this quickly is to hit Tara. He does, and his chip shocks him - Tara is human. It was just family legend, to keep the girls in line. They leave, empty-handed.

Tara's party turns out great - they listen to My Vitriol, Dawn buys her a broom... Giles, a crystal ball. Dawn runs around excited having never been in a club before. Willow and Tara dance and Willow tells Tara how proud she is of her, growing up in the environment she did and being the person she is now. Tara rests her head on Willow's shoulder and the two dance into the night, their feet never touching the ground.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

The oppression of Tara's family depicted here is unbelievable. The scene for that is set the moment Tara meets her brother in the shop (and before then he's already proved himself to be a fool anyway) - down to some beautiful acting from Amber Benson (Tara). In general, I really think a lot of men are total dicks anyway so the times you feel most for Tara are when her cousin Beth badmouths her. If a man says a women's place is the kitchen, it's bullshit. If a woman says it I just want to scream... when Beth says pretty much that it makes my blood boil... it's a devastatingly effective episode. Check out the "You've gotta go through me" sequence where Tara realises she has Buffy's support - genius. Oh yes. This episode rocks. I mean, they have My Vitriol on the soudtrack!

Didn't take long for them to trash the magic shop, did it? Giles has had the shop for about a week, and already it's been ripped apart by demons. Some things never change. Finally, an episode this season with more Willow! Yay.

@{b}Trivia@{ub}

Megan Gray plays Sandy, the vampire that Riley meets in Willy's bar. The character previously appeared in Season Three's Doppelgängland as the girl at the Bronze killed by Vampire Willow. Nice touch. Both episodes being written and directed by Joss probably had something to do with it.

Fools for Love: Ben instantly qualifies as potential love interest for Buffy when he takes his shirt off. Spike has his second lust-filled dream about Buffy. Could this be love? And Willow and Tara may not snog on screen, but they do hug.

This week's music is provided by Yo La Tengo ('Tears Are In Your Eyes'), My Vitriol ('Cemented Shoes'), Motorace ('American Shoes') and Melanie Doane ('I Can't Take My Eyes Off You'). The first track plays in Willy's place when Riley gets picked up by Sandy. The others feature at Tara's birthday party at the Bronze.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "FOOLFORLOVE" "Buffy.guide: Fool For Love"

@{b}Fool For Love@{ub}
5ABB07

"You are beneath me" - Sassidy, Buffy

It's a regular night for Buffy, in the graveyard, patrolling for vampires, just like always. She comes across a vamp punk in a Clash t-shirt and the pair fight, just like always. This night, however, something is different. Buffy is about to dust the vamp when he intercepts her move and drives the stake back towards her. It sticks in her gut - stabbed, with her own stake. Buffy pulls out the stake but, in shock and too weak to fight, decides to run. But the vamp catches up easily, takes Buffy's stake and is just about to kill her when Riley appears and knocks him down. The two wrestle on the ground, the vamp eventually knocking Riley aside and escaping.

In Buffy's room, Riley uses his medical knowledge to patch Buffy up but advises her to see a real doctor and then asks how many vampires attacked her. Buffy says one, embarrased and not sure how she could have made such a mistake. Dawn appears to warn them that Joyce is approaching and Riley quickly hides the bloodied cotton buds. Joyce appears and when she sees the disinfectant, Dawn covers for Buffy pretending it's a nail polish experiment. Joyce leaves the room and Buffy shows Dawn her bandages, then asks for her help with the household chores. Riley takes on the non-household chores: he will patrol with the Scooby Gang tonight. On patrol, Xander, Willow and Anya watch on in bemusement as Riley creeps ahead among the headstones, sending them an array of confusing military hand-signals.

Buffy meanwhile beats herself about the head for nearly getting herself killed last night, and is researching the Slayers that came before her in the hope of learning from their mistakes. Buffy and Giles are at a loss - there's no-one keft to tell them how their final battles went. Then Buffy remembers Spike has killed two Slayers in his time and pays him a visit to ask him how. Buffy offers Spike cash for his information and he notices her injury. Relishing the attention, Spike teases her for a while before relating his story.

London, 1880 - At a party, William the Bloody sits alone in a corner writing a poem. The men and women at the party are discussing a rash of disappearances and William says he would rather set his mind on things of beauty - his poetry. One man snatches his unfinished poem and reads it aloud, to the amusement of everyone but William. He walks through to a lounge where the object of his affection, Sassidy, sits alone, and admits his poems are about her. But she tells him he means nothing to her and walks away. "You are beneath me." William leaves and wanders around town, tears rolling down his cheeks. Tearing his poetry up in a dark alleyway, he is approached by Drusilla, who asks him why he's crying. Sensing his loneliness, Drusilla offers him a life away from the fools who surround him. She feeds on him but despite the pain he does nothing to prevent her.

Sunnydale, Present - The Scoobies stalk the punk vamp who staked Buffy, and find there's a whole gang. There's too many to take so Riley suggests they come back in the morning with weapons. At the Bronze, over a game of pool, Spike tells Buffy that becoming a vampire was a profound experience - he rejected society's rules and got himself a gang.

Yorkshire, 1880 - Inside a mineshaft, Angel holds William against a wall by his neck and threatens to kill him for getting them into trouble in London. When Angel lets go, William tells Angel his name is Spike now, and he'd do well to remember it. The two argue over Angel's desire to keep a low profile and Spike's love of complete chaos, and Angel pins Spike to the ground, telling him one day he'll learn the hard way - from an angry crowd, or from the Slayer. Spike asks: "What's a Slayer?" From then on, as Spike now explains, the Slayer became an object of obsession. Rather than hiding from the Slayer he hunted her.

China, 1900, Boxer Rebellion - As the town burns, Spike fights with a Slayer who's armed with a sword and some devastating martial arts knowlege. Spike sticks her sword into a nearby monument and, swordless the Slayer continues to fightm barefist. Pining him up against a pillar with her leg, she pulls out a knife and it about to end his life with it when a blast at the window knocks her aside. As the two struggle, the Slayer drops another weapon and knocks Spike away so she can grab it again, but Spike is too quick to return and just as she grabs for the weapon, Spike grabs her arm and twists it behind her back. She's unable to move and Spike drinks from her - he has won. The Slayer speaks in a Chinese tongue: "Tell my mother I'm sorry." The message is lost on Spike, who has sex with Drusilla as the building burns down. Later, Angel congratulates Spike - this makes him one of them. They leave China, the town in flames behind them.

Sunnydale, Present - Buffy looks disgustedly and Spike, who finds it hard to believe Buffy doesn't get off on violence like he does. Spike tells Buffy that sooner or later some force of evil or another will defeat her; the problem is that her victories have made her over-confident. Buffy says she can handle herself and Spike knocks her in the stomach to prove his point. They both scream in pain, drawing attention to themselves, and a small crowd gathers. Spike has more to teach her and leads the way. Meanwhile, Riley returns alone to the vampire gang's hideout at the graveyard. The punk vampire uns to him and gets dusted for his troubles. Then, with perfect timing, Riley sets a granade and runs, the rest of the vamps inside runningover the granade just as it detonates. Outside the Bronze, Buffy and Spike share a demented kind of sparring session. Buffy pins him to the ground and demands to know how he killed the second Slayer.

New York City, 1977 - Spike, decked out in bluejeans, a black top with badges and spiked hair, fights another Slayer on a graffitti-covered train carriage. Spike tells Buffy this Slayer was more like her - "cunning, resourceful and hot.... But death is on your heels baby, and sooner or later, it's going to catch you. Part of you wants it." Spike pins the Slayer down and snaps her neck.

Sunnydale, Present - Spike concludes that because every day Buffy slays, she wonders what it must be like - every Slayer has a death wish. Even Buffy, although her ties in the real-world have kept her alive so far. Buffy tells him to get out of her sight and Spike dares her to hit him. Spike moves to kiss her and she steps back, then pushes Spike to the floor and says that even if she did want to die it would never be Spike. "You are beneath me," she says, throwing him his money and walking off into the night. Spike gathers his cash, sobbing, but his grief soon turs to anger. He heads for Buffy's house, stopping by his crypt to grab his shotgun.

South America, 1998 - Spike argues with Drusilla, who's been having an affair with another demon. Drusilla says when she sees Spike all she sees is the Slayer, so great is his obsession.

Sunnydale, Present - At Buffy's house, Buffy goes to tell her mum she's done the grocery list to find her packing things for a trip. When she asks where she's going, Joyce tells her she's going into hospital for a cat-scan. Some time later, Buffy walks out onto the back steps of the house and holds her head in her hands, unable to stop the tears. Spike approaches and Buffy lifts her head and asks what he wants now. When Spike sees she's been crying he asks whats wrong and whether there's anything he can do for her. Buffy doesn't answer and they sit, in silence.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

This is like a mix between @{"Angel" LINK "ANGEL"} and @{"Becoming" LINK "BECOMING1"}, but centered around Spike rather than Angel. Of course, the main difference between the two stories is that Angel's soul has been restored. However the the idea that someone with a soul is automatically good is obviously wrong, so why shouldn't someone without a soul be capable of compassion? In this episode, Spike explodes that very myth. Would this have happened had Spike not had his implant? Of course not - then again, Buffy would probably have killed him by now if that was the case. But from this point on, their relationship has taken on a different meaning.

As always, the glimpses into the past are a real treat, as are the costumes and wigs and stuff that come along with it. Of course the fact that vampires do not age gives the writers free reign to recall any event or situation from the time of their death up to the present day. There are also some nice continuity references: Did "William the Bloody" get his name from his bloody awful poetry? One of the "gentlemen" who ridicule Spike also says he'd rather have railroad spikes in his head than listen to that rubbish. Interestingly, Drusilla feeds off Spike, giving the impression that she made him a vampire - however in previous episodes, Angel has been named as Spike's sire.

The scenes with Riley are strange. The way he takes out the vampire gang is impressive but it's difficult to see what purpose the scenes serve. The punk vampire thing is also strange. Don't you hate cliches? God, I hate it when people reduce an entire movement to some fashion thing they think ended in 1979. Punk is alive in 2002 and now more than ever it's as much about having a brain than anything else. Spike's a big fan of the Ramones etc, and indeed the second Slayer battle takes place on a train in 1977, so I'm guessing there was supposed to be something subliminal there?... Speaking of trains, don't you love train scenes? The way the carriage shakes and the high speed. Interesting use of such a train setting can be seen in the film 'Stigmata'.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "SHADOW" "Buffy.guide: Shadow"

@{b}Shadow@{ub}
5ABB08

"Just do what I do - flip through the pages and look busy" - Anya

It's the day of Joyce's cat-scan. Buffy buys a coke for Dawn while they wait and Dawn wonders aloud what "cat" means. At the Magic Box, Giles shows the guys his advert in the new phone book: "Your one stop spot to shop for all your occult needs. " Xander and Willow tell Giles about Riley's solo vampire-slaying and then get down to some more research on the Beast. In a plush hotel across town, Dreg, one of the Beast's babbling servants, presents her with an age-old spell. He calls her Glory. Glory's spell will work once she gets some ingredients - which she plans to pick up at the Magic Box.

Riley calls at Buffy's to find the door unlocked and ajar, walks in and finds Spike sniffing various items of clothing in Buffy's room and throws him out. Spike tells him he was out with Buffy drinking last night and says he's not Buffy type - she likes her men to have a dark side. Riley flips and pushes Spike outside near the sun, telling him he's the one who knows what Buffy needs - them Spike informs him that Buffy's over at the hospital right now. Buffy hadn't called him. Riley goes to the hospital and sits with Dawn while Buffy talks to her mum. They've found a shadow on the scans and they're going to do a biopsy to check it out.

At the Magic Box, Tara and Willow formulate a theory that the Beast (who we now know as Glory) pre-dates written language, citing the description of her as "that which cannot be named". Just then Glory walks in to buy her ingredients, Giles serves her like any other customer and she leaves. At the hospital, Riley lays a jacket over Dawn, who's sleeping in the waiting room. A doctor emerges from the recovery room and informs Buffy that Joyce has a brain tumor, and that the condition will progress very quickly. Joyce has about a 1 in 3 chance of survival. While the doctor asks questions about whether Joyce uses a cellphone and other things, Ben the intern approacvhes and tells him he's needed in ICU. Ben advises her to take a break, get out of the hospital for a while.

Buffy, having always been able to fix things before, is frustrated that she can't do anything to help her mother. She tells Riley there must be a spell or something they can do to fix it. She leaves Dawn for Riley to drop at school and they decide not to tell her anything yet. Dawn will go over to the Magic Box after school. At the shop, Anya finds a copy of Glory's receipt and realises two items on there are for a powerful spell. Giles is unconcerned, saying the woman he sold them to would have to have enormous power... then the gang (minus Xander) realise the Beast has been in the shop. Riley takes Dawn to the park and she tells him she's glad he's around - and so is Buffy. She mentions Angel and unintentionally hurts his feelings by telling him Buffy doesn't get worked up over him like she did over Angel.

Buffy asks the guys about a spell but the general concensus is that magic and the human body shouldn't be mixed. The mind is so complex - too much could go wrong. Anya lets slip about Giles selling the ingredients to Glory for the spell, and that now intends to use the spell to transform a cobra into a reptile monster. Glory goes to the zoo and takes a cobra from its glass case, places it in a pot, then begins chanting with Dreg. Buffy surprise-attacks Glory but she manages to get in only a few punches before Glory over-powers her and throws her through the glass case, all the while completing her incantation. The cobra breaks its container as it grows into a large demon and Glory sends it on a mission to find the key. Riley visits the Magic Box and Xander confronts him about his decision to go back to fight the vampires alone, and if he's ok. Riley says he's fine, "just a little crazed". After he leaves, Buffy calls and tells Giles the snake demon is loose, and school's out so Dawn's on her way there now. Buffy stays at the hospital, determined she will be there when her mum wakes and is told the news.

While Dawn studies and the doctor tells Joyce the situation, Riley drinks at Willy's bar and meets Sandy again. They dance, and he allows Sandy to feed from him for a few seconds, then stakes her. The Cobra-demon passes through the park and realises the key had been here - he can sense the key using a special vision given to him by Glory. Buffy arrives at the Magic Box to pick up Dawn and the Cobra-demon smashes in through the window before Dwn has a chance to get her things together. The snake recognises the key and leaves to tell Glory the news. Buffy realises what the snake's mission was and she sets off in pursuit of the snake. Buffy can't keep up with the snake and Giles picks her up in his car. Buffy jumps on the snake and manages to strangle the life out of it with a chain... Or not! Suddenly it flings Buffy from its back. Buffy gets up and punches it repeatedly in the head until it stops moving, and well, a little while longer than that, just to be sure. It was close - we see Buffy and the snake are only a metter of yards away from Glory's appartment.

At the hospital, Joyce tells Buffy she wants to talk to Dawn alone. Buffy sends Dawn in and sees Riley, who's wearing a long-necked sweater to hide the bite. He tries to get her to cry and let it all out but she won't. If she starts now, she won't be able to stop. Dawn calls Buffy back into the room, leaving Riley stading alone in the coridoor, helpless.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Seeing Spike sniff Buffy's sweater puts the moment they shared at the end of @{"Fool For Love" LINK "FOOLFORLOVE"} into yet another strange perspective. Is Spike a good guy now? Who knows?

Effects-wise, the snake looks pretty cool until they try to show Buffy hanging onto its back - then she looks like a barbie doll in a noose, blowing in the wind. No, really, you should try that one, it's uncanny... Also, in the scene where Buffy slays the snake-demon, the demon's sudden re-animation seems unnecessary, and ruins the illusion even more when we see her repeatedly punching what is obviously a rubber model. Why didn't they cut that? I know I would have.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "LISTENINGTOFEAR" "Buffy.guide: Listening To Fear"

@{b}Listening To Fear@{ub}
5ABB09

"I don't wanna be the one that finds the bodies anymore." - Willow

Buffy and Dawn are visiting Joyce when the doctor comes in and tells her she's scheduled for surgery at 10am the day after tomorrow. Joyce can't stand the thought of waiting in hospital another two days. Joyce tells Buffy she should be patrolling but Buffy is sure the Scoobies have everything under control. In actual fact, they're taking the beating of their lives from two vamps. Riley didn't show up so they're struggling but, moving quickly, Willow manages to dust them both. Riley would rather not patrol - instead preferring tonight to be fed on again by a lady vampire.

Willow brings presents to the hospital: a beer-hat for Joyce, a book about spells for Dawn, and a history book and yo-yo for Buffy. Willow discusses a history test with Buffy and Joyce suddenly proclaims: "I'd rip it in half, and stick it in bed with me!!" The girls leave Joyce to have a rest and Buffy explains to Dawn that the tumor can cause Joyce to say strange things, but after the operation, she'll be okay again. Walking down the corridoor, a mental patient points at Dawn and says there's no-one in there. Ben walks over and tells them the mental ward is booked to capacity and they're letting the patients with families go home. He asks what the patient said to Dawn but Buffy says he was just babbling.

Tara and Willow are snuggling under the stars, naming their own constellations, when they spy a meteor flashing through the sky. It lands in the woodland in Sunnydale and something climbs out. A mental patient is taking a walk through the woods and the demon which crawled out of the meteor attacks him, then makes its way into the hospital. Joyce has decided she wants to go home. They cal a doctor in to discuss it and Joyce gets agitated. Buffy sends Dawn out of the room to get something from the vending machine. The doctor advises against Joyce returning home: it means Buffy taking care of her round the clock, checking vital signs and administer medicine. But Buffy is willing and the doctor says they'll have to go through all the instructions before Joyce even thinks of getting out of bed. Meanwhile, the meteor demon, climbing undetected along the ceiling, moves towards Dawn. Tara and Willow have alerted the Scooby Gang and they come to the conclusion that a demon crashed to Earth in the meteor. They check the surrounding area and find the mental patient, dead. Riley notices a substance in the dead guy's mouth and as soon as he extracts it the entire gang notice the horrible stench. Riley says he'll examine the body while the rest of the gang go and research. When the gang are gone, Riley makes a call on his cellphone to the military.

At the mental ward, the night nurse turns the light off for the night. The ET-demon is in the room, and he attacks one of the patients, but in the ward office, the nurse pays no attention to the cries from the room - that's normal on a mental ward. The demon then watches Buffy, Joyce and Dawn as they leave hospital for home. At home, Joyce has Buffy turn off all the lights because they hurt her eyes. Meanwhile a helicopter lands in the woods and Riley briefs the soldiers on the situation. The guys decide to use geiger-counters to trace the demon and get to work searching the area. Despite the fact it's still night, Joyce gets up to make breakfast, leaving the stove on un-ignited and breaking a few pots before Buffy and Dawn come in, turn off the gas and manage to get her back into bed. Dawn strokes her mum's head, when suddenly Joyce jumps back away from her. "Don't touch me! You thing! Get way from me! How did you get here?" Dawn runs from the room and Buffy tells Joyce to get some rest, then goes to speak with Dawn. Dawn has realised mad people keep calling her a "thing," saying she doesn't belong here. Buffy tells Dawn it's not her, it's them, and not to listen when people say things like that. The Scoobies research at the Astronomy section of the university. Willow finds similar cases dating back to the Queller impact in the 12th century, and Xander finds a small anecdote about primitives who prayed for the moon to send meteors to "quell" the madmen.

Willow finds cases on the computer of great epidemics of madness followed shortly by hollow-meteor events like theirs in Sunnydale, and the guys decide Glory probably summoned the Queller demon. Willow calls Riley to tell him, but he already knows - he's down at the hospital with the corpses of five mental patients. Riley says he thinks he has the demon cornered and tells Willow to keep researching. At home, Dawn listens through the wall as Joyce babbles incessantly. Buffy, unable to stand the noise, goes into the kitchen to do the washing-up and puts the radio on, but it fails to keep her thoughts from her mother and she starts crying. Joyce continues to babble about being stared at and we realise she's actually seeing a demon - the ET is on her ceiling. As Riley realises the demon has eluded them and how, by hitching a ride under the car as Joyce was taken home, the demon falls on Joyce and salivates on her face. Dawn hears the noise and comes through with a coatstand to knock the demon off Joyce. When it gets back up and comes after her, however, she runs and calls for Buffy, who can't hear because she's running water. Dawn gives a big, loud scream and Buffy races upstairs and encounters the demon. They struggle and fall back downstairs. Buffy loses sight of the demon before she gets up and walks around catiously, checking every shadow for the monster. She grabs a knife from the kitchen and something moves - it's Spike, stealing pictures of Buffy from the basement.

The demon jumps at Spike and pushes him to the ground. They wriggle on the floor and Spike kicks the knife out of Buffy's hand by accident before she has the chance to do anything. The demon then suddenly turns to Buffy and lunges at her. Spike grabs the knife and throws it to Buffy, who makes sweet mincemeat out of the demon as it pins her down. Spike helps her up, and the military guys bust in a little too late. Buffy runs upstairs to check Dawn and Joyce are ok. Ben finishes his shift at the hospital and gets into his car to find Dreg in the back seat, who tells him that summoning the Queller demon has drawn attention to them. Ben tells him to get out and he obliges. Ben says he's sick of cleaning up Glory's mess.

Back at the hospital, Joyce is getting ready for surgery when she tells Buffy she's realised Dawn isn't her child. But they agree that Dawn belongs to them. Buffy promises her mum that she will care for Dawn if anything goes wrong.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

I already thought Joyce was a tad insane anyway. Her sudden lapses into madness are somehow more convincing from her than they would be coming from, say, Xander or Willow. Not much really happens here though. The gang just slay another demon. Joyce goes home for a couple of days and drives the girls mad.

The main revelation in this episode is the connection between Ben and Glory. It's a connection we discover soon, but the gang don't find out until near the end of the season, when Spike proves immune to some kind of magic Glory worked on the gang to make them forget that Glory and Ben are in the same body.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "INTOTHEWOODS" "Buffy.guide: Into The Woods"

@{b}Into The Woods@{ub}
5ABB10

"If you touched her, you know I'd kill you for real." - Riley

The Scoobies are at the hospital when Giles appears and asks Buffy and Riley if he can get them anything. Buffy can't stand the wait but Riley tries to convince her that it's a good sign - if they'd been quick it would mean they couldn't do much for her. A doctor approaches and tells them Joyce is in recovery and he managed to remove the whole tumor. Later, Xander and Anya mind Dawn while Buffy and Riley enjoy some alone time. Riley tells Buffy he's proud of how well she held together and Buffy says she's happier now her mum is out of the woods. Later, as they make love, Spike watches from outside the window, chain-smoking. When Buffy's asleep, Riley slips out and Spike follows him to a heavily-postbilled building and watches him walk in.

At the hospital, Buffy and Joyce have the most normal conversation they've had in a month or more. Joyce doesn't lapse into madness even once - everything is hunky-dory.  Later, the military finds a hot-spot of demon activity out of town and Grant suggests to his superior they get Riley in on the operation. That night, Buffy's in bed alone when Spike walks in and tells Buffy he has something show her, something she needs to see. After Buffy dresses, Spike takes her to the building Riley entered earlier and when they enter Buffy sees vampires feeding on people - but they're not fighting back. They've paid for it. Spike points Buffy upstairs where they find Riley, being fed on by a female vamp. Buffy and Riley's eyes meet and without waiting for an explanation, she leaves. As Riley tries to leave after her, the vamps stop him and beat him for bringing the Slayer to their pad. When he gets home, he realises Grant and another army soldier is there. They tell him about their operation in the rainforest and ask him to join them. They're heading for Central America at midnight tomorrow - it's up to him if he comes along.

It's nearly Christmas, and the gang prepare the Magic Box and bicker abut who's done the most work. Buffy comes in tells them all about the vampire feeding brothel, and Anya says it's been going on for centuries. The gang are confused by Buffy's urgent need to wipe out the nest but come along to back her up. They find the nest deserted and the gang get incresingly confused by Buffy's agitation. Riley goes to Spike's to get revenge over him for telling Buffy about his problem and stakes him with a plastic stake. Riley tells him to stay away from Buffy otherwise next time it'll be wooden. Spike tells him he sometimes thinks he got the better deal and he couldn't stand to Buffy as close to her as Riley is and not realy have her. Riley, more depressed than ever, shares Spike's alcohol, while Buffy trains tirelessly across town at the Magic Box. Riley comes over and asks the guys if he can be alone with Buffy. When he goes in to talk, Buffy won't let him touch her. He tries to explain why he started - he wanted to know why she'd been so enthralled by Angel and Dracula. The vampires made him feel wanted - Buffy doesn't do that to him. Buffy says he just can't handle the fact that she's stronger than him, and she's given him everything. But he doesn't believe her.

Riley tells Buffy about the military operation and that he'll leave tonight if they haven't sorted out their problems. Buffy's insensed that he's giving her a few hours to decide it. Riley says he's leaving unless she gives him a reason to stay. She says nothing and leaves. Walking through the streets engrossed in her own thoughts, it takes Buffy a while to realise she's being followed by a couple of vamps from the nest. All of a sudden she finds herself surrounded by seven vamps, but manages to slay them all effortlessly, except for the last one - the female she saw feeding on Riley that night. Buffy puts her makeshift stake (a large wooden spike) down and the vampire runs, thinking she's gotten away. Then Buffy, with spot-on accuracy, throws the stake straight at the vamp, running 60 yards away, and she's dust.

Xander appears and tries to get her to explain what's wrong. He can tell it's about Riley and Buffy tells her what he's been doing behind her back. Xander accuses her of treating Riley as a rebound guy - why else isn't she out there getting him to stay? He convinces her and she runs for the helipad. As she draws near, the helicopter rotors being to spin. He gets in and by the time Buffy finds them, they've taken off and can't hear her shouting for him over the noise of the engine. At home, Xander tells Anya how much he's in love with her, shaken from his talk with Buffy. Riley rides out in the helicopter as Buffy sits at home on the stairs, alone. It's over.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Giles' line, "The hazards of the underworld can become addictive to... some people," is a continuity reference to his own misguided experiments with black magic in @{"The Dark Age" LINK "THEDARKAGE"}.

Riley's gone. I personally will not miss him, and I'm not sure why, maybe cos he's just such a big jock beefcake. Joyce's luck at having her tumour completely removed lures Buffy into a false sense of security and sets us up for a shock to the system later on this season in @{"The Body" LINK "THEBODY"}.

