@endnode

@node "TRIANGLE" "Buffy.guide: Triangle"

@{b}Triangle@{ub}
5ABB11

"You do well to flee, townspeople! I will pillage your lands and dwellings, I will burn your crops, and make merry sport with your more attractive daughters!!" - Olaf the troll

Xander and Anya talk in bed about Riley's absence and Xander wonders aloud how Buffy's dealing with it. Of course, she's out patrolling, and when she saves a nun she asks her about becoming a sister! While Giles and Buffy spar, they talk about going to the Watcher's Council for help in finding out about Glory - all their other sources are tapped (Giles' collection of books) or missing (Riley). Anya is delighted to hear she'll be running the store for a week in Giles' absense and Tara says a trip to England sounds exotic (obviously never been here then). Giles is less than happy to be leaving the shop entirely in Anya's hands and Willow says she'll help out.

Back home, Buffy and Dawn look at Joyce, wearing her normal clothes for the first time since she became ill. She couldn't stand the frilly bathrobe anymore. In Buffy's room, Dawn notices Buffy has taken Riley's pictures down. Buffy is still, however, living in the hope that Riley comes back. In his crypt, Spike rehearses a speech to his Buffy mannequin telling her how much he cares about her. He ends up getting into a massive argument with the dummy, and after smashing it over the head with his box of chocolates, he picks her up, replaces the wig and tries again. At the Magic Box, Tara and Willow work on a simulated sunlight spell to kill vampires using the shop's stock and Anya says they shouldn't be using it without asking Giles. The tensions between Willow and Tara are worsened when Willow temporarily makes the cash-register disappear into thin air. The pair argue and Xander walks out, angry and unwilling to referee their arguments. Tara leaves too, leaving Willow to try her spell while Anya disrupts her. Partway through an incantation, the pair engage in an argument and Willow's words accidentally summon a Troll demon, who proceeds in trashing the shop, before leaving. Giles will not be pleased.

At college, Buffy and Tara talk about the new semester, and Riley being missing. Tara tells Buffy about the argument at the Magic Box and Buffy freaks out, scared that Xander and Anya are going to fall out and break up. Meanwhile, Willow and Anya pursue the Troll demon in Giles' car, following the mass of debris he's left in his wake. Willow finds it hard to find a reversal spell because her pages are blowing in the wind - when Anya takes a sharp corner they fly away. That's that plan out the window! (Sorry). Xander, still in his bad mood, comes across Spike, who asks how Buffy is, and if she's holding a grudge against him. Xander doesn't know what he's talking about. Buffy and Tara reach the Magic Box to find it deserted and wrecked, before heading straight out in pursuit of the demon. It's now evening, and the Troll demon is busy wrecking the entire town when he smells ale an heads to the Bronze, where Spike and Xander are sharing in their relationship woes. He picks up a large metal keg of beer and bites into it, drinking the contents in a few seconds, before demanding stronger ale from the barman, and babies to eat. Spike and Xander try to sit him down and get him some slightly more humane food but fail.

Anya and Willow arrive, followed shortly by Buffy and Tara. Spike says hello to Buffy but she ignores him, concentrating on where the demon has come from. Anya has Willow start her spell and the troll turns to Anya and complains that she's always spoiling his fun, just like when they were dating. The troll was Anya's first victim as a vengeance demon. He wants to kill Anya, then Xander points out that he seems to enjoy being a troll. But as the troll points out, he was imprisonned for centuries until Willow released him. And now, she can't reverse the spell for some reason, so Buffy and Spike fight the demon, Spike copping a feel of Buffy momentarily when the troll throws her on top of him. The troll begins knocking at the pillars that hold the Bronze's top platform up and it comes down, leaving the people on top hanging on for dear life. The troll gets away, and Buffy sends Xander to follow him while Willow and Anya head to the Magic Box to find a spell that will work. At the shop, they argue again. Willow thinks Anya will hurt Xander, while Anya accuses Willow of being possesive. The troll appears again, and throws them both over the counter into the display cases.

Xander arrives and tries to stop Olaf the troll but inevitably starts getting his arse kicked. Olaf, however, is impressed by Xander's persistance, and decides to reward him - he will kill just one of his women, and he may choose which one. Xander refuses to choose, and the Troll breaks his wrist. Xander still refuses, so the troll decides to kill Xander instead. Anya jumps forward and pleads with Olaf not to kill him. Buffy appears and as she fights the troll, Anya attempts to destract him so that Willow can take away his hammer using a spell. Without his hammer, Olaf is supposed to be powerless - but unfortunately, he's still a strong troll. When he tells Buffy that Anya and Xander will never last, she takes this as her cue to beat the hell out of him. She's adamant their love will last forever. The troll defeated, Willow sends him to an alternate universe.

Giles gets back after just three days away, empty-handed information-wise. Enjoying tea and biscuits with Joyce and Buffy, he tells them he's given them information about the key, but not that it's Dawn; still it's a worry. Giles has no idea what would happen if they figured out Dawn was the key. Dawn listens from the stairs outside the door, confused by what she's heard.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Xander and Anya's relationship seems very important to Buffy. They've been together for ages, they fight but never split, they appear made for each other and that's Buffy's great hope - her light at the end of the tunnel. Sarah often has trouble conveying emotion in scenes which are supposed to play funny. Her scene with Tara where she begins to cry about Anya and Xander's "miraculous love" is one example of this. Another memorable moment happens during @{"Real Me" LINK "REALME"} when Buffy laughs at Harmony's attempt to get a gang together... cringe-worthy.

Anya's complete cluelessness regarding human customs and values doesn't sit right when demons often pop up in both Buffy and Angel (and to co-exist, both shows must play by the same rules) who do understand the rules. Indeed, when she first became human, her first instinct was to find a date for the school dance - and it happened to be Xander she chose. It seems strange... maybe she's "selectively" human.

The last scene is a pivotal point in the Dawn story. She's already picked up that something wasn't right (mentally incapacitated people - including her own mother - have said she doesn't belong in this world) but she now realises that despite Buffy's assurances that she was a normal teenager, she isn't... and Giles, Joyce and Buffy know.

