@endnode

@node "CHECKPOINT" "Buffy.guide: Checkpoint"

@{b}Checkpoint@{ub}
5ABB12

"Ooooh, I like [Dawn], she's sassy! And I'll kill her. I'll kill your mum. I'll kill your friends. And I'll make you watch when I do." - Glory

Giles has summoned the gang over to Buffy's house with some news: the Watcher's Council may have some information on Glory and are on their way to California. Buffy doesn't want them around - she doesn't trust them. Joyce finds Dawn listening on the stairwell again and tells her to go to bed and get some sleep. Giles says they need all the help they can get - they're lost at the moment. Meanwhile, Glory brain-juices another victim - this time a mailman. Dreg reminds Glory that she hasn't much time to find the key, but she's sure Buffy knows where it is - and is confident she'll have it soon.

Quentin surprises Giles when he turns up at the Magic Box. His cronies search the premises somewhat rudely, criticising Giles for having potent magic ingredients on sale to the general public. They then close the store "for the duration of the Council's review". Giles is angry - he knew nothing of any "review". Quentin explains that if Giles and Buffy do not pass the review of their capabilities, they will not receive the vital information they need on Glory. Buffy isn't so much finding it hard to concentrate in her History lecture. She's not even trying, and mumbles something mid-way through the professor's speech without realising. To try and save her embarrasment she makes an argument about the professor's supposed facts, but he ridicules her in front of the whole class. Later, Buffy takes it out on an unfortunate vamp, but her gratification is denied by the sudden presense of Spike, who dusts the vamp for her. He upsets Buffy by pondering aloud the reasons her boyfriends leave her so predictably.

Ben's at work when Jinks, Glory's other servant, appears, asking for information on the Slayer, where her house is and who her friends are, but Ben refuses. When Buffy gets back to the Magic Box from her patrol to find the Watcher's Council members and Giles, her day couldn't get worse. They're going to be staying longer than Giles thought; reviewing Buffy, her training and methods, talking to her friends... Quentin refers to Buffy as an "instrument" and Giles snaps, but Buffy calms him down. Quentin threatens Giles with deportation if they don't have Buffy's full co-operation. Jinks informs Glory that Ben will not help her, and she wonders why Ben won't help, talk to Buffy, seduce her and "bang the key out of her".

Buffy and Giles consider aloud punching Quentin but decide against it. Buffy's more worried about her knowledge than her physical fitness - she's sure she'll fail the review. The Council suits question the Scooby Gang. Xander's Zeppo complex is brought up again when he's asked if he has any special skills whatsoever and has to answer no. Spike is also questioned, and he seems to want to hinder Buffy's progress despite his apparent affection for her. Buffy goes through her physical review and finds to her horror that she in expected to know the Japanese terms for various attacks and moves, and Giles attempts to translate as Quentin calls out his commands. Buffy decides it's time to do things her way and nearly kills one of the Coucil members - his life saved by Xander's straw-filled dummy. Quentin has seen enough and gives Giles and Buffy a few hours to prepare for the mental review.

When Buffy gets home she finds Glory in her house, asking for the key, but Buffy denies any knowledge of where it is. Dawn attempts to sneak out of the house when Glory calls her in and asks if she has any idea where the key is. Unable to get any information out of either sister, Glory leaves, promising someone will die next time they meet. Joyce comes through asking who was here, and Buffy simply tells her to get packing.

Buffy takes Joyce and Dawn to Spike's place for safekeeping. Spike obliges, hoping it will raise his favour with Buffy. Joyce and Spike hit it off, talking about a soap-opera called Passions. It's 7.20pm and Buffy's already late for the meeting with the Council when she's surrounded by three armed, chain-mailed warriors. She fights valiantly, knocks all out but one, who she pins down and unmasks - he's human. He claims to be part of a vast army, the Knights of Byzantium, sworn enemies of the Slayer. He says more will follow as long as she protects the key, until they destroy Buffy and the key. She takes his sword and lets him go, rather than take a human life.

Buffy finally arrives at the Magic Box and tells Quentin there will be no review. She knows why the Council has come all this way to hassle them. They are afraid of Buffy's power. She has power over the Council, and power over Glory. She needs the key and Buffy has it - therefore Buffy has the power. When one Council member interrupts, he has another narrow miss with a sword while the Scooby Gang watch, admiring Buffy from upstairs. Buffy calls the shots: Quentin will tell them everything they know, and everything else they learn. The Magic Box will stay open. Giles will be re-instated as Buffy's watcher, at full salary, retro-actively from the month he was fired. Quentin tells Buffy her terms are acceptable and Giles is about to crack out the Scotch when Buffy tells him to wait. She wants to know right now what kind of demon Glory is. "Well that's the thing, you see," Quentin sighs. "Glory isn't a demon. She's a God."

@{b}Notes@{ub}

As always, the sight of Quentin along with six others from the Council is ridiculous - do they all get a wage? It would appear that yes they do. And judging by the suits, not exactly minimum wage if you catch my drift. Or maybe that's the costume department trying to make them all look "British" :O)

Spike has a brilliant moment in here which reminds me of the Hannibal Lecter / Clarice Starling scenes in 'Silence Of The Lambs'. A female member of the Council questions Spike and admits she wrote her thesis on him. There's a mixture of fascination and dread in the woman, while Spike talks very calmly in much the same manner that Lecter did.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "BLOODTIES" "Buffy.guide: Blood Ties"

@{b}Blood Ties@{ub}
5ABB13

"It's blood. It's Summers blood... It doesn't matter where you came from or how you got here. You are my sister." - Buffy

Buffy's nearly twenty but despite Willow's protests she doesn't want a party, insisting the group stay focused on their fight against Glory. It still hasn't quite sunk in that they're up against a real God. As the Scooby Gang sit around the table at the Magic Box, Giles says that according to the Council's research, Glory and her cohorts ruled over "one of the more seriously unpleasant" demon dimensions, and Glory has found a way into their reality, her power only slightly stunted by her current human form. He goes on to explain that existing in this reality is a strain on her mental state and she must feed off "that which makes the human mind a cohesive whole" - which is the "brain-sucking" we've already witnessed. The guys ask about the key and Buffy tells them she and Giles know where it is, but they're upset that they didn't tell the rest of them. Unable to satisfy the gang with her excuses, Buffy realises she must come clean about Dawn.

The Knights of Byzantium are chanting when Glory's minions approach and start a fight. They're easily beaten - but just as a Knight is about to finish off Dreg with his sword, Glory catches it by the blade and then casually knocks him fifteen metres away. While he tries to reach for his sword again, Glory beats the other two and snatches the sword out of his reach. "Hey, nice sword... bet it hurts!" Next day, Tara and Willow are outside the Magic Box performing an early-warning incantation which should tell them if and when Glory approaches them. Dawn asks if she can help but Willow says Buffy wouldn't approve and Dawn goes inside. Inside, Xander and Anya try too hard to act normal - a sure way to act weird if ever there was one. Buffy's fear that the gang would act strange around her was apparently not unfounded. Dawn finds Buffy with Giles, and Buffy asks her how school was. Dawn says she has a homework task to write a letter to her future self, and notices as Giles pointedly slips his notes out of her reach.

Meanwhile, Glory tortures the now-captive Knight of Byzantium but he won't tell her where the key is, and claims he doesn't know himself, so Glory brainsucks him. At Buffy's party, Willow and Tara give her a frilly top and Dawn gives her a picture of the two of them in a home-made frame with seashells on it. Later, Buffy, Giles and Joyce are talking about Dawn as she listens from outside, but Buffy reailses she's there before anyone says anything they shouldn't. Dawn has picked up on how weird everyone has been acting and accuses everyone of talking about her. Anya says she and Xander were actually talking about sex, and begins to go into detail when Buffy tells her to stop. Dawn storms upstairs.

A little while later, Dawn climbs out of the window to run away, and doesn't get very far before Spike makes her jump. He's standing outside the house with the chocolates for Buffy in his hand, and Dawn notices the box is all battered from Spike's earlier temper-tantrum. She tells him she's going to break into the Magic Box to steal things, and invites him along. Spike does the breaking in, and Dawn finds the notes Giles hid from her, in a hidden drawer. Dawn reads his notes, occasionally asking Spike for clarification. Giles' notes say that only those "outside reality" can see the key's true nature. Dawn asks Spike what this means, and he says it could be anyone with second-sight, or mental patients. Dawn, of course, remembers several incidents where madmen have pointed her out and said she doesn't belong. She's beginning to realise, and Spike continues reading, the notes confirming for Dawn that she is the key.

Buffy, Tara and Willow discuss the lack of so much as a card from Riley. As they chat, Tara suddenly looks over Buffy's shoulder... Dawn is standing at the doorway, with a large knife in one hand, her other arm cut up pretty badly. "Is this blood?" she asks. If she can bleed, she can't be a key or a thing. "Am I real? Am I anything?!" The party's over, and the guys leave, each offering their help as they do. Buffy says she and her mum can deal with it. They talk to Dawn and try to convince her that they love her regardless but Dawn screams at them to get out. At the Magic Box, next morning, Buffy says the group's focus should be on the key and what it's for, why it was created. Giles wonders aloud how Dawn got in, then Anya finds cigarette ash in one of their artefacts - for Buffy this spells Spike.

Buffy arrives at Spikes and he's angry that Buffy blames so much of it on him, and tells her she should have been more honest with Dawn in the first place. At Buffy's, Joyce tells Dawn she'll be late for school. Dawn won't go but when Joyce tries to cheer her up with some soup, she decides she'd rather be anywhere else and goes. At the hospital, Ben finds the Byzantium knight on the mental ward. Dreg appears and tries again to threaten him but Ben knows Glory can't touch him. Later, Dawn reads through her diaries when she hears voices downstairs. It's Joyce telling Buffy that Dawn's been suspended for shouting at a teacher. Dawn hears Buffy reasoning that Dawn thinks she can do anything now. She's not real. Dawn takes it the wrong way and goes into her room, and starts trashing, tearing her posters down and ripping the pages out of her diaries.

Oblivious to the noise upstairs, Buffy and Joyce are arguing: Joyce says they should be there for her, as her family, but Buffy says Dawn needs space, and answers about where she comes from. Suddenly the smoke alarm sounds, Buffy and Joyce run upstairs and find Dawn's stuff burning in her bin and the window open. She's gone. Buffy soon has the entire Scooby gang looking for her. She and Spike go together and Buffy tells Spike she blames herself for not telling her sooner, but Spike says Dawn would have done something like this anyway - she's 14. Dawn finds her way to the hospital's mental ward and asks the patients what she is and where she came from, but gets no sense out of them. She runs out and Ben finds her, and gets her some hot chocolate. When Dawn begins to confide in him, he realises she's the key and freaks, telling her to get away fast. Dawn doesn't move and suddenly Ben morphs into Glory. They apparently share the same body.

Glory tries to get Dawm to tell her what she was talking to Ben about - she doesn't see everything Ben does. A security guard walks in and tells Glory she shouldn't be here, and she snaps his neck without a second thought before deciding they should go somewhere more private to talk. In another hospital room, she asks Dawn where the key is and Dawn says she might know, if Glory tells her more about it. The Scooby Gang check the hospital and a janitor passes them, telling a guard there's a guy in the locker room with his head twisted almost clean off. As Dawn interrogates Glory, Glory realises Dawn is just trying to get information out of her. She's losing her mind and needs to brain-suck soon, and turns to Dawn... Then Buffy comes through the door. There will be no Dawn-sucking today. Dawn skedaddles and Buffy attacks Glory, managing to get a few punches in at Glory before she counters. The Spike holds Glory and Buffy hots her again, but Glory uses a free leg to kick Buffy away, then headbutts Spike and throws him across the room, unconscious.

Xander sneaks round armed with a crow-bar, while Tara and Willow work on an incantation. Giles takes an oppurtunity to fire an arrow at Glory but it simply bounces away. Xander gives Glory a blow to the head but she shrugs it off and throws him across the room. She throws the crowbar straight at Dawn and Buffy dives to stop it in mid-air, wounding herself but saving Dawn. Then Willow and Tara complete their spell and Glory disappears - teleported a good few hundred feet above town, she falls to Earth with a bump. Buffy asks Dawn if she's okay, and Dawn asks why she cares. Buffy puts her hand on her crow-bar inflicted wound, then holds Dawn's own bloodied hand with it. They share their blood, it's Summers blood. Buffy doesn't care where Dawn came from, they are sisters. They hug, and it looks like there is hope in this hopeless situation.

Dawn remebers Ben had been there, but can't remember when he left; it seems that along with the transformation, Glory performed some sort of memory alteration so that Dawn would not realise she and Ben share the same body. Hand in hand, the two sisters walk home.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Michelle Trachtenberg (Dawn)'s anguished performance is great. Particularly effective is her scream to Buffy and Joyce to get out of the room. I think I'd make a shit actor, myself. I just couldn't fake a scream like that.

What makes Glory a God? Did she create something? It's pretty ironic to hear Dreg make his smart-ass remark "You really think he'll help you now?" in answer to the Knights' "Such is the will of God" chant... which seems to suggest that there are Gods, and then there is God. Goddamnit! I'm confused also. Also, should we trust Ben? He appears to be protecting Buffy and Dawn but there does appear to be something shifty about him all the same.

Anya's blunt, outspoken nature again leads to funny more moments, for example when she gleefully announces to the group that she wishes Buffy's presents were hers. I still don't think she could possibly be that stupid, but still, it's funny. Also, check out how quickly Buffy opens Dawn's present - uncanny!

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "CRUSH" "Buffy.guide: Crush"

@{b}Crush@{ub}
5ABB14

"I'm gonna stake you so much with the Slaying powers that I have because I'm the Chosen One!!" - Harmony.

At the Bronze Spike sees Buffy siting alone while her friends dance - Willow with Tara and Xander with Anya - and decides to join her and make conversation. Buffy snubs him and Spike tells her to suit herself, but that he thought his recent good deeds would have earned him some respect and consideration. Then Xander comes and kicks him out of the chair and when Spike has gone, realises he's taken his money. Buffy spies Ben from across the room and goes over to thank him for trying to help Dawn. Spike sees from across the room, thinks she's chatting him up, and feels a twinge of jealousy.

A train stops at Sunnydale's station, and when no-one steps off despite the fact that this is the last stop, the railman on the platform steps on to investigate. The entire carriage has been attacked by vampires - a real feast - and when he tries to run, he becomes dessert. Buffy gets home from the Bronze and relieves Giles of his duties - he's been watching over Joyce and Dawn in her absence. As Giles leaves, he tells Buffy she should act as normal as possible with Dawn rather than going so easy on her. Buffy takes this as a license to interrogate Dawn on her latest wrong-doing: borrowing one of Buffy's sweaters. Meanwhile, Harmony tries to tempt Spike into bed but his mind is on Buffy - in fact he only agrees to have sex if they do a little roll-play with Harmony dressed up as the Slayer.

At college the next day, Willow and Tara discuss the Hunchback of Notre Dame. Buffy didn't read it, but she rented the film. She sees a student reading the local paper, the front page of which details the massacre at the railway - it looks like vampires to her. Spike crawls into his crypt from an underground tunnel to find Dawn watching him. She wants to hang out with him because he talks to her like a peer rather than a child like everyone else, but Spike disapproves, not wanting to get on the wrong side of Buffy. But they get talking, and soon Buffy and Joyce are wondering where Dawn is. Buffy goes to look, and it's late evening by the time she finds them, Spike telling Dawn creepy vampire stories, in the crypt. Spike tells Buffy he was just about to send her home and apologises for causing her to worry. Buffy and Dawn walk home and Buffy realises Dawn has a crush on Spike. Dawn says she can't help it, but it doesn't matter anyway since Spike wants Buffy. Buffy looks at Dawn, confused. She obviously hadn't picked up on it.

Buffy and Xander check out the train carriage and Buffy tells him about Spike's alleged feelings for her. He asks how she knows this, and Buffy says Dawn found out while hanging out at his crypt, and she thinks Dawn has a crush on him. Xander's shocked - he's always been Dawn's crush. They leave the train, having missed an item left in the luggage space - a doll, presumably belonging to Drusilla. Buffy gets home that evening to find Joyce and Dawn entertaining Spike, who's over supposedly to appologise for last night. He takes her aside and says he has some information on two vampires responsible for the train massacre. They drive down to the warehouse where the vamps have been hiding and wait in the car - Buffy's jumpy and freaks out when he reaches across into the glove compartment for his bourbon. They see the vamps go in and follow after them. Buffy looks around at the room and realises the vamps have been living here some time - whoever's responsible for the train only got into town that night.

Buffy asks him why he brought her down here and he admits he has feelings for her. Buffy stops him when he's about to say he loves her and runs off, making it clear she isn't interested in him. Spike's walks home, bummed out, and when he gets there he senses someone else in the room. It's Drusilla, and she says she's come to make everything right again. She's working on making Angel evil again, and wants the three of them to reband, and be a gang like old times. Spike makes an excuse that he doesn't want to go to L.A. but Dru has already heard about his chip. She tells him the pain in his head is a lie, he's still a killer. Harmony appears and begins slagging off Dru for hurting her "booboo". Spike grabs her and throws her across the room, saying it's over. Not because Dru is back: But because Spike is back.

At Buffy's house, Willow and Joyce listen to Buffy as she recounts her conversation with Spike. Joyce and Willow are worried that Spike could become a danger to them if he thinks there's even the slightest chance of them ever being together. At the Broonze, Spike and Dru dance together and spot a couple making out passionately up on the high tier. They walk up and Dru snaps the girl's neck and passes her to Spike. Then she snaps the guy's neck and feeds. Spike hesitates, but when he sees Dru drinking, it doesn't take long before he does too. Meanwhile, Buffy has decided to go and talk to Spike, just to clear the air, and asks Willow to do something while she's gone. She arrives at Spike's and jumps down into his "basement", where she finds a collection of photographs and pictures of her, along with the doll Spike has been dressing up as her. Just as Buffy realises the scale of Spike's obsession, he appears. Buffy sees blood on his lips and asks him what happened. She's come unprepared for a fight and steps back. Dru appears from behind her and jabs her with a cattle-prod. Buffy falls to the floor and Dru prods her again, knocking her out.

Dru wants to tie Buffy up and torture her but Spike says he's through playing. Then Dru hands him the cattle-prod, but instead of prodding Buffy, he prods Dru. When Buffy and Dru come round, they're both tied up. Spike says he's going to prove his love to Buffy but Buffy says he couldn't possibly love without a soul. Drusilla argues that it is entirely possible for a vampire to love. Spike says he's going to kill Drusilla for her, if she admits she feels something for him. If not, he'll untie Drusilla and let her killl Buffy. Buffy tells him the only chance he had with her was when she was unconscious. Spike is livid and decides maybe he should kill the both of them and end his torture. Just then Harmony shoots him in the back with an arrow. She says she's sick of being treated like a dog by him. She turns her back and Spike jumps at her. They fight and Dru and Buffy start trying to free themselves. Dru's free first, having only been tied up with rope, and she fights with Buffy, who's still chained up. When Drusilla's about to snap Buffy's neck, Spike comes over and saves her, throwing Dru to the ground.

Dru and Harmony leave, fed up with Spike, followed by Buffy, who gets a punch in first. Spike follows her home, and Buffy tells him she wants him to stay away from her and her friends and family. Spike tries to follow her into the house and realises Buffy has had a protection spell put on the house against Spike.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

There's a couple of those moments of Buffy genius here. For example, we have Harmony's Buffy impression which really is beyond belief. Then there's the visual-only gag on the train carriage when Buffy sits on one of the seats, in the exact same pose of the person who died there, now outined in white tape. Speaking of that same scene, just how likely is it that the police would have missed Drusilla's doll despite obviously spending hours cleaning the carriage up, taking fingerprints and removing the bodies? I know cops can be pretty stupid but that's über-stupid.

There's also Spike's line "I've done the whole LA scene, Dru... it didn't agree with me", which is prime Buffy humour and also a reminder of one of the vampire "perks": as long as you avoid Buffy, you've got enough time to see the whole world if you want to.

The Ramones song Spike sings is 'I Wanna Be Sedated' from their album 'Road To Ruin' (Sire). It's also on their 'Anthology' CD, which of course you should buy, or at least steal :O)

