@endnode

@node "IWASMADETOLOVEYOU" "Buffy.guide: I Was Made To Love You"

@{b}I Was Made To Love You@{ub}
5ABB15

"I'm alive. I can tell because of the pain!" - Xander.

Buffy takes her frustrations about Spike on a punchbag. She says she feels dirty, somehow responsible for what he feels. Giles suggests Buffy calms down. "Me too," groans Xander - it turns out the punchbag is actually Xander in industrial-strength padding. She appologises and leans him against the wall to rest since he can't sit down. She says that for once she'd like someone normal to like her. Maybe she could Slay less, and spend more time laughing at her hypothetical new guy's jokes. Xander says all he'd have to do is see her heart and he'd fall in love with her. The needy Buff hugs him, touched beyond words. Meanwhile in town, a car pulls up the curb and a curiously-mannered girl in a pink dress gets out. She thanks the man in the car for the ride, and he expresses concern at letting her out in such a dangerous place, asking what she's looking for in Sunnydale. She tells him she's looking for true love.

Buffy and Dawn are helping Joyce decide what to wear for her date with a "nice, normal guy" called Brian. Joyce is nervous and asks Buffy for advice, but she says she's not qualified to give that kind of advice - both of her boyfriends to date have left town. Joyce assures her she's just had some bad luck, before asking what time it is yet again. Meanwhile, Anya is telling Tara about how she trippled her money with online trading. They come across the girl in the pink dress, who asks where Warren is. Tara and Anya say they don't know a Warren, and she thanks them anyway and moves on to the next person she meets. At the Spring Dance, Buffy and Xander have a dance together. When the song's over, they break off, and Buffy notices Ben, but pretends not to and stands nearby to see if he says anything. He says hi, and asks if she's having fun. Buffy asks him to dance and he says sure, and goes to put his glass down first, promising he'll be right back.

The girl in pink walks in and starts calling out for Warren, who's here and grabs his girlfriend and tells her they've got to leave quickly. The Scoobies have noticed that the girl in pink talks funny and are confused that she's been looking for Warren all day and still hasn't found him. Spike approaches Buffy while she waits for Ben, and she tells him to leave. Ben gets back to Buffy and he gives her his number. Spike finds April, the girl in the pink dress, and hits on her. Unimpressed, she pinks him up and throws him through a window. Buffy goes to talk to April, but she won't stop looking for Warren and pushes Buffy out of her way. Later, the gang agree that April appears to be a robot. Xander suggests Warren is the person who built her, and Willow says she should be able to track down someone with such an unusual name. Buffy gets back to relieve Giles of his Dawn-watching duties and he says there's only so much he can take - Dawn's had him eating cookie-dough and talking boys. Just then, Joyce gets home and it seems her date with Brian went well...

3.30am, and April is still looking for Warren, knocking on people's doors to ask for him. In the morning, Willow finds Warren Meers on the net along with a home address for his parents. Tara says it's sad that Warren couldn't find someone and it strikes a chord with Buffy, who calls Ben and arranges to meet for coffee. Warren and his girlfriend Katrina are about to hurry out of the door when they find Buffy standing in the way. Katrina demands to know what's going on with all these girls and Warren tells her to shut up. She walks off. Spike appears at the Magic Shop to a predictably cold reception, and Giles tells him to "move the hell on". Warren tells Buffy about the reasons he built April, not as a sex-toy but as a girlfriend. She was built to love him, but it backfired - he thought he would love her but he couldn't, the whole thing was too easy and predictable and so he left her in his dorm room, hoping her batteries would run out. They should have by now... but they haven't.

April finds Katrina and asks her where Warren is, and Katrina tells her to keep away from her boyfriend. April grabs Katrina and begins to suffocate her, teling her to stop lying. Meanwhile, Spike puts all of his Buffy "memorabilia" in a box, saying "too right I'll move on." Buffy and Warren find April holding Katrina by the neck, saying she's "gone to sleep". Buffy takes Katrina and finds to their relief that she's alive. Buffy tells Warren he should tell April the truth and so he breaks up with her. April's Combat Mode is suddenly enabled, and she flings Buffy into the air. Then she breaks off part of a see-saw to hit Bufffy with but Buffy takes it from her and smashes it into her torso, revelaing her robot guts. Katrina freaks about Warren's ex-girlfriend being a robot and runs off. April gets Buffy by the neck and is about to strangle her when the batteries finally begin to die. Confused by her sudden lack of strength, April calls out for Warren.

Buffy sits April on a swing and April tells Buffy she did everything she should have done but apparently it wasn't enough. Buffy assures her he never meant to hurt her, and tells her he'll come back for her. The last sentence April manages is "When life gives you lemons, make lemonade". Her batteries finally die and engrossed by her own feelings of lost love, Buffy doesn't move from the spot. Later, she talks with Xander and comes to the realisation that she needn't be with anyone, she can be alone for now if she likes. She calls Ben and leaves a message on his answerphone, saying now isn't the best time for her to see someone. At the other end, Glory listens and comes to the conclusion that Ben has been working against her by helping Buffy. Spike pays a visit to Warren's and his mother lets him in. Spike's placing an order - he wants a robot made in the image of Buffy, and hands Warren his box of photos and sketches.

Buffy gets home and finds flowers from Brian for Joyce in the hallway. She walks to the bottom of the stairwell and calls for her mum. Then she turns around and sees her mum on the sofa, in the living room. "What are you doing?" Buffy asks. Joyce doesn't respond. "Mum? ... Mummy?"

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Xander and Buffy's hugging scene at the beginning is a slightly-overdue insight into Xander and Buffy's complex relationship. Their friendship is never as obvious as Buffy's with Willow, or indeed Xander's with Willow, but it does seem just as important to both of them, as this tender moment shows. Xander's comment that the Hellmouth "seems a pretty terrible place to try to build anything" boils the show right down to its essence; love stories in a world of chaos.

Anthony Stewart Head has the ability to convey a tremendous sense of menace when the occasion demands, and his confrontation with Spike in this episode is frighteningly intense. We see a constant flurry of kicks and punches in Buffy, but here Giles' simple shove, along with his words ("move the hell on") works on a more human level to much greater effect. Part of the scene's power lies in audience empathy for Spike. It's one of those moments, like getting found out, where your stomach sinks.

The final scene where Buffy discovers Joyce uses excruciating dramatic irony - when she calls upstairs we can see a body on the sofa behind Buffy, but for a minute Buffy doesn't notice. Absolutely shudder-worthy.

