@endnode

@node "THEBODY" "Buffy.guide: The Body"

@{b}The Body@{ub}
5ABB16

"We're not supposed to move the body!" - Buffy.

Last Christmas - Buffy, Dawn, Joyce, Xander, Anya, Willow, Tara and Giles are enjoying Christmas dinner. Anya informs the gang that Santa does in fact exists - although he doesn't bring presents so much as disembowell children. In the kitchen, Giles opens anothr bottle of wine and Joyce complains about her oven - she's burnt a pie. Buffy goes to cut off the burnt part, but is too close to the edge of the work-top and the whole thing heads for the floor.

Present - Buffy runs over to Joyce's body and shakes her, screaming at her, but gets no response. She runs for the phone and dials 911. The woman on the other end asks for Buffy's address to send an ambulance over. Buffy barely manages to get the words out because she's so shaken. The operator asks Buffy if she knows how to start C.P.R. and in her shock, Buffy's mind is blank. She gives her instructions down the phone, which refreshes Buffy's memory and she puts down the phone. She pushes back Joyce's head and blows down her mouth, then massages her heart. She repeats this, but the second time something cracks and Buffy picks up the phone and tells the operator, who says it isn't important and the ambulance will be there soon. Buffy says Joyce is cold and asks if she should warm her up but the operator simply says that if Joyce isn't responding to CPR, the best thing is to await the paramedics. Buffy says she has to make a call and hangs up.

Buffy stares at the handset for a few seconds before speed-dialing Giles' number. He answers and Buffy says "Giles, you have to come. She's at the house," before hanging up. The paramedics arrive and Buffy realises that in moving Joyce to clear her airway, she hitched her skirt up. Buffy pulls it back down to preserve her dignity before the paramedics enter the room. The paramedics move Joyce to the floor and ask Buffy a few questions about when she found Joyce, which she manages to answer. Their resuscitation works and Joyce coughs, and they take her to the hospital where she's given a clean bill of health. Except she isn't. One paramedic turns to the other, knowing that continuing would be pointless. "She's cold, man... Call it." He gets to his feet and tells Buffy her mother is dead, she died a "good while" before Buffy found her, and tries to reassure her by telling her Joyce probably felt very little pain. He says the coroner's office will pick up the body to determine the cause of death conclusively. The parameics leave, telling Buffy to sit and have a drink of water, not to disturb the body, and that they are sorry for her loss. Buffy calls "good luck" at them as they leave for another emergency.

Buffy walks into the hallway and throws up, before opening the back door and looking out. She can hear children playing. She takes some kitchen roll from the kitchen to clean up her mess and then Giles arrives. He's assumed Glory has paid them a visit and is confused when Buffy says the coroner is coming. Then he notices Joyce in the living room and rushes to her. Buffy shouts at him, telling him they're not supposed to move "the body". Realising how she's just referred to her own mother, she freaks out again and Giles tries to comfort her with a hug but it seems not to register. The coroner arrives and bags Joyce up. Dawn cries in the toilet at school having been called "freaky" in front of everyone and a friend tries to comfort her. They're going to be late for a lesson if they don't hurry, so Dawn dries her eyes and then venture out into the corridoor. At their art class, Dawn's next to Kevin, who says he heard about her cutting herself. She begins to deny it but he tells her he understands that feeling, of wanting to do something extreme.

Buffy walks into the classroom, but Dawn doesn't see her until she right alongside her. Buffy takes her outside and as they walk Dawn asks where Mum is. Buffy says she has some bad news, and something went wrong with the tumour. Dawn asks if she's ok as Kevin and some other of Dawn's classmates watch through the glass, unable to hear what Buffy is saying. They watch as Dawn begins to sob and falls to the floor. Tara and Willow wait for Xaander and Anya to arrive in his car, none of them speaking until Tara sees them arrive and tells Willow. Willow can't decide what to wear - her clothes seem either too sombre or too childish and she can't find a particular blue top which Joyce really liked. Tara tries her best to calm Willow down, but to little avail. Anya asks Xander what will happen but he's not sure either. They meet with Willow and Tara and Xander hugs Willow, before they fall into an uncomfortable silence. Anya asks again what's going to happen and Willow says she supposes they'll all meet at the morgue. Tara says Giles is accompanying Joyce's body there, while Buffy goes to school to tell Dawn. Willow decides she has to change again, while Xander tries to find someone to blame.

Anya unintentionally upsets everyone by asking if they're going to see the body. Then Tara says they will have to take over patrolling. Willow wants to change again, and Tara goes to check if Willow's blue top is in the laundry room. Anya asks if the body will be cut open, and Willow tells her to shut her mouth. Anya can't understand why she isn't allowed to ask these questions, or why Joyce can't just get back in her body and not be dead. Anya breaks down and Willow and Xander realise she's in pain too. Anya sits in a chair in the corner of the room and finds a blue sweater, which she puts in the dresser drawers. Willow doesn't notice. Xander paces up and down for a minute before punching his hand straight through the wall, and they're still pulling it out when Tara gets back. She tells Willow she couldn't find the top, but Willow says it doesn't matter. They decide they should set off now to be there for Buffy... after Willow's changed again. Outside, Xander's double-parked car earns him a ticket.

At the morgue, the doctor confirms that Joyce died of an aneurysm near where the tumour was removed. Giles tells Buffy he'll handle as much of the paperwork as he can. Dawn heads to the bathroom and Willow says they should get some food - Willow, Xander and Anya go, leaving Buffy and Tara alone together for a while. Tara tells Buffy her own mother died when she was 17. Dawn comes out of the bathroom but instead of going back to the guys, she heads for the pathology room. Locking the door behind her, she finds her mum, who's covered up, and contemplates taking a look before she realises one of the bodies in the room has risen - he's a vampire. Buffy goes to look for Dawn and finds her struggling against the vamp. She busts the door open and forces him off her. While they fight, Joyce becomes uncovered and after Buffy snaps the vamp's neck, Dawn goes over to look, and asks if Joyce is cold. Buffy says it's not Joyce. She's gone. Dawn asks where, and puts out her hand as if to touch Joyce's face...

@{b}Notes@{ub}

This is painful to watch. No matter which characters you relate to most in the show, you can't escape the emotional impact of this episode because every major character is affected by Joyce's passing. Even Spike, as we find out in the next episode @{"Forever" LINK "FOREVER"}, has been upset by Joyce's passing. It's the biggest upheaval so far in Buffy history... and interestingly, it's a natural rather than supernatural one. What else can I say? Joyce held Buffy and Dawn's lives together, was Giles' on-the-sly love interest, and coped extremely well, I think, with the knowledge that Buffy kills vampires. Her strangely sarcastic nagging-mum humour will be remembered by all.

Anya's part in this episode must have been a major consideration. On the one hand, her complete lack of tact could have threatened to alienate her entirely from the gang; on the other, it would have been out of character for her to suddenly be all sensitivity and consideration. What we get is a compromise on the two - it's Anya, so she doesn't feel the need to restrict herself in her quest for knowledge and asks some pretty taboo questions. To compensate, her breakdown makes us realise she's only asking because she's confused.

@{b}Notes on cameras, cutting, editing, sound and other depressing stuff@{ub}

This is really the season where the production team started to play with the shooting methods. This episode obviously has to be a high-impact episode and benefits in this respect from the heightened sense of reality that handheld camera shots promote. Also, when a character walks around dazed, as Buffy is when she leaves the room to call an ambulance, the movement of the camera can be used to convey that as much or as little as the director wishes - so here, as well as up-and-down style shakiness, we get a side-to-side movement that makes us feel a little sea-sick and nauseous. Also, at some points Sarah is too close to the camera or out of focus - occasionally the action happens out of frame. Handheld camera is generally used by indie film-makers who're on a tight budget - see the likes of the Blair Witch Project - but it's a liberating device to use - there's no longer the need to worry about perfect shots.

The freak-out atmosphere is even further enhanced by Buffy's P.O.V. shots. For example, the telephone receiver before she calls Giles - under an insane amount of stress, the only reason Buffy is able to actually call him is presumably because she's called him hundreds of times before and has his number on speed-dial. When the paramedic informs Buffy that Joyce is dead, there are numerous, quick close-up shots of him and his uniform, badge, etc. Buffy also stares at her vomit soaked tissue until Giles arrives and she snaps out of it. It's very much like a David Lynch movie - it makes very real, normal things seem the stuff of nightmares... which is what death is, after all.

Soundtrack-wise, the general lack of incidental music is a smart move. What little sound there is, is incredibly focussed: all background sound is eliminated and the sounds - for example, the zip on Joyce's body-bag and the scissors uring her examination at the morgue - are given real texture and meaning. This minimalistic approach makes the vampire fight at the end seem very claustrophobic, every breath and every squeak of rubber-soled sneaker against the tiled floor reverberating around the room, but somehow giving the impression of isolation.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "FOREVER" "Buffy.guide: Forever"

@{b}Forever@{ub}
5ABB17

"Well, what do you know! Bitty Buffy!" - Spike

Giles takes Dawn and Buffy to choose a coffin for Joyce. Buffy chooses a particular coffin and Dawn says, what if mum wants a different one. As her final resting place, it should be one she likes, but how can they be sure? Buffy decides it wasn't a good idea to bring Dawn along but she insists she's okay. Over dinner, Buffy discusses flowers and the fact that Joyce didn't want a wake, with Giles. Dawn feels left out of the proceedings and hadn't been aware of Joyce's wishes should she die. The phone rings and Buffy hopes it's her dad - he still hasn't called. Dawn says she doesn't want to be at home after the service tomorrow and asks if she can go to Willow's instead. When Willow and Xaner leave, they find Spike coming with flowers. Xander thinks Spike's trying to score points with Buffy and tells him to get lost; Spike throws the flowers on the floor and takes off. Willow picks up the flowers and points out to Xander that Spike didn't leave a card with the flowers.

After the service, Dawn goes home with Willow and Tara, while Buffy stands by her mother's grave until it's past sunset. A shadow appears from behind her and the figure apologises for not being able to get here sooner. It's Angel. Tara and Willow are having a hard time comforting Dawn, and tell her they can do anything she likes. Dawn's pleased to hear this because she alreay has something in mind - she wants to do a spell to bring Joyce back. Meanwhile, Anya tells Xander that Joyce's death has made her realise that they're all a part of something bigger - the cycle of life and death, and its meaning. Tara and Willow tell Dawn that witches can't mess with the natural order of things but Dawn says that as witches, that's all they do. But life and death is different, the two Wiccans reason - and it's dangerous. Dawn sulks and lays on her sleeping bag.

Buffy tells Angel how worried she is about the coming days - up until now she's had things to do regarding Joyce's funeral, but now it's over she can't see how she's supposed to resume normal life. Angel tells her she is strong, and even if she doesn't feel like it now, she will make it through. He tells her he'll stay in town as long as she likes. Buffy suggests forever and they kiss. The sun's coming up soon and he'll have to leave, but they still have a few minutes left.  Jinks approaches Ben outside the hospital and tells him of Glory's approval of Ben's interest in the Slayer. She hopes it will lead to more information about the key. Ben says he wouldn't share that information with Glory, and nearly says he wouldn't do that to an innocent girl... in fact, the word "innocent" rolls off his tongue before he can stop it and Jinks realises Ben is talking about a person. Ben realises the only way to keep Jinks quiet is to kill him, so he takes his knife and stabs him with it.

Willow and Tara tell Dawn they're going to get breakfast before their first class of the day and she says she wants to sleep some more. Willow says she'll call on her at lunchtime and as she leaves, she uses her telekinetic powers to stick out one of the books in the bookcase. When the coast is clear Dawn checks out the book and finds a section on resurrection. At the Magic Box, under the guise of helping out, Dawn looks around for further information and ingredients. Giles tells her the most dangerous books are off the floor, and as soon as she's alone for a second, she goes up the stairs and finds what she's after, managing to avoid Giles on her way back down. After nightfall, she attempts the spell at Joyce's grave. Spike finds her and realises that she's trying to raise Joyce. Dawn asks him not to tell anyone and he says he won't - he's going to help her, and tells her not to tell Buffy. Dawn asks why he's helping if he doesn't want credit he says he doesn't like to see Buffy and Dawn suffering. Meanwhile, Giles sits alone at home, drinking and listening to his old LPs.

Two of Glory's minions bring Jinks to her - he's still alive (barely) and informs Glory that the key is in human form. Spike takes Dawn to the house of a creepy old guy he's heard about, and the old man advises them strongly against attempting a resurrection. He takes a strand of Dawn's hair and tells her she has strong DNA, so Joyce is at least a good candidate. As he walks round the room, Dawn notices he has some kind of tail under his clothes. He tells them they need an egg from the nest of a Gora demon to complete the spell, and writes down an incantation for Dawn to recite. He says she will also need a picture of her mother; if the spell goes wrong, destroying the picture is the only way to reverse it. He tells Spike where the Gora is nesting in town and Dawn goes to pay him but he refuses her money and shakes her hand instead, telling her to keep in touch. Dawn looks into his eyes and they turn black, which freaks her out.

Spike and Dawn find the nest, and Dawn insists she help him get the egg while he destracts the demon. Spike wakes the two-headed demon and starts to fight with it while Dawn grabs the egg. They make a run for it, but Dawn rops the egg and runs back for another, ignoring Spike who says it's too dangerous. Given no choice, Spike runs back to distract the Gora again, getting bitten in the process. They escape with the egg and Dawn does the spell at home alone. Willow and Tara are talking about what they had for breakfast, to put in Willow's new journal. Joyce's death has made her realise how fast life goes by and wants to remember everything. Tara notices their copy of 'The History Of Witchcraft' is missing and Willow tries to act innocent. Tara says that the book refers to specific rituals and potions, and they have to call Buffy straight away.

Buffy gets to Dawn just as she finishes the spell and asks her what she's done, and Dawn says mum's coming home. Buffy tells her about Tara's warning that these spells go wrong, but Dawn's not convinced and says she needs her mother, she doesn't have anyone else. Buffy tells her that's not true and Dawn accuses her of not caring about Joyce's death and treating it like a big chore, "cleaning up after mum's mess." Buffy slaps her out of anger and immediately regrets it, then explains that she's had to keep busy with things to stop herself from falling apart. Neither of them notice Joyce's shadow pass the window, but when they hear the knock at the oor they know who it is. Buffy, in tears, has forgotten trying to be strong and runs for the door, for her mother. Unable to face the possibility that Joyce has come back wrong, Dawn rips Joyce's photo before Buffy manages to open the door. Buffy looks out to find no-one there. Dawn comes to Buffy and they both hug, falling into tears with the front door still open.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

While this episode is obviously deeply rooted in the events of the last, this is a more business-as-usual episode than you might at first imagine. Someone does a magic spell for selfish reasons and it backfires - we've seen this before in @{"Bewitched, Bothered and Bewildered" LINK "BEWITCHED"} and @{"Family" LINK "FAMILY"} @{"The Witch" LINK "THEWITCH"}, for instance.

The scene where Giles listens to an old vinyl LP - the band's Cream I think, but don't quote me on that. Willow's journal - you should keep a diary, it's the coolest thing ever.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "INTERVENTION" "Buffy.guide: Intervention"

@{b}Intervention@{ub}
5ABB18

"Ten. I'm serious to the amount of ten." - Buffy
"Spike!! It's Spike! ... And he's wearing a coat!!" - Buffybot

Giles cooks dinner at Buffy's house for himself, Buffy and Dawn, and even helps wash up afterwards. Giles suggests to Buffy that they start her training again soon, but she dashes the hope evident in his voice by expressing her concerns about what Slaying is doing to her. The perfect Slayer, she says, is inhuman and uncaring - she's scared she cares less about the people around her than she should and blames herself for Riley leaving. She doesn't even know if her own mother knew how much Buffy loved her. She wants a break from Slaying. Giles says he may have an idea that will regain Buffy's focus and answer some of her questions. There is a sacred place in the desert, not so far away, where previous Slayers have found it helpful to visit. It will take about two days. Buffy's reluctant to let Dawn out of her sight, but Dawn says she should go, and she'll be fine hanging out with the gang.

Spike picks up his Buffybot from Warren and checks with him that it has all the extra programming and "special skills" he asked for. He complains that she looks a little plasticy but when the Buffy Robot kicks into action and runs over to kiss him, he changes his mind. Meanwhile, Glory meets with her minions and tells them that since the key is human, they should watch Buffy and find out who's new in her life. Giles drives Buffy out to the desert in his BMW. The actual location of the sacred place is a secret and Giles cannot take her there - he must perform a ritual to transfer his guardianship of the Slayer to a "guide". The ritual involves Giles doing a funny little dance - much to Buffy's amusement. Spike and Buffybot get busy in his crypt.

Giles's chants summon Buffy's guide - a big... cat thing - and she leads Buffy to the sacred spot, and Buffy recognises her surroundings. Meanwhile, Tara has worked some protection spells on Xander's place, where she, Xander and Anya are currently watching over Dawn; Willow's at a late evening class. Anya takes her earrings off and when she walks across the room, Dawn slips them into her pocket. Through the window, we see one of Glory's minions watching them. Buffybot tells Spike how hard she tries to resist him, but she can't... then spoils the moment by asking him if he wants her to start the program over. When Willow leaves class she's also followed by one of Glory's minions. Buffybot gets up while Spike's half-asleep, declaring it "time to slay."

In the graveyard, Buffybot encounters Anya and Xander, who're doing a patrol of their own. Xander is surprised to see "Buffy" back so early and worries that she doesn't quite seem herself. Spike appears and attempts to split the gang up so he can take Buffybot back home. Just then a group of vamps appear and they fight, as two of Glory's minions look on. When that's all done and dusted, Spike and Buffybot suggest Anya and Xander head home. Xander tells Anya he's worried because Buffy seems spaced-out and didn't ask about Dawn. They hear moaning from the graveyard and look back to see "Buffy" having sex with Spike! Xander and Anya go back to his place to tell Willow and Tara what they've seen, and they decide Xander should go and talk to her. In the desert, Buffy is visited by the First Slayer.

Buffybot is servicing Spike orally when Xander visits and accuses him of taking advantage of Buffy in her weakened state. Glory's minions burst in and knock Xander out, before taking Spike, believing him to be the key. The First Slayer tells Buffy that she's full of love, that love is pain, and pain will help her fight. She also says that love will bring her to her gift. Buffybot misses Spike and goes out to look for him. At Xander's, she finds Willow, who tells her how concerned she is about her affairs with Spike. Willow becomes even more confused when Buffy says "Angel's lame. His hair goes straight up and he's bloody stupid!" Xander arrives and tells them all that Spike has been taken to Glory, who thinks he's the key. When Xander asks how they can find Spike, Buffy helpfully informs him that she fights - with weapons. They leave Dawn under Tara's care and go to Buffy's for more supplies.

Buffy tells the First Slayer she's confused: How will love lead her to her "gift"? Is the gift for her, or hers to give? The First Slayer replies simply: "Death is your gift." Buffy refuses to see death as a gift, but the First Slayer will speak no more, and vanishes into thin air. Glory's minions deliver her Spike and she knows straight away that he is not the key - he is impure, a vampire. Jinks protests that "Buffy" protected Spike above all others when they fought the vampires in the graveyard. Annoyed, since she can't even brain-suck a vampire, she throws Spike against a wall and then tortures him by sticking her finger right into his body. Xander, Anya and Buffybot get to Buffy's place and begin gathering weapons. Buffybot has no idea where they will be able to find Glory and Willow suggests Buffy goes upstairs for more weapons. Anya says she should change her clothes too, into something more "fighty".

In Buffybot's absence, the group discuss their action-plan: they will have to talk to Buffy - she needs to know that the mission priority here is not to rescue Spike! Real Buffy walks in and Willow remarks that she got changed very quickly. The guys confront her about having sex with Spike and of course, she knows nothing about it. Just then, Buffybot walks in and they realise she's a robot. Buffy's annoyed at the guys that they couldn't tell her from a robot, but then Buffybot reminds them of the more pressing issue: Glory has Spike. They don't know where to start looking, but Buffy says she has an idea. Meanwhile, Spike gives in to Glory's torture and says he'll tell her who the key is.

Buffy gathers the Scoobies at the spot where Buffy killed Glory's snake-demon. She tells them to split up, checking the priciest-looking places first. Spike, meanwhile, tells Glory that the key is Bob Barker from TV's 'The Price Is Right', which she obviously doesn't buy, then assures her that Buffy will kick her "skanky, lopsided" arse. He offends her by calling her a whoreish fashion victim and ske kicks him so hard he flies out of the room, the chains that bound him breaking like they were spaghetti. Spike tries to get away in an elevator, but misses it and prises the doors open, jumps down on top of the carriage and drops through the trapdoor. Spike's about to step out of the lift at the ground floor when noe of Glory's minions blocks his way.

Buffy arrives with Xander and they fight with the assembled minions. Then Giles and Buffybot arrive and Giles joins in the fight - getting himself pinned down at the throat by one minion. He calls for Buffy, and the Buffybot lifts the minion off Spike. He throws Buffybot against the wall, and she stops functioning. Then Real Buffy comes in and knocks the offending minion to the ground. The minions run back to Glory and she punishes them for letting Buffy and her friends get way with Spike. A little later, Willow checks out Buffybot and finds out she's just fried a couple of connections, which can be fixed easily. Xander admits to feeling a little sorry for Spike. Spike's in his crypt, nursing his nasty wounds when Buffybot walks in and coos over him. She asks why he let Glory hurt him, and he says it's because she wanted to know who the key was. Buffybot says she can tell Glory and then she won't have to hurt him but Spike stops her and says if Glory found out and something happened to Dawn, it would destroy Buffy. He'd rather die than see Buffy in that much pain.

Buffybot leans forwards and kisses Spike, and he realises it's not Buffybot, but real deal. She thanks him for helping her and Dawn, and says she won't forget it.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Xander says he has no weapons in his house - doesn't this seem ridiculous, since the reason they were all at Xander's house was to protect Dawn? What were they going to use to defend themselves?!

"Death is your gift" - the words of the First Slayer are the first real hint as to the events at the end of the season in @{"The Gift" LINK "THEGIFT"}, although Buffy's "Summers Blood" speech in @{"Blood Ties" LINK "BLOODTIES"} and even an obscure speech by Faith in @{"Graduation Day - Part Two" LINK "GDAY2"}, almost two years ago, may refer to Buffy's gift. We also see here the first moment where Buffy feels something other than contempt for Spike - and kisses him.

Among the fave funny moments in this episode are: Buffybot's point-of-view spots which show Buffy's main priority "Please Spike" and subdirectories like "position 11", and identify Willow as gay from 1999-present day. Also, there's the moment when Buffybot offers to sketch some of these positions for Willow.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "TOUGHLOVE" "Buffy.guide: Tough Love"

@{b}Tough Love@{ub}
5ABB19

"Mmmmm... vitamins!" - Glory.

Buffy's stops by Prof. William's classroom to apologise for missing his lecture, and to tell him she's quitting college to take care of Dawn. He signs a form for her and tells her he's sorry for her loss. Buffy tells him how much she enjoyed his poetry class and says she hopes she'll be back. Ben arrives late for his shift at the hospital to find out he's been sacked - he hasn't shown up for work in two weeks. He goes to the locker room to pack his things away and gets increasingly worked up about what Glory's doing to his life - then he feels her coming, and transforms. Glory's hungry.

Later, at her apartment, Glory pampers herself with a bubble-bath, while three of her minions stand next to the bath, blindfolded, holding a loofah, a box of chocolates, and a refreshing drink for her. She asks them to tell her everything they saw while they spied on Buffy and the gang, so she can figure out for herself who the key is. Buffy and Dawn sit in Principal Stevens' office - it appears Dawn has been skipping school. The Principle has Dawn wait outside while she talks with Buffy alone. At the Magic Box, Anya bewilders Willow and Xander with her new-found racism and disapproval of all things un-American (such as French people and people who don't think money can buy happiness).

Buffy and Dawn arrive and Buffy leaves Dawn to start on her homework while she talks to Giles in the training room. Giles says Buffy will have to put her foot down, and Buffy tries to persuade Giles to do it for her. He refuses, saying it should be Buffy who does this, and she has to start now. She walks back through to the shop, where Dawn is stood with Xander, Anya and Willow on the floor around her making a triangle shape. They're all laughing and Buffy tells Dawn she's supposed to be doing her homework. Willow explains that she was using visual stimulation to help Dawn learn but Buffy's having none of it and tells Dawn to get her things together. From now on she'll be doing her homework at home. Willow tells Buffy she shouldn't be so hard on her and she should "de-freak" and invites her to the World Culture Fair. Buffy declines and takes Dawn home.

Glory gives her minions a cosy little speech at her apartment. She was under their noses all along! The monks did a great job, she says, of hiding the key - all the little details made her seem so human! "I think it's time to collect the key." Willow and Tara discuss Buffy and Dawn's problems and Tara says she Willow can't know what it's like to lose a parent. Willow looks upset and Tara feels like she's said something wrong. Willow admits that she feels like her opinion doesn't count because she didn't lose her mum, and that Tara "sort of" acts like the big knowledge woman. Their discussion becomes a broader argument about their relationship - Willow feels like Tara's been doing everything longer than Willow: coming out, witchcraft... But Tara says Willow is way beyond her there - her power is frightening. Willow's changing so fast, she doesn't know where she will fit in her life. Willow's upset that she Tara apparently thinks so little of their relationship and runs off.

Glory's minions watch Buffy's house. Inside, Buffy talks to Dawn about her list of chores. Dawn won't take her seriously and so Buffy tells her what the principle told her when Dawn wasn't in the room - if Buffy can't make Dawn go to school, they'll take her into care. Tara sits alone at the culture fair while Willow sits at the Magic Box, both miserable. Tara feels a set of fingers interlock with hers. Tara thinks it's Willow, then she turns and realises who it really is - Glory. Giles tells Willow that she'll feel better once she makes her apologies... and as he's speaking, finds one of Glory's minions eavesdropping on them. It takes little persuasion for him to tell them everything - he says Glory knows who the key is, "the witch", and there's nothing they can do to stop her. Willow realises he's talking about Tara and runs out to find her.

Glory squeezes Tara's hand so hard that it bleeds and tels her not to cry out because she'll kill everyone who tries to help her. She tastes Tara's blood and realises she's just a normal human. But knowing that Tara still knows who the key is, she attempts to bargain with her: if she lets her know who the key is, she won't brain-suck her. Tara glances back at Glory defiantly as Willow runs through the fair crowd towards them. Powerless to stop her, Willow bears witness as Glory pushes her fingers into Tara's head, leaving her insane, and then is gone. The guys take Tara to hospital and the doctor says Tara will have to stay overnight for observation and Willow can take her home tomorrow. Tara's not making any more sense - she's become just like the other patients. Buffy arrives at the hospital a little late because she's had to drop Dawn off with Spike.

Dawn tells Spike that she sees herself as the reason for what's happened to Tara, and for Spike's bruises and all the pain and suffering that wouldn't have happened had she simply never existed. She wants to be good, but she can't even though she's not necessarily evil. At the hospital, Willow tells Tara she'll see her tomorrow as the nurse takes her away to a bed. Willow wants revenge and starts after Glory until Buffy think she makes her see sense: she may be an incredibly powerful witch, but Glory is a god. Willow takes little notice and at the Magic Box, she runs up the stairs into the section with the extra-powerful stuff in and finds a hidden book entitled 'Darkest Magick'. Willow makes her way to Glory, who mocks her when she first floats in, but soon finds Willow can do more damage to her than Buffy has managed so far.

Buffy, Spike and Dawn sit underground, and Buffy explains that Willow was about to go and try exacting revenge on Glory until Buffy cooled her down. Spike and Dawn question Buffy's wisdom in trusting that Willow wouldn't go off and try to tackle Glory alone - even if it was potential suicide. Spike would do it. Imagine if it was me, says Dawn, which is the clincher and Buffy sets off in a hurry. Despite her initial success, Willow is finding Glory mostly impervious to Willow's supernatural attacks. Picking up one of Willow's knifes, Glory pins her to the wall and is about to kill her when, yes, you guessed it... Buffy grabs Glory's hand and fights her for a while before helping Willow off the floor and, Willow holding Glory back with a spell, they make a run for it.

Willow, Tara, Buffy and Dawn eat together in Willow's room, Willow and Dawn taking turns to spoonfeed Tara. Buffy asks Willow if she'll need anything, but Will says she thinks she'll manage. Tara is her everything, her commitment to her is stronger that all, and she will look after her even if she never recovers. Buffy tells her she understands. Suddenly the room rips open and Glory stands in the sunlight. Tara freaks and Dawn tries to calm her down - but she was wrong to draw attention to herself because Tara looks at her and, like the other mental patients, can see she is the key, and comments about the "pure green energy" she can see... Glory knows.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Tara first airs her concerns about Willow's increasing powers in this episode. This comes to a head later, but for now it's going to fester. That scene is incredibly well done - if you have the episode on video, once you've watched the scene, rewind to the start and see how much the mood has changed.

"She's a talented girl with a sharp mind - when she puts the effort in!" ... I used to get that from my teachers, with the requisite scowl, all the time. Teachers hate underacheivers.

