@endnode

@node "SPIRAL" "Buffy.guide: Spiral"

@{b}Spiral@{ub}
5ABB20

"Florence bloody Nightingale to the rescue (!)" - Spike.

Follows on from @{"Tough Love" LINK "TOUGHLOVE"}.

Left with no choice but to run, Buffy grabs Dawn and makes a run for it, diving straight through the door towards the the university halls. Willow holds Glory back with another spell, takes Tara and runs. Walls, however pose little threat to Glory and she simply walks through them in pursuit of Buffy and Dawn. Running like the wind, she manages to get ahead and confront the sisters. She asks Buffy if she has any final words, and Buffy says indeed she does: Truck. Right then, a massive tanker smashes into Glory and sends her flying into the air. She lands on a car roof, and is about to get up when she feels Ben coming on. Ben finds himself in the middle of a wreck, wearing women's clothes, with absolutely no recollection of how he even got there.

Safe at Xander's - for the time being - Buffy tells the rest of the gang what happened, and tells them the only option is to leave town. Buffy says they cannot possibly fight Glory and if they stay, they'll die. They have to leave right away, and not tell anyone they're leaving. While the guys pack, Buffy's going to find some transport. At Ben/Glory's apartment, Ben gives one of Glory's female minions Glory's shredded clothes. She manages to dote on him as well as attempt to extract any information he has about the events of the day, and Ben tells her how frustrated he is that he can't have a normal life. She reminds him that he wouldn't exist at all if it wasn't for Glory. He says it doesn't matter how he came by this life, he plans on keeping it. He says he's going to find the key first and she asks him if he could really take a human life?

Buffy arrives to pick up the gang in a large motorhome with the windows mostly covered up. They get inside and Giles finds to his and Xander's horror that Spike is driving. Buffy says they need him and he's coming whether they like it or not and they hit the road, Buffy shutting herself away from the rest of the gang in the other room. Two knights of the Byzantium discharge Orlando, the knight who was brain-sucked, from the hospital. They take him back to their leader, where he babbles about a shiny key and a shiny pretty girl. The leader realises he means that the key is in human form, and tells his troops to prepare to advance. We see there are hundreds of them. In the motorhome, Giles has taken over the wheel and poor Xander is feeling travel-sick. Spike says he ha his eye on a Porsche which had just enough room for him, Buffy and Dawn. Xander's sick of Spike's obnoxious talk and goes up to the front to talk to Giles. Giles says that Buffy may be right, that in a confrontation Spike may prove useful.

Willow tells the guys she still has had no luck researching. Then Tara opens the shutters and the sunlight streams in on Spike. Willow tells Tara not to do that and Tara starts crying. Willow apologises to Spike while Tara starts crying about the fact that the sun is gone and its "all dark". Meanwhile, in the hospital's mental ward, the patients chant in union: "Dark. All dark." Their chants changes to "Soon" and Glory's minions find out that the moment is coming, "the signs are in alignment". Dawn goes through to find Buffy and thanks her for everything. Buffy feels like she doesn't deserve thanks - she's running aaway from evil, but it should be the other way round. Dawn says look on the bright side - things can't get any crazier, right? Just then an arrow pierces the rear of the motorhome, just missing Buffy's head. Buffy looks out to see several, heavily-armed, Byzantium knights following them on horseback. They run into the main room and the arrows start coming thick and fast.

Buffy tells everyone to get down and Spike suggests Giles uses the motorhome as a weapon in its own right. Buffy assures Willow they won't hit the horsies... then tells Giles to aim for the horsies. Giles's swerving does little to shake them, and one knight jumps on top of the van, and drives his sword down through the roof. He doesn't hit anyone, but tries again. And again - this time Spike stops the blade before it buries into Buffy's brain and holds it while the knight attempts to pull it back. Xander helps Buffy out of the roof-hatch and just as she gets up on the roof, the knight gets his sword free. The knight falls and loses his sword, he and Buffy trade blows for a second, then he manages to push her over the edge. Holding on to the roof-rack, Buffy waits for him to peer over and boots him in the head. Inside, Dawn bandages Spike's hands. Just as Buffy dispenses with the first knight, two other knights throw grappling hooks at the roof-rack and one of them breaks through the window next to Dawn, but Anya fends him off with her frying pan!

Buffy throws another three Byzantium knights overboard and soon it appears they've given up - no sign of them in the rearview mirrors. Then Giles sees, coming the other way, a knight with a large spear. He throws it through the window and it hits Giles, who loses control of the motorhome, throwing Buffy off to the ground. The van skids sideways and rolls onto its side, but the gang escape with minor injuries. They take refuge at an old, disused petrol station and lay Giles down on the counter. Buffy's trying her hardest to figure out what to do next - they have to move because they're too close to the wreck of the motorhome and easy to find, but Giles looks like he might die soon. To make matters worse, the knights re-appear and start firing flaming arrows in at them. One knight and the General manage to break in and Spike is helpless to fight since the Byzantium are human. Willow puts an energy barrier up around the garage while Buffy manages to knock out the knight and disarm the general. Once the barrier is up, the gang tie up the general and Buffy questions him.

The general refuses to tell his men to surrender, saying the key is too dangerous to exist; even if it's not Dawn's fault she must be destroyed. Buffy tells him that they are not enemies. Tara freaks out and starts saying it's time - and again, in the mental ward, the patients are echoing her words. They break from their restraints and escape, knocking out the nurse. Orlando, the insane Byzantium knight, is also saying "it's time" and one of his fellow knights decides to put him out of his misery. While the clerics try to break Willow's barrier, a weak Giles tells Buffy how proud he is of her. She's everything he could have hoped for. Giles puts his head back and loses consciousness with his hand in Buffy's. Buffy asks Willow to open a door in the barrier and asks if they will let someone come and help; they do after all have their general. Inside, Willow fixes the phone and Buffy calls Ben and asks him to do a real big favour. Ben arrives and makes his way inside, where he treats Giles. He says he's stable but he needs to be moved to a hospital.

Spike and Xander argue about what action they should take. Spike thinks they should make a break for it, but Xander sees no sense in that. Buffy breaks up the discussion and the general laughs at the mess that the gang are in. Buffy asks him to tell her what he knows. Glory, the Beast, along with two other hellgods, ruled over a demon dimension of unspeakable torment until her power grew beyond what the other two gods could conceive. They became afraid and decided to strike against her before she attempted to take over the dimension and banished her in the body of a mortal new born baby boy. The Beast's only weakness is when she is in this human form - kill the man, and the god dies. Alas, the identity of the man has never been known. Buffy's encounters with Glory have been glimpses of the true beast - such is her power, she can temporarily escape the mortal body of the man.

Dawn asks about what she stands for as the key. The general tells her that she was created to open gates between dimensions - using her power, Glory hopes to return to the hell dimension she's been banished from. The key opens all the gates, between each and every dimension - realities will bleed into each other, and the universe will collapse into chaos. Nearly as old as the Beast itself, the key was found by monks who thought they could harness the power of the key for good, but they failed. Out of the room, Dawn asks what they are going to o. Buffy doesn't know, but promises she won't let anything happen to her. The general calls Ben over and attempts to convince him to kill Dawn and save the order of the universe. Dawn stands by Giles's side and Ben comes over. He tells her it's not her fault Giles has been hurt, and takes a needle and fills it up, telling her sometimes bad things happen to good people. He walks up behind her... and injects Giles. Then he begins to feel Glory coming on and starts shouting at the gang to let him out right away.

Sensing something is seriously wrong, Buffy shouts for Willow to open a door, but it's too late and Ben morphs into Glory. She sees the general and kills him by throwing a wheeltrim at him, frizbee-style. Spike goes to attack her, followed by Buffy, but neither manage to get a punch in. Glory spies Dawn, takes her and runs, punching a hole in Willow's barrier. The hole seals up and Buffy can't get through to follow them, and runs inside to tell Willow to get the barrier down. By the time she returns outside, the entire army has been slain. No longer able to cope, Buffy drops to the floor, giving up. Willow shouts at her to get up, they need her, but her voice is just a distant echo.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

It's interesting to imagine how Glory actually managed to kill the entire army of Byzantium in the fifteen seconds Buffy was gone for. So she finally has Dawn... what is she going to do with her?

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "THEWEIGHTOFTHEWORLD" "Buffy.guide: The Weight Of The World"

@{b}The Weight Of The World@{ub}
5ABB21

"Is everybody here very stoned?!" - Spike.

At her apartment, Glory ponders out loud why, if she's this close to returning home, she doesn't feel happy, while Dawn sits opposite her, gagged. Spike has hotwired Ben's car and they all agree they should go. Even Giles seems a little stronger. Buffy, however, still hasn't uttered a word. She's completely spaced. Willow and then Spike try to snap her out of it. Spike tries punching her and Xander freaks at him. They begin fighting and Willow uses a spell to seperate them. She says once they get back to Sunnydale, Xander will take Giles to hospital, Anya will look after Tara, and Spike will go to find out where Glory is. Willow is going to try and help Buffy in the meantime.

Spike asks what to do if they come across Ben. Willow says Buffy doesn't need a doctor and Spike laughs, saying especially not one who's Glory!! It seems the trick Glory works on humans so they can't see her transform doesn't work on vamps. Spike has a hard time convincing the gang that Ben and Glory are one and the same - patricularly a lightheaded Giles. Glory continues to feel guilt and can't understand why: she's a god and a god has no concept of right and wrong. She even offers Dawn a pizza. Dawn tells her not to call her "Dawny" and Glory gets pissed. She's certain Dawn has done something to make her feel guilt and then calls her minions in to annoint her. She tells Dawn that her blood is the key - all the has to do is bleed Dawn dry, and Glory can go home. She plans to perform the ritual tonight.

Willow leaves Tara in Anya's care while Willow goes to perform a spell to try and get inside Buffy's mind. She sits opposite her friend and soon finds herself in a house she doesn't reconise. She finds a little girl sitting at a small table with her dolly. She says hi to Willow and Willow replies, "Hello Buffy." Meanwhile, Spike busts into Glory's place and looks around. Willow asks Little Buffy what she's doing here, playing with her dolls. She has to come out - they need her. Little Buffy says it's a big day for her, and the door opens. Little Buffy's mum and dad come through holding a baby and introduce her to her new sister, Dawn. Little Buffy's jealous at first but when Joyce lets her hold Dawn, she says she'd like to take care of her. Willow hears footsteps and turns around - now at the Magic Box, she observes the present-day Buffy sombrely putting a book on the shelf. Then she finds herself next to a fire.

At the hospital, Giles is up and walking. He asks Xander how Buffy is and he explains that Willow is trying to reach her psychically. Giles suggests they check Glory's victims on the medical ward but Xander says he already did - there's no-one there. They meet with Spike, who tells them he found nothing at Glory's apartment. He does say however that he knows a guy who may be able to help. Glory meanwhile begs her minions to do something to get Ben out of her - his humanity is "infecting" her and she can't bring herself to harm Dawn. A minion tells her there's nothing that can be done about it, so Glory decides she wants to do the ritual now. At the fire, Willow witnesses the First Slayer telling Buffy that death is her gift. Then she sees Buffy putting the book back on the shelf again. Next she finds herself following Buffy down the coridoor of her house.

Glory's minions tell her that if she kills Dawn now they'll lose everything. She apologises for being so emotional, and asks them to leave so she can talk with Dawn. She asks how people can possibly live like this, in this world, slaves to their own feelings, being torn apart by them. Still inside Buffy's head, Willow follows Buffy into Joyce's room, where Joyce's grave is on the floor, and the carpet is grass. Willow says she's sorry, but Buffy tells her not to be - death is her gift. Buffy crosses into Dawn's room, where Dawn is crying, and sits on the edge of her bed. Buffy tells Willow that death is what she does. She takes a pillow from next to Dawn and begins to smother her with it. Willow tells her to stop but Buffy tells her it's okay, because she's figured it out: "Death is my gift".

Glory turns back into Ben and asks Dawn if Glory has hurt her. Ben's remembering all the awful things Glory has done. The minions knock on the door and Ben answers before knocking them out. He says he'll take her as far as he can and then ditch her before Glory returns. Willow finds herself back at square one, at the table with Little Buffy. She watches as her parents come home with newborn Dawn and Buffy puts the book on the shelf in the Magic Box again. Spike and Xander call on the creepy old guy who helped Dawn with her resurrection spell. Xander finally fully realises that Ben is Glory - "it's like a fog has lifted" - Ben and Glory are melding together. The old guy says he can't help and advises them to stay out of her way. He tries to bullshit them with a story about a bloke in China, but Spike knows better than to fall for it, and sees that the old guy is actuslly standing in front of what Spike is after.

The old guy jumps across the room and pulls a sword on Spike, who knocks the sword aside. Then the old guy unleashes his long tongue on Xander, smashing him against the wall. He throws the box Spike wants on the open fire and then grabs Spike and tells them that Glory's day is coming. Xander gets up and knocks the old guy over and struggles on the floor with him while Spike grabs the box out of the fire. Xander manages to drive the old guys sword into his body, resulting in much gloopiness. As we see once Xander and Spike leave, however, he's not quite dead. Back in Buffy's mind, she walks towards Dawn's room to kill her again. Willow says she must stop this, reliving something that never happened. Buffy says it did happen, and doesn't know what Willow's talking about.

Ben and Dawn are walking through town when they see minions nearby and duck down an alley to evade them. Ben peeks out and when he turns back, Dawn knocks him out with some heavy chains, not fully trusting him. She says she's sorry, and she hears Glory's voice: "Sorry?! That actually hurt, you pre-pubescent puke!" Glory says she doesn't want to waste a drop of Dawn's blood - but she knows a lot of ways to hurt her without the bleeding. She becomes Ben, and he says "leave her alone". Glory tries to keep him in his place but he keeps coming back and the two enter into an argument. Dawn tries to escape but Glory stops her, throwing her against a dumpster. Glory tells him she's going home no matter what he does, and he says she'll need Dawn's blood. He smashes a bottle and holds it at Dawn, saying when he's finished there won't be enough blood to fill a bottle-cap. Glory attempts to make a deal with Ben: She offers him immortality in exchange for Dawn. Ben declines at first, but soon hands her over to Glory's minions.

Buffy and Willow stand in Joyce's room again. Willow asks again why Buffy keeps doing what she's doing, and Buffy says, again, that this is what she does. Then they're in the Magic Box again, Buffy and Willow now watching Buffy put the book on the shelf. Willow asks her why she keeps repeating this moment. The two Buffys explain that this is the moment she quit. She realised she couldn't beat Glory and for a second, wanted it to happen; if Glory beats Buffy, Dawn would die, and Buffy would grieve, but it would be over. By wanting Glory to win, just for a second, Buffy believes she killed Dawn. When Glory came and took Dawn away, Buffy's sure she could have done something more, but she didn't. This is why she killed her sister. Willow tells Buffy(s) that Dawn's not dead yet - but she will die if Buffy doesn't snap out of it. If she can't, then she really did kill Dawn. Willow walks away and Buffy asks where she's going. Willow says she's going where Buffy is needed and invites her to come along. In the real world, Buffy's suddenly animated again and the first thing she can think to do is cry. Willow rushes over to comfort her.

At the Magic Box, Giles tells Buffy that Glory intends to open the inter-dimensional portal with a ritual blood-letting: of Dawn's blood, at a certain time and place. Once the blood begins to flow there is but one way to close the portal, which is to kill Dawn.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

The idea of time-loops is explored in Buffy again, in @{"Life Serial" LINK "LIFESERIAL"}, an episode where the Trio put Buffy in a reality loop. Similar ideas have also been used in Star Trek TNG and the X-Files episode 'Monday'.

This episode is host to one of those Buffy "moments": when Giles furrows his brow and says "So... do we suspect there is some kind of connection between Ben and Glory...?"

She's only just gone insane? Hmm, anyway I forgot to make any notes while I was watching and now I have to watch the ending so see you there.

Little Buffy is played by Alexandra Lee.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "THEGIFT" "Buffy.guide: The Gift"

@{b}The Gift@{ub}
5ABB22

"But you're just a girl..."

It's night-time and a boy, roughly Dawn's age, is being pursued by a vampire, who catches up with him in an alley. Buffy pops her head out and asks "innocently" if they're having a fight, and says fighting's not cool. The boy asks her to go and call the police but the vampire says he'd quite like an appetiser: it seems he doesn't recognise the Buffster. They fight and Buffy snaps his leg. He throws her on top of a dumpster and she summersaults back down giving him a hefty kick in the process. When he's dusted, Buffy tells the boy he should go home. He asks how she did that - she's just a girl. "That's what I keep saying," she replies.

Back inside, Buffy has Giles go over the ritual yet again. She says she could not kill Dawn; if the portal is opened she will be protecting Dawn, not killing her. Buffy says the monks essentially made Dawn out of her - they are a part of each other. Anya attempts to lift the mood and says they should stop Glory before the ritual commences. By Giles' calculation, they have about two hours. Willow suggests they stall Glory until it's too late to go through with it. Anya remembers the Dagon Sphere and suggests @{"Olaf" LINK "ABOUTOLAF"}'s hammer will make a great weapon against Glory. The gang still have no idea how to find Glory however. Sitting in an armchair, Tara starts talking about having to be somewhere... It's the big day, and "it" calls her.

Ben brings some clothes to Dawn for her to wear for the ceremony. Dawn cannot bear to look at Ben, who has betrayed her, and screams at him to turn back into Glory. Glory tells Dawn she shouldn't blame Ben - he's just trying to live. His influence may have held Glory back when she fought with Buffy, and that why she's not dead. Dawn says, maybe Glory just can't take her. But as Glory points out, Buffy hasn't been to rescue her yet. Then Glory tells Dawn how the ritual works. If Buffy does show, it might not be to save her. Buffy trains while Giles and the gang try to come up with more ideas. Giles comes in and apologises for having to say and do things people don't like. Buffy says if he tries to hurt Dawn, she'll stop him. Buffy thinks about their past battles - she's always won them, always known which way was right. Now she doesn't know, and all she wants is her mother. Buffy thinks the First Slayer's claim that death is her gift means that a Slayer is nothing but a killer but Giles disagrees. Buffy says that if Dawn dies, she quits.

It's time, and Glory has her minions take Dawn to the top of a makeshift tower. Meanwhile, in the Magic Shop basement Xander and Anya get dressed hurriedly - in the middle of their search for the Dagon Sphere they decided they needed to relieve the tension. Anya's still as tense and doesn't think she could be any more nervous - until Xander pulls out a ring from his pocket and asks her if she'll marry him. She slaps him, and tells him he's just proposing because the world's gonig to end. He says he's proposing because it's not, and Anya says yes, but tells him to give her the ring "when the world doesn't end". Buffy's especially interested in what Willow's coming up with, since she's the only person who's been able to harm Glory at all so far. Willow is working on a spell that will hopefully reverse Glory's brain-sucking of Tara, weakening her. Willow tells Tara it won't be long, and she slaps her. Willow promises she'll bring her back.

Buffy and Spike go to Buffy's for weapons. Buffy has to invite Spike in, having had the protection spell worked against him previously. Buffy tells him she's counting on him to protect Dawn. He promises he will, then tells her he knows she'll never love him, but he's grateful she treats him like a man. Glory's minions leave Dawn at the top of the tower, promising her Glory will be with her shortly. Tara leads the way to the tower for the gang. Giles asks Willow if she needs anything - she says courage, and Spike offers her some of his ever-present bourbon. Saying no thanks, Willow follows Tara around until Glory confronts them, and Willow works her magic, holding Tara and Glory by their heads. When the trick's done all three of them are thrown outwards and to the floor. Glory feels weak and needs to feed - and the first candidate she sees is Buffy. Buffy throws the Dagon Sphere at Glory, but although it appears to weaken her, she soon crushes it and renders it powerless. While Buffy manages to kick Glory's ass a little for once, Spike, Giles, Anya and Xander get to work fighting against the minions and mental patients guarding the tower.

Willow finds Tara and she's made a full, if traumatic, recovery. Meanwhile, Glory is gaining strength and punches Buffy's head clean off - a little too clean actually; she realises she's been fighting a robot. She asks if everyone knew the Slayer was a robot, and then hears real Buffy's voice from behind her. She turns around to meet the full-on impact of Olaf's hammer. "You're not the brightest God in the heavens, are you?" Buffy hears Dawn screaming for her and starts to make her way up the tower. Glory gets up and comes after her, and they fight part-way up the tower. They both lose balance after much ducking and punching, and fall right back to Earth. Glory notices Buffy doesn't have the hammer anymore, and thinks she may just win the fight now - until Xander deals her a hefty blow with a wrecking ball! Buffy uses this time to find the hammer again. Giles, Anya and Spike have been forced into hiding, but Giles seems optimistic; there are only a couple of minutes left to start the ritual in. What he hasn't banked on, though, is the presence of the creepy old resurrection man at the top of the tower. Dawn thinks he's here to help - but then he pulls a knife. Spike can sense him up there and Willow communicates with Spike telephathically, telling him to get up there right now. She clears a path for him through the crowd and he runs up as fast as he can, to find the creepy old man about to start the ritual. Quick as a flash, Old Creep runs round Spike's side and drives the knife into his back before he can even make a move, before throwing him over the side of the tower.

Buffy's doing some serious damage to Glory with Olaf's hammer; she's on the floor, and we can hear her bones crunching. Glory turns into Ben, and he apologises. She tells him never to come near her and her friends again, and he promises neither he or Glory will. Buffy leaves to get Dawn. When she's gone, Giles appears and asks Ben if he can move. Ben says Buffy could have killed him. Giles begs to differ - Buffy is a merciful hero, and despite the fact that Glory will re-emerge and cause her grief, Buffy couldn't take a human life. Giles can, however. He reaches down and puts his hand over Ben's mouth and nose, suffocating him.

Meanwhile, on the tower above, the creepy old guy makes cuts on Dawn's body. Her blood starts to flow just as Buffy arrives and knocks the old guy straight off the tower. The portal opens and immediately bad things start to happen; bolts of lightning spike out of the portal, ripping holes in roads and turning buildings into monster hideouts. Spike, lying on the ground, very nearly falls into a fresh crack, and Anya gets hit by falling rubble. Even a dragon-like creature flies out of the portal. Dawn knows about the ritual and tells Buffy she has to jump to stop this. Buffy won't let her sister kill herself. Dawn says that the blood must stop flowing, and this is the only way. Buffy comes to a realisation. Dawn was made out of Buffy, like she said; they share blood. And death is her gift. Either one of the sisters can jump now to close the portal, and Buffy must make the ultimate sacrifice. She must give her life so Dawn can live.

Buffy tells Dawn some important messages she must know, kisses her on the cheek and runs towards the end of the tower platform. She dives, falling through the portal and ending her own life. As the sun rises and they find Buffy's lifeless boy at the foot of the tower, Willow and Tara hold each other, Xander carries Anya and Giles looks at his Slayer in an impossible state of shock. Spike cries, unable to contain his grief. Dawn remembers her sister's final words:

@{i}"Dawn, listen to me. I love you. I will always love you. This is the work that I have to do. Tell Giles that I figured it out, and I'm okay. Give my love to my friends - you have to take care of them now. You have to take care of each other. You have to be strong. The hardest thing in this world is to live in it... Be brave. Live. For me." @{ui}

@{b}Notes@{ub}

You know something special is going to happen right from the start: The introduction starts with Giles' famous "You are the Slayer" speech in the school library (from @{"Welcome To The Hellmouth" LINK "WELCOMETOHELLMOUTH"}) and flashes through various scenes from season one (with its impossibly youthful-looking cast), season two, three, four and five getting faster and faster... And we have watched it all. Just the sad ones like me then? Oh well. Anyway, even my clueless pet hamster cries when he watches this. This episode was everything about Buffy taken to its logical conclusion: they tied up all the strings, returned Tara's sanity, had Xander and Anya getting un-officially engaged, and in "most sweaty naughty feelings causing one" had the most disgusting line one of Glory's minions could have mustered. So... why did they make a sixth season?

It's a strange one. Season six is well worth watching but you can't help but feel a little cheated. There's no way now that the Buffy legacy can be laid to rest properly, or in quite as spectacular a fashion as if they'd simply said the fifth season was the last. They obviously either thought they could bring something new to Buffy's table, or decided they might like to make a bit more money. Well I won't kid myself, the show isn't a purely artistic proposition, it's there to make money too. I guess you just have to cross your fingers and hope cash never becomes the overriding factor.

If, like i did, you get an attack of deja vu while watching Tara pick up that brick right before Willow works her brain-sucking reversal spell, you're probably thinking of the episode @{"Bad Eggs" LINK "BADEGGS"}, in which various spaced-out students were moving rocks about for the Bezoar.

