@endnode

@node "BARGAINING2" "Buffy.guide: Bargaining - Part Two"

@{b}Bargaining - Part Two@{ub}
6ABB02

Follows on from @{"Bargaining - Part One" LINK "BARGAINING1"}.

"Okay, this is really starting to grate my cheese!" - Xander.

As the Biker Demons circle Buffybot, she worries that she's close to a system failure. Tara and Anya find Xander and Willow, who's still unconscious. They decide to split up to evade the bikers and Xaner promises Tara he'll look after Willow. They'll meet at the Magic Box. Meanwhile the Buffybot looks like it's going to need more than a quick service when the bikers have finished. Six feet under, the real Buffy claws manically at the roof of her coffin.

Xander sets Willow down by a tree and asks where she is. She soon recalls the events of the night, and Willow wants to go back and finish the ritual. Xander tells her the Urn of Osiris was broken, and knowing she can't find another Willow realises that Buffy's really gone. At Buffy's, Spike's enjoying a bit of TV while he watches over Dawn. He hears a bike outside and peers out to see what's going on and the whole neighbourhood is being trashed by Biker Demons. Tara and Anya come close to being caught by bikers and hide for a few seconds. They the Bikers decide to loot some stores and Anya starts to worry they'll head for the Magic Box, and call Dawn and Spike from there. Dawn meanwhile, is freaking out. Spike says they have to leave the house, and promises he'll protect her. At the cemetery, Buffy climbs out of her grave and reads her own tombstone. Not exactly her usual self, she looks at the burning town through blurred vision and wonders what happened.

Anya and Tara get to the Magic Box to find no sign of Willow or Xander, so Tara uses a locator spell, guessing they're lost in the woods. She's right, and Xander and Willow have pretty much given up hope of finding their way out of the woods. Xander starts to tell Willow off for not telling him how extreme the trials would be, when a light appears. Xander thinks it's a motorcycle headlight until it comes up close; then he thinks it's a firefly. Willow recognises the small blue-white glowing entity as Tara's work. The light leads them out of the woods. Meanwhile, Buffy leans against a car to rest and the alarm goes off. The noise is too much for her to bear and she covers her ears with her hands. The owner of the vehicle comes out of his house with a gun and tells Buffy to get away from his property. He fires the gun into the air and Buffy goes.

Spike watches the carnage from behind a hedgerow and smiles - it looks like fun. Anyway, he finds a baseball helmet and bat, and gives the helmet to Dawn. He leaves Dawn hiding in the hedge and manages to knock a biker off his bike. Taking the bike, he shouts to Dawn, who jumps on, and they set off in search of refuge. Xander and Willow get to the Magic Box and ask where Dawn and Spike are. Willow says they haven't been able to get hold of them, and suggests going out to look for them. Anya says there's no way they can do it - Willow's drained, so they're just four humans against a town full of demons. They need Buffy. Willow says Buffy isn't coming back, they need to get out there now. Buffy comes across a group of the biker demons, who have decided they'd quite like to stay in town a while. They have Buffybot chained up to their bikes and as Buffy screams "No!" they accelerate and tear the robot into several pieces.

The demons see Buffy and think it's another robot. They try to run her over with their bikes but Buffy eludes them after one accidentaly throttles the other with his chain. Willow, Tara, Anya and Xander are armed and walking through the streets. Anya's still nagging Xander about announcing their engagement, while Tara reasons that maybe the spell wasn't supposed to work, and fate sent the demons to stop the spell before it was completed. Just then, Buffy jumps down in front of them. They think it's the Buffybot at first... but when the "robot" doesn't say anything, Willow realises she's the real deal. Buffy runs but they catch up and corner her, and notice her hands are bloody. Xander realises she must have crawled out of her own coffin. Buffy doesn't respond to any of the gang. Just then, some of the bikers appear and the gang attempt to scare them off by telling them two of them are witches; Xander even pretends to be a warlock. The demons are not conviced and they knock Willow and Xander down. The demon's leader says they doesn't want to fight them; they're just going to rape them instead.

Sickened, Buffy approaches the leader and he hits her - angered beyond mere words, she takes him down with three casual blows. She fights the remaining demons with equal gusto. Meanwhile, Spike and Dawn find Buffybot's torn-apart remains. Dawn find there's still some life in Buffybot, who tells her that there's another Buffy, but she doesn't know where she went. Dawn realises real Buffy must be back and runs off into the night. Spike, who's been searching around for bits of Buffybot, doesn't realise Dawn has gone until she's too far ahead of him to catch. With the demons dead, Buffy runs off again, leaving the gang wondering whether to follow her or not. One of the demons on the floor, however proves not to be so dead, and tries to slash Xander with his cat-like retractable metal claws. Buffy, meanwhile, finds the tower where she sacrificed herself to save the world, after killing a biker demon wearing a Judas Priest t-shirt. The gang fight the demon, Willow's magic proving especially useful, until he grabs her by the thoat. Before he has the chance to do any real damage, Tara buries an axe in his back, like a pro.

Up on the tower, Dawn finds Buffy and asks how she got back. The dodgy tower lists and Buffy looks towards the edge, apparently contemplating another jump. Dawn tries to talk Buffy away from the edge and Buffy asks if she's in hell. Dawn says she isn't, and begs her to stay and live, for her. As the tower starts to collapse, Buffy realises Dawn is in danger and runs to her aid. Holding Dawn, she jumps out onto a pulley, which gives way and they plummet towards the ground. Some cardboard breaks their fall, but then the platform drops from the top of the tower. Buffy gets up with Dawn just in time to avoid a severe braining. As they run, the entire tower collapses into a pile of rubble. Dawn embraces her newly-returned sister, glad to have her back, but Buffy looks less than happy to have been resurrected.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Being buried alive has to be one of the worst things imaginable. Do you think you could get out? I don't think I could. In the past people have been buried alive on purpose - by twisted serial killers, or the Acient Egyptians. But years ago, before science gave us heart and life monitors, people were occasionally pronounced dead because their pulse was so weak it was undetectable.

Weird how "normal" it is for Americans to own a gun. I think almost every family must have one (how many times have you heard, "Honey, go get the gun..."?). I once heard that someone's shot dead in LA every 27 minutes. The gun-totting guy in this episode also fires his gun into the air - which, given the right set of circumstances, can still prove fatal. That discharge goes somewhere, you know.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "AFTERLIFE" "Buffy.guide: Afterlife"

@{b}Afterlife@{ub}
6ABB03

"Willow's getting pretty strong. It's hard to get a good night's death around here..." - Spike.

Xander, Anya, Willow and Tara head for Buffy's house, hoping to find her there, and several biker demons almost knock Xander over as they leave town. Willow's beginning to worry that Buffy came back wrong somehow. Meanwhile, Dawn's taken Buffy home. Inside, she sees all the differences. Dawn tells Buffy that Willow and Tara live here now - in Joyce's old room. Buffy asks what else is different, and Dawn says Giles left today. Spike drops by looking for Dawn and gets mad at her for running off and getting herself in danger. When he sees Buffy, he's awestruck, in complete disbelief. Buffy asks how long she was gone; Spike says 47 days. The gang come in and break up the quiet moment, and overwhelm Buffy with questions and babble. Dawn gets them to back off and asks them how they already knew Buffy was back. Willow admits they did a spell, but they didn't think it had worked. Buffy says she just wants to go to sleep.

As Xander and Anya leave, they find Spike, who's pissed at the gang for not telling him they were bringing Buffy back. Xander asks Spike if he can look him in the eyes and tell him seeing Buffy alive wasn't the happiest mooment in his life. As he leaves, Spike warns that magic always has consequences. Inside the house, Buffy stares at herself in the mirror. Willow and Tara go to bed and Willow says she's still not convinced Buffy's okay. Tara says perhaps everyone was so worried about it going wrong, they never expected it to go right. In her room, Buffy looks at her pictures, and as she looks they become dead bodies. She closes her eyes for a second, and they're back to normal. Willow and Tara are sleeping peacefully when something smashes and wakes them up. Buffy's standing at the foot of the bed: "What did you do? Do you know what you did? You're like children, your hands smell of death! Bitches! Filthy little bitches rattling the bones! Did you cut the throat, did you pat its head?!" Buffy throws a crystal ball at the wall behind Tara and Willow's heads. "The blood dried on your hands, didn't it? You were stained, you still are! I know what you did!"

Willow hits the light and Buffy's nowhere to be seen - there's no broken glass either. They check in on Buffy and she's fast asleep in bed. Willow denies knowing what "Buffy" was talking about, depsite the fact that they apparently refer to her sacrifice of the young fawn. They see a strange blob move across the ceiling, and decide they have to call Xander. Xander answers the phone and tells Willow she should get out of the house... then he sees Anya walking towards him, laughing psychotically and cutting her face. Her eyes are white all over. He takes the knife and then Anya falls to the floor, her cuts gone. In the morning, Anya tells the gang it's possibly a hitchhiker demon, who saw Buffy moving between dimensions and tagged along for the ride. Buffy comes down and tells the gang about what happened to the photos last night. The gang get researching and come up pretty much empty, Buffy says she misses Giles and then heads out to patrol. Dawn says she should definitely go, she'll be safe with the others. We see her eyes are white all over, like Anya's were.

Anya returns from the 24-hour coffee shop with drinks when Dawn suddenly calls the gang idiots and tells them she can smell the death on them, before breathing fire across the room and setting the research books on fire. The blob goes away and Dawn's okay again. But where has it gone? Spike is pacing up and down at his crypt, when he hears a noise upstairs. It's Buffy. He talks to her and tells her how much he regrets that Dawn got hurt and Buffy had to jump. He tells her that every night since, he's played the whole thing through his mind and saved her. At the Magic Box, Xander asks Tara if she or Willow knew that the spell might have these consequences. Tara says that Willow wuold never do anything to harm anyone and before the pair finish their discussion, Willow realises where the demon has come from. It didn't follow Buffy back, but is in fact a "price" to pay for their gift - Buffy's return. Unfortunately, if they kill the demon, Buffy will disappear too. Dawn freaks out, but then Willow realises the demon is only temporary. The only way it can survive much longer is if it kills Buffy. Xander's eyes suddenly turn white as he says "thanks for the tip", and the blob makes its way for Buffy.

At Buffy's house, the blob tells Buffy she doesn't belong here, and surrounds her so she can't move. Xander, Anya and Dawn drive to Buffy's, and Xander explains to Dawn that Willow and Tara are working on a spell to give the demon a body for Buffy to fight. Willow and Tara's spell works and Buffy decapitates the demon as Xander, Anya and a grossed-out Dawn stand in the doorway. The next morning, Dawn's leaving for school when Buffy stops her and hands her a packed lunch. Dawn's touched that her sister made her lunch and gives her a hug. Buffy drops by the Magic Box and gives the gang her thanks for getting her out of hell. They all hug and Buffy leaves, to find Spike loitering outside. Buffy's surprised to see him, since it's daylight, but Spike says he's okay if the sun's low enough and he sticks to the shadows. He asks why she's leaving so soon after telling the gang thanks, and she says she wants smoe time alone. Spike then goes to leave, but can't because of the sun. Buffy says it's okay, that he can stay. He asks her if he can get her anything and Buffy says she's okay.

Buffy decides to confide in Spike, and tells him she wasn't in hell. Where she was, she was content, happy and complete. She thinks she was in heaven - and her own friends brought her out of there.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

The structure of this episode is impossibly scrappy. The biggest flaw is that adequate explaination is not given as to why Buffy can fight the "blob" once it has a form. Also, when the "blob" demon confronts Buffy, it manifests itself as a cloud-like spirit, which can in fact physically interact with Buffy - something in direct contradiction to Willow's earlier claim that the demon doesn't exist physically in their dimension. Of course, the demon is not the most important part of this episode, it's just there as filler while the major issue of Buffy's rehabilitation is dealt with.

