@endnode

@node "FLOODED" "Buffy.guide: Flooded"

@{b}Flooded@{ub}
6ABB04

"Easy! We burn the house to the ground and collect the insurance. Plus, fire: pretty!" - Buffy.

Buffy approaches a dripping pipe in the basement, armed with a wrench. Dawn's not convinced of her sister's ability to handle this problem, and says they should call a plumber, but Buffy goes ahead. She tightens the joint and it appears to have worked. There's a rumbling sound and suddenly several holes appear in the pipes areound the room, one spurting water right at Dawn, who runs upstairs. Buffy just stands there, watching as the cellar begins to fill with water. While a plumber Xander knows from the trade looks the pipes over, Buffy's standing at the sink, just watching the water run down the plughole. Buffy's not herself, and even tells Dawn she should eat breakfast at least three times a day. The plumber comes up from the basement and tells them the entire system needs replacing - and it's going to be pricey, even though Xander did a little bargaining for them. Buffy says there won't be a problem paying him. Willow, however, tells her friend that's not quite true: Buffy's all but broke.

Almost all of the money Joyce left behind after her hospital bills is gone. Anya suggests Buffy charges for her Slaying duties, which everyone else thinks is an awful idea. Anya says, why not, Spiderman charges. Dawn says he doesn't and asks Xander who's right. Xander has to agree with Dawn, and Anya storms out. He follows her outside and find out the real reason she's upset is that they still haven't told everyone they're engaged. Xander tells her he wants to make sure every step is just right. They kiss and everything seems right until Anya says "Hey, you tricked me! With your lips and your fancy talk!" and walks off again.

Buffy applies for a loan at the bank, taking along all the information she could find; the loan officer is rather bemused to find she even brings along her old school report cards. He refuses Buffy's application because she has no income. Just then a gang of demons jump through the windows and start knocking out the customers. Buffy goes to fight one of them and the rest of the demons run to the cash registers and get with the robbing. The demons get away with the money but Buffy's presence has at least cut short the orgy of violence. Buffy still doesn't get her loan. Later, Willow watches Buffy train at the Magic Box and says she's glad to see Buffy angry because she hasn't been very emotional since she got back. The rest of the gang are researching, Xander attempting to work up the courage to tell everyone about his engagement to Anya. Dawn begs Tara to let her research, and she comes up with the goods: the leader of the gang was M'Fashnik.

Buffy walks in and tells Dawn she disapproves of her researching. Just then Giles walks in. His eyes confirming what he dared not believe, he can't think of anything to say for a minute. They hug and then go back to the training room to talk, while outside M'Fashnuk stalks along the streets. She asks how England was and Giles says he met some old friends, and made a new one. Giles asks Buffy how she is - she looks tired. She's had trouble sleeping because of her dreams. Buffy starts preparing for the upcoming slayage and Giles goes through to see how te gang's research is coming along. Dawn shows Giles what she's found so far and Giles explains that M'Fashnik demons are glorified errand-boys; performing violent acts for a high price. M'Fashnik pays Warren and two friends, Jonathan and Andrew, a visit and tells them that he wants payment for his work. The three guys have told him that they were "super-villains", commanding over the demon realms with magic and machines. He says that for pitting him against the Slayer, they will pay with their lives. The demon chokes Jonathan and the boys say they didn't know Buffy would be there, and offer him anything in return - he says he wants the Slayer dead. Warren, Jonathan and Andrew go to confer on how.

Giles hears all about Buffy's cash problem while she sets him up a bed on the living room sofa. He offers to help her go through the bills in the morning and Buffy tells him how glad she is that he's back. He says he's glad she's back to and goes to reach for her hand to comfort her, but she gets up and walks away before their hands touch. Warren argues with Jonathan and Andrew; they don't want to kill Buffy, and talk Warren round. Warren has a brain-wave: he gives the demon Buffy's address so he can have the pleasure of killing the Slayer himself. Giles tells Willow how angry he is that Willow used the magic she used to bring Buffy back. He trusted her, but she's put the whole world at risk. Giles said she was lucky, and calls her a "rank, arrogant amateur." Willow says that it's true the magics she used were powerful - she is powerful - and says it's not a good idea for Giles to piss her off. Giles says he very much doubts Buffy's come through unscathed.

Spike finds Buffy outside thinking to herself, having heard Giles' argument with Willow. Spike says they just care about her, and Buffy says that makes it even harder - she's trying to feel okay just for them. Buffy asks Spike why he's always around when she's upset - he reckons it's when she's alone, and he's "not oe for crowds these days." They sit on the back steps of the house, talking in the moonlight. Inside, Giles and Dawn, unable to sleep, are about to go through to the kitchen for some cereal when they hear a rapping at the door. The door busts open, knocking Dawn to the ground, and as we suspected, M'Fashnik is paying a visit. He throws Giles across the room and he goes straight through the bannister of the staircase. Buffy's heard the commotion and stops M'Fashnik before he can hurt Dawn further and they fight, Buffy freaking over everything that gets smashed. She gets him down to the basement to fight him, which is still flooded, knocks him down and kills him.

Next morning, The Trio celebrate their first successful bank robbery, and Jonathan makes hypnotising Buffy and making their her their "willing sex-buddy" part of their mission statement while he lights a cigar with a dollar bill. The gang attempt to fix up Buffy's house but end up throwing out most of the stuff that got trashed. Buffy depairs, but Giles tells her she will learn to deal with it soon enough, just like her mother did. The phone rings and Buffy answers - it's Angel. He's heard that Buffy's alive, and must leave immediately to meet him.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Here we meet The Trio for the first time, who prove to be this season's most unlikely villains. Comparisons might be drawn between them and the X-Files' three Lone Gunmen, three informants to Mulder who were paranoid to the point of insanity (they had about seven locks on the door to their HQ). There's the obsession with gadgets and stereotypical "geekiness"... but unfortunately, The Trio aren't quite as cool as Frohike and the guys. Warren's obviously the leader; his remark that "Forces sometimes have great power over the weak-minded" is of great irony. Jonathan and Andrew prove themselves easily lead, and in scenes where the two try to stand up to Warren they're still nervous even though it's two against one.

Continuity references are made about all three members of The Trio. Warren's is the most recent, he offers the M'Fashnik demon a robot girlfriend, like one he built for himself (see @{"I Was Made To Love You" LINK "IWASMADETOLOVEYOU"}). Jonathan makes a comment about a spell he made so that everyone would think he was cool in @{"Superstar" LINK "SUPERSTAR"}. Andrew is the brother of Tucker Wells, who trained hellhounds to attack his fellow students during @{"The Prom" LINK "THEPROM"}.

Dawn's scenes with Giles are full of warmth and humour that brings a smile to your face, and here the most notable exchanges are about their cereal experiment (mixing every cereal in the house up in one bowl), and Dawn's vision of doom: working in a "poorly ventilated sweatshop" to earn a living.

