@endnode

@node "LIFESERIAL" "Buffy.guide: Life Serial"

@{b}Life Serial@{ub}
6ABB05

"What the f..." - Buffy.

Buffy arrives home with takeaway food for the gang - but they're already sat eating. They asks if she wants to talk about her time with Angel but she doesn't and they accept it. Giles asks her what her plans are now regarding her life, and Buffy says she wanted to re-enroll for college, but she was kinda dead at the deadline. Willow and Tara suggest she sits in at their classes and audit for the remainder of the semester. Bright and early next morning, Warren finishes work on a surveillance van so that they can watch Buffy while each of them perform various tests on her to find out her weaknesses. Andrew has painstakingly spray-painted a Star Wars image of Dark Star on the side of the van but Warren has him spray over it - they don't want to draw attention to themselves.

Buffy's first class of the day with Willow, Sociology, doesn't go so well. Unable to understand most of what the students are discussing, Buffy's at a loss. Walking through the corridoor after the class, Willow and Tara tell her she's just a little rusty. A boy bumps into her and carries on walking, careful not to show his face as Willow shouts after him for being so rude. It's Warren and he's planted a strage hexagonal object on Buffy. He radios back to the van, where Jonathan and Andrew receive his order to initiate the "pulse sequence". They do so and the van's radio dish pops out. Tara hands Buffy a book on art to look through since they have a twenty-minute gap before Tara's Art Appreciation class. Buffy hears a weird noise and suddenly Tara is sat down, halfway through relating a story about cooking for Willow. Tara says she must have been really engrossed in the book. Buffy goes to drink from the water fountain when she hears the noise again and Tara's calling her from the end of the corridoor, saying they'll be late for class.

The Trio observe Buffy as time accelerates an skips, Tara asking Buffy where she's been - she's missed the Art class. Time moves again and Tara disappears before she can be of any help, and Buffy finds her outside walking away. She calls but Tara doesn't hear, and everyone starts moving faster and faster, knocking into her as she crawls to refuge, finding a spot under a stone table. She finds the object Warren planted on her and he self-destructs it. Everything is normal again. Inside the van, Jonathan and Andrew give Warren "140 points" for his efforts. Andrew's up next. At the construction site, Xander introduces Buffy to Tony, the foreman. Xander's pulled a few strings to get Buffy a temporary job but the guys are less than happy to find out she's a girl. They're quietened when Buffy lifts a heavy beam over her shoulder with ease, and even has to be told to slow down by an hourly-paid worker who's worried he won't get paid enough if Buffy does all the work so quickly.

Inside the van, Andrew plays a set of panpipes, which grabs Buffy's attention for a second as she's getting a drink. Tony walks over and makes Buffy jump and she pushes him, seeing a demon behind him. Several of these demons appear, and when she kills them they disappear, apparently melting into the ground. Warren and Andrew fight over the binoculars, knocking the horn of the van and catching Buffy's attention. Xander walks over and asks Buffy what happened. Tony tells Xander he was just about to tell Buffy he was impressed with her work when she suddenly attacked him. Buffy takes Xander aside and tells him there were demons, but they melted away. Xander's distraught, and tells Buffy she should go see Giles right away - there could be a connection between this attack and the time fluctuations Buffy experienced earlier. Buffy decides to take up Giles' offer of employment at the Magic Box after all.

Warren laments Buffy's lack of focus career-wise as he listens in on her conversation with Anya. Jonathan works a spell and inside the Magic Box, the doorbell rings as a lady customer walks in. Giles tells Buffy that when running the store, he found it useful to pretend he was in the library sometimes - that way he concentrated on service, not sales, which equals more satisfied customers. Anya tells Buffy to go and sell the lady something and she walks over, being stopped on the way by a guy who asks her which of the scented candles on the table will create a romantic atmosphere. Buffy picks out the nicest smelling one for him before asking the lady how she can help her. The lady says she heard the Magic Box had a mummy hand, and Buffy goes to get it for her. When she finds it, the hand jumps at her and strangles, until she fights it off and stabs it with a nearby dagger. The lady customer refuses the hand because it's dead.

The doorbell rings and the lady walks in again, and Giles gives Buffy his speech about service again. As Jonathan rejoices at sticking Buffy in a loop, Anya tells Buffy to go to the lady again. Buffy stops on the way by the guy with the candles again, and then tells the lady she can't have the mummy hand. The lady insists that she must have the hand and she called just twenty minutes ago to confirm that the shop had one. Buffy has to go and get it, but fails to do so without killing the hand, and the riddle starts again. This time, Buffy has to prise the hand from the lady's neck, the customer's not satisfied and again the riddle starts over. Buffy tries to escape, rips the doorbell down, kills the lady customer, nothing works! Next, Buffy tells the customer there's no way to get that particular hand - but she can special order one. The customer leaves satisfied, and the riddle is solved. Giles congratulates her on her first sale while The Trio debate just how long it took for Buffy to finish the riddle, and Anya notices Buffy didn't charge for delivery, and says she'll take it out of her wage. Buffy puts her badge on the table and walk out.

Buffy and Spike drink together and get royally pissed, basically. Spike says rather than just leaving Giles to research, they should get out on the streets and talk to demons for their information on who or what is messing with Buffy. They go to the back room at a bar and Spike sits down to play cards, explaining to Buffy that the demons talk as they play. Buffy can't believe her eyes when she sees that they play for kittens! The Trio meanwhile are on the road, in search of Buffy, apparently not done messing with her. Spike cleans the guys out and they accuse him of cheating. They argue and it gets tense, Spike saying if there's a fight, it'll be against him and Buffy. Buffy says she's not getting into a bar-fight and knocks over the kitten's basket. Spike follows her out of the room and asks her what's wrong. She says everything - she feels too dumb for school, to strong for construction, and bored at the Magic Box. She thought Spike would help her but all he's done is cheat at kitten-poker. She storms out of the bar and Spike follows.

Outside, Spike finds Buffy watching the Trio's van. She says she's seen it before, and Jonathan sees Buffy approaching on the CCTV. A "demon" jumps out of the van and tells Buffy she cannot defeat him, because he's been testing her and knows her weaknesses. If she were sober, Buffy might sense this isn't actually a demon, but she takes a drunken swing at the "demon" and misses, then aims a kick at his chest and manages to hit him. He admits defeat and throws a smoke-bomb at his feet before running off, and Buffy and Spike both think he's exploded. The "demon" reaches the van and reverses his disguise spell - and we see it's Jonathan. Inside, Warren says they have a lot of information on Buffy now, and soon they could be a real threat to her. At home, after a lengthy barf-a-thon, Buffy tells Giles she thinks she's screwing up, and Giles says she's trying too hard to solve all her troubles at once. Buffy says the phone company say it's not hard enough, and to help, Giles writes her a cheque. Buffy refuses politely at first, then accepts, saying it's a little like having her mum back. She thanks him and tells him she feels safe in the knowledge that he'll always be around.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Tara's line "Once, Willow and I were watching Sponge Bob Square...", which gets cuts short because of The Trio's antics, refers to the Nickelodeon cartoon 'Sponge Bob Square Pants', about a sponge... called Bob... with square pants. In the basement, Buffy finds a magic ingredient labelled "Petrified Hamster", which has been referred to jokingly a couple of times already on the show. As a hamster-owner, I of course do not approve!

The Trio's scenes are even more humourous than in the last episode, and again make it hard to believe these three boys could be a serious threat to Buffy.

A major flaw in this episode occurs with Buffy travelling forward through time at increased speed. The people who bump into her must be incredibly clumsy, because from their point of view she'd be standing completely still! One last thing - Buffy's bwerrherrr noises each time she downs a shot drinking with Spike is so annoying it's impossible to describe.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "ALLTHEWAY" "Buffy.guide: All The Way"

@{b}All The Way@{ub}
6ABB06

"I was gonna pay for it... I mean, no, I was gonna nick it 'cause that's what I do..." - Spike.

It's the Halloween rush at the Magic Box and all the gang are helping out. While Anya skates around the shop, Xander tries in vain to entertain the children, dressed as a pirate. Willow gets mad at a customer who "thinks witches are all hairy moles and rotten teeth", but her heart is warmed by the sight of a little girl in a witch costume. While Willow takes the little girl for some candy, Dawn slips a coin-like trinket with a dragon on it into her back pocket. Anya asks Buffy to fetch some Mandrake Root from the basement, and she obliges. Down in the basement, she meets Spike, who's stealing seasoning for blood. He shows Buffy where the Mandrake Root is kept and then asks her if she'd like "a bit of the rough and tumble". Buffy's thrown and Spike says he's talking about patrolling! Buffy says maybe tomorrow. Back upstairs, Buffy sees Giles and suggests she should patrol. He says it's Halloween, there's no need because that's time-out for the undead. Meanwhile, a strange old man returns home, humming to himself, having been shopping. "Happy Halloween," he mutters, handling a large knife, "I'll give you something special this year."

The tired gang say goodnight to their last customers, when Anya tells them tomorrow is post-holiday clearance. The gang groan. Xander watches as Anya teaches Dawn the "dance of capitalist superiority" and decides it's time to annouce his and Anya's engagement to the group. The gang are mosty shocked, but Tara manages to congratulate them. They kiss, and Giles cleans his glasses so he doesn't have to watch. The guys put some music on and make drinks, and Buffy tells Xander and Anya she's sorry they couldn't have a big fancy party. Willow does a spell to decorate their surroundings and it looks great. Anya hugs Willow, and Giles and Tara share a look of concern. In the kitchen, Willow and Tara argue about Willow's reliance on magic. Tara says she chouldn't use magic to do something, when she can do it naturally. Willow asks Tara what her problem is, the magic is harmless. Dawn walks in and apologises for interrupting. Willow says it's okay, they're done, and walks out.

Out in the hall, Buffy tells Xander she can't believe he's getting married. Dawn tells Anya how lucky she is, then makes for the door, saying she'll see the gang tomorrow. Buffy asks where she's going, and Dawn says she's sleeping at Janice's, and Buffy had said she could go. Buffy doesn't want her to and looks to Gies for support, but he says it's not up to him. Buffy lets Dawn go, reluctantly. She meets up with Janice and they've both told their parents they're sleeping at the other's house. They go to the park and meet two jock meatheads, Zack, who's Janice's boyfriend, and Justin, a guy Dawn has "seen around" and likes. The foursome walk round the neighbourhood, letting down tires and egging houses. Dawn tells Janice she really likes Justin, and Zack asks Justin what he thinks of Dawn. "What about going all the way? Don't you think the moon and the stars look pretty tonight?" Janice catches up with the boys and says she's bored, but Zack wants to do one more house. Giles congratulates Xander and freaks him out with talk of down-payments and moving in together.

The last house the gang stop by is the old man Coldenbach's house. Zack tells Janice to go smash the pumpkins outside the house but she won't and Dawn volunteers. She holds the pumpkin high above her head and is about to bring it down when the old man opens the door and tells her she shouldn't do that, sometimes the pumpkins bite. He asks them in and tells them he used to design toys. Justin goes into the kitchen to help the old man with the treats. In the kitchen, old man takes a knife, but before he can do anything with it, Justin appears quite suddenly to his left... and he's a vamp! He sinks his fangs into his neck, as the old man's home-baked confectionery drops to the floor. He runs out and tells the girls they have to leave straight away, because he's swiped the old man's wallet. The girls run ahead while the two boys discuss whether to eat the girls or have sex with them first.

Xander is getting increasingly freaked by all the possibilities the future holds and steps out with Buffy for some air. Buffy tells Xander this is how life is supposed to be, and Xander feels a little better and heads inside. Buffy says she'll go and take Spike up on his offer of patrol. Justin gives Dawn some cash from the old guy's wallet and then puts his coat around her. They look into each other's eyes and Janice appears, asking where Zack is. Justin says he went to get the car; meanwhile, Zack has hijacked a car, sucking the occupant dry. Buffy, walking through town, sees a bite-mark in the driver's neck as she's taken away in an ambulance. Janice's mother calls Buffy's house and Giles answers; they soon realise Dawn and Janice aren't at either house, and Giles tells her he'll tell her if he hears anything, before breaking up the party and telling the gang the situation. He asks Willow and Tara to check downtown while Xander and Anya stay home in case Janice's mother calls again, then heads out to Spike's in the hope of finding Buffy there.

Janice kisses Zack and runs off into the woods - he pursues, vamp face on. In the car, Dawn asks Justin what he's expecting, and he says he wants to taste her. They kiss, and Dawn says wow. Justin realises it was Dawn's first kiss, and she's embarrassed, but they kiss again. Willow and Tara are searching for Dawn at a club, and frustrated by how long it's taking, Willow starts a spell. Tara asks what she's doing, and Willow explains that all she's going to do is momentarily shift everyone but 15-year-old girls into an alternate dimension! Willow can't understand why Tara sees a problem with this. She accuses Tara of talking to Giles about her behind her back. Tara asks Willow if she's just expected to keep quiet about it, and Willow says that'd be a good start. Tara storms off.

As Dawn and Justin kiss, he begins to turn vampish and nips her lip. He apologises and tells her how beautiful she is, and they carry on kissing. Buffy arrives at Spike's, telling him there's trouble and vamps about. He asks if Giles found her and realises Buffy doesn't know - he tells her Dawn's missing with Janice. They gear up and set out to find her. At the cemetery, Giles hears a girl scream, and runs over to the source of the scream - Janice, Zack's fangs deep in her neck. He knocks the vamp off and they fight, Giles getting beaten until he aims a solid kick at the vamp. Zack gets staked on the branch of a tree - what's the chances of that? Giles asks Janice where Dawn is but she doesn't know. Dawn sees that Justin is a vampire and jumps out of the car. He stops her and says she's different and special about her. He tells her it will only hurt for a second, and goes to bite her. Giles appears and tells him to let her go - suddenly headlights flip on all around - they are surrounded by vampires.

Spike arrives, followed by Buffy. Buffy asks Dawn why she was parking with a vamp, and Dawn says she didn't know he was a vamp - they just met. Hmm, wrong argument. The vamps are getting restless and the fight starts. Giles is pinned against his car by a vamp while Buffy dusts another, almost off-handedly. Justin tells Dawn he gets why there's somthing special about Dawn - it's because her sister's the slayer. Dawn kicks him in the nuts, as Buffy throws her stake over to Giles, and he dusts the two vamps who were giving him a hard time. Spike dusts one vamp who calls himself a rebel for fighting on Halloween, before getting jumped by another. Buffy kills another vamp by trapping his head in a car door. Justin jumps on top of Dawn and she says she thought he really liked him. He says he does, and she says she does too. He reaches down to bite her and he's suddenly dust - we see Dawn's staked him with an arrow.

Back at Buffy's, Buffy apologises to Xander for how the party ended, and saying goodnight, he and Anya leave. Tara and Willow go upstairs to bed - and they're still not happy with eachother. Buffy leaves Giles to take care of reprimanding Dawn, much to his dismay. Willow tells Tara she's sorry, but Tara says sorry won't cut it. She doesn't want to argue, she just wants to go to sleep. Willow walks over to her dresser and holds a small flower in her hand and she says the word "forget". She gets into bed and asks Tara if she's mad. Tara asks, "About what?"

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Willow has crossed another line here - she's now manipulating the lives of the people that love her in order to suit her own needs. Here she's taken away a part of Tara's life, which is awful even if it is a part that's upsetting her lover. The universe has become Willow's playground and she no longer knows right from wrong.

We're fully introduced to a different side to Dawn in this episode - her social life. However, in the past, what little snippets we've seen of her with friends have been with nice people like Kevin, who she sits next to in art class. Her "friends" here are beyond annoying, and you can't help but wonder what she's doing hanging out with such assholes.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "ONCEMOREWITHFEELING" "Buffy.guide: Once More, With Feeling"

@{b}Once More, With Feeling@{ub}
6ABB07

"They got the mustard out!!!"

7:00am: Buffy's alarm goes off. Rather than stopping the alarm, she picks it off the bedside table and looks at it curiously. Tara and Willow wake, Tara finding the strange flower Willow used in her spell under her pillow. She doesn't know what it is, and smiling, puts it with the pot pourri. At the Magic Box, Xander and Anya look through a bride-to-be's magazine. Giles walks over to Buffy with a large axe. Time to patrol, and it's a regular day in Sunnydale. Singing to herself in the graveyard, Buffy admits she's going through the motions, backed up by the creatures of the night, who notes she "hasn't got that swing." Buffy sings as she dispatches the all-singing all-dancing demons: @{i}"I can't even see if this is really me, and I just want to be alive." @{ui}

Buffy goes to the Magic Box next morning and casually asks the gang if any of them happened to break into song last night. It appears they did, and Giles gets thinking. He suggests, beginning to sing, that it's a dancing demon. But that dosn't seem right. Willow suggests they're stuck in someone's nightmare, Xander suggests witches until he sees the looks on Tara and Willow's faces. Anya theorises it's bunnies and suddenly goes into dodgy "rock-chick" overdrive and Giles and Willow get the books out before things get really ugly. Buffy asks the gang what they can't face together. They all sing along in unison, and reach the song's conclusion. After, they get researching and Buffy pops her head outside to see if they're the only ones affected. Apparently not - the people in the square are singing about washing.

Dawn arrives at the Magic Box and tells them they were singing at school too. She steals another object while the gang aren't looking. Tara and Willow go off, ostensibly to get a volume that will help them, but take a walk through the park, where Tara sings to Willow about how she's brought her out of herself. They get home, where Willow levitates Tara as she sings. At the Magic Box, Xander says he's pretty sure Tara and Willow aren't researching right now, if you catch his drift. Dawn says the whole singing and dancing thing is romantic - what could be wrong with it? Across town, as if in answer to Dawn's question, a man tapdances at great speed, obviously in distress. As he does so, smoke rises from his body and he bursts into flames. He drops dead as a demon watches from a few feet way, declaring this real entertainment.

In the morning, Anya and Xander find themselves singing about the niggling little things they don't like about each other but daren't mention - his snoring and supposed cowardice, her greed and hairy toes. Xander sings about how petrified he is and Anya says she's read about marriages that end in betrayal. They both conclude that they'll never tell; but of course they have. They find Giles in the street and tell him he has to stop what's happening. They walk past a woman who's singing to a traffic warden about a ticket he's giving her. Giles says Buffy is looking for leads but she doesn't seem so well - he feels helpless. Buffy drops by Spike's to ask him if he knows what's causing the singing and dancing, and he sings to her about the torment is causes him to be around her, yet he still follows her around. He begs her to let him "rest in peace" if she's not interested in him.

Tara stops by Dawn's room and says they know it's a demon of some sort causing the disturbance. Dawn says how glad she is that she and Willow made up after their fight over magic. Tara doesn't know what Dawn's talking about, since Willow worked a spell on her so she'd forget it. Tara looks at the flower and realises what Willow's done. She leaves Dawn alone in the house while she nips to the Magic Box for something. With Tara gone, Dawn goes to her jewelery box and looks at her stash of items from the shop. She puts a necklace on and starts to sing about whether anyone notices or cares, when three masked figures come and kidnap her. Dawn finds herself on a pool table, and tries to escape in a bizarrely choreographed ballet of sorts. The demon we saw before, watching the burning man, sings to Dawn and asks why she wants to go. He sings that he has been summmoned by her, and that he's far from being a good demon - the energy of the songs gets out of control.

He says Dawn will be his queen in the underworld, but she protests that she's 15 and that's illegal! Then she mentions Buffy being the Slayer and the demon has his three minions go fetch her - he wants to see Buffy burn. Giles and Buffy train, and he asks her if she's spoken to Dawn about the incident at Halloween. Buffy says she thought Giles had taken care of it, and asks what she would do without him. Giles sings that he's getting in the way of her independance by staying around, and feels like it would only do her good for him to leave. Tara finds the flower in a book - the Lethe's Bramble, used for mind control and memory-altering spells - and knows for sure that Willow has erased part of her memory. She and Giles then sing a duet about having to leave Willow and Buffy.

Spike bursts in with a minion under his arm and the minion tells Buffy all before running off. Giles tells Buffy to go out alone to retrieve Dawn. In the street, Buffy stands by a large oil can that's on fire and sings about the fire freezing her - when she touches it, it doesn't burn. She wants her fire, her focus back. @{i}"So I will walk though the fire." @{ui} Spike decides to go and help Buffy, as do the Scooby Gang, realising the jeopardy Buffy could be in, chorusing @{i}"We are caught in the fire, the point of no return, so we will walk through the fire, and let it burn." @{ui}

Buffy arrives at the music demon's hideout and kicks the door in. She asks him what his name is. He says he goes by many names. Buffy tells him she has a deal, that if she can't kill him, she'll go to hell in Dawn's place. What if he kills Buffy, he questions? Buffy says it won't help. He asks if she doesn't see life as a miracle. She sings her answer as the Scooby Gang arrive. She sings about how life is a song and we play our parts, then asks why her friends don't understand why she isn't jumping for joy about being alive. Of course, she knows the answer: @{i}"There was no pain. No fear, no doubt, 'till they pulled me out of Heaven. So that's my refrain, I live in Hell 'cause I've been expelled from Heaven. I think I was in Heaven. So give me something to sing about." @{ui}

Buffy starts dancing wildly, smoking as the music gets faster. Spike stops her, and tells her life is not a song. It's not bliss. You have to go on living. Dawn stands up and recalls Buffy's words to her up on the tower that fateful night: @{i}"The hardest thing in this world is to live in it." @{ui} The Musical demon guy congratulates them on a show-stopping number Willow tells him angrily to get out of town. He says he and Dawn will be on their way - after all, she summoned him. Dawn maintains that she didn't, and the demon points out that she is wearing his talisman. She says she found it on the floor at the Magic Box, but hasn't summoned anything. Xander owns up. He thought that singing and dancing would solve all their problems. The demon says he'll pass on making Xander his queen, happy to have caused them so much chaos, and sings his goodbye. @{i}"See you in Hell." @{ui}

Dawn's the first to start the bittersweet closing number. @{i}"Where do we go from here?" @{ui} Spike walks, followed by Buffy. He tells her to go back inside and finish the musical, but she wants to sing to him. He sings back, they walk towards each other and they share a kiss. The End.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Once again the 'grr...arg' of the Mutant Enemy animation has been changed - this time the 'grr...arg' is sang, opera-stylee.

I wrote this synopsis based on the extended version of the episode, as found on the video release. There's no way to do justice to this episode in text, you just have to see it. It's hard enough for me to keep stopping the video, because it whole thing just flows so well. It's difficult to avoid being pulled into the emotional gravity of the episode, despite the level of cheese (intentional or otherwise).

All the characters sang their parts and I was particularly impressed by Anthony Stewart Head's voice, especially on his duet with Amber Benson. The wobbliest voices are probably Sarah Michelle Gellar's and Nicholas Brendon's.

Willow's theory that they're all stuck in a kid's nightmare is a reference all the way back to the season one episode @{"Nightmares" LINK "NIGHTMARES"}, where a boy, who'd been beaten up by his baseball coach, caused the town's people to experience their own worst nightmares. Anya refers to the Chumash tribe, who featured in @{"Pangs" LINK "PANGS"}.

Spike's performance 'Rest In Peace' is not punk enough for his roots - the song's all stadium-rock and posturing.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "TABULARASA" "Buffy.guide: Tabula Rasa"

@{b}Tabula Rasa@{ub}
6ABB08

"Bloody Hell... Sodding, blimey, shagging, knickers, bollocks. Oh God - I'm English!" - Spike.

Buffy patrols the graveyard, and Spike appears. He wants to talk about their kiss but Buffy says it means nothing and won't happen again. A stake flies towards them out of nowhere and Buffy pushes Spike to the ground before it hits him. A shark-headed demon and two bodyguards appear and Shark-Head asks when he's going to receive the forty siamese kittens Spike owes him. Shark-Head says he doesn't want to see anyone get hurt - so he turns his back and lets his boys deal with it. Buffy's having none of that, but while she deals with them, Spike runs off. Shark-Head promises to catch up with Spike and talk some more another time.

At Xanders, Anya wonders aloud what it was like for Buffy in Heaven. Willow's guilt is indescribable, but Xander has simplified it - Buffy's good, Buffy's not dead, so that must be good. Instead of worrying about what they did then, they decide they should worry about making things easier for Buffy now. Willow suggests a spell but Tara predictably freaks out about the idea. Xander and Anya excuse themselves, and Tara tells Willow she knows she used the spell on her. Tara says Willow can't just change things to her own liking - especially not her own girlfriend. Willow says she'll go without magic for a month to prove she doesn't need it - Tara says go a week, then we'll see. Willow says that's easy, unaware of just how dependant she is becoming.

Giles tells Buffy of his plans to leave for England. She feels liek he's abandonning her and asks why now, but he says if he doesn't go now, she'll always turn to him, and she has to learn to handle things on her own. She says she can't do it alone, but Giles believes this is the right thing to do. At Buffy's, Tara and Dawn call for Willow from the bottom of the stairs, asking if she's ready yet. Willow appears, with a towel over her head - not quite ready, then. They go to wait in the car with Giles. Alone, Willow uses a spell to get herself ready to go super-quickly, and then works on an incantation to make Buffy and Tara forget their recent pains. She burns a Lethe's Bramble in the living room fireplace and touches a white crystal to the flame. She says that when the fire burns out and the crystal turns black, the spell will have been cast. She leaves the bag containing more brambles by the fire, and puts the crystal in her pocket.

At the Magic Box, Giles is about to tell the gang he's leaving when Spike bursts through the door wearing disturbing English countryman getup. He's in disguise, hiding from the debt collectors. While Spike has their attention, Willow checks the crystal - it's black. At Buffy's, we see a spark fly from the fireplace onto the bag of Lethe's Brambles and they begin to burn. Giles tells the gang he's leaving for England, indefinately. Buffy freaks out and says she can't do this. She says it feels like she's dying - and indeed, she drops to the floor on the spot. As do the rest of the gang - it appears Willow's unintentional over-brambling has had a more potent effect on the gang.

When they wake, it's dark and the gang remember nothing. Dawn's scared, but Buffy tells her not to be afraid - she doesn't know anyone here either. Dawn asks who she is, and Buffy doesn't know. None of the gang remember a thing. Giles suggests they've all been drinking, but they see no booze. Willow realises they're in a magic shop, and Buffy says maybe that's what's happened - a magic spell. Giles says that's utter rubbish. Magic! Ha! The very thought! Giles and Spike both freak out when they realise they're English - then Spike suggests he's Giles' son. Willow, Xander, Giles and Tara check their Wallets for ID, and find out their names from there. Buffy's finds Dawn's name on her sister's necklace. Spike looks for his name in his jacket, finds the name Randy, and freaks at Giles for calling him Randy Giles. Willow finds another name on her jacket - it's Harris, since she borrowed the coat from Xander. They theorise that they're boyfriend and girlfriend, since they woke up next to each other.

Anya figures out her name because she has a key that fits a lock on the counter, and some forms nearby say the shop belongs to Rupert and Anya. Buffy still has no idea what her name is, and she chooses to name herself Joan. Dawn laughs at Buffy's name and they're soon arguing with a fluidity that can mean only one thing - they're sisters. Buffy suggests they go to the hospital to find out what's happened to them. They open the door to find the two vampires who're after Spike. Not recalling having ever come face-to-face with vampires before, the gang scream and hide. Willow and Xander find a trapdoor to the sewer, and the gang start towards it just as the vamps burst in. One vampire hassles Spike for his kittens, of which he knows nothing, while the other restrains Buffy. She breaks away and instinctively stakes the vamp hassling Spike. He turns to dust and the other vamp makes his exit, promising to be back, while the gang try and make sense of what they've seen.

Outside, Shark-Head says to his men that the humans will turn on Spike soon, and if not, they'll just burn the place down. Buffy tells the gang to go down the trapdoor to the sewer while she and Spike run for it above the ground. Giles and Anya want to stay at the shop and try some spells. Buffy and Spike burst out, and a vamp soon catches him; he turns around, puts his own vamp face on, and punches him. Buffy sees Spike's vamp face and freaks out. The gang meet a vamp in the sewer, as Anya and Giles try to find the right book - the first spell Anya tries conjures up a bunny, and she hasn't forgotten her fear of those! Spike runs after Buffy and she tells him to look at himself - he's a vamp. He concludes that since he's fighting on Buffy's side, he must be a noble vampire, one with a soul.

Anya sticks with the same book in the hope she can banish all the bunnies she's made, but it's not working - unless the magic shop is going to become a pet shop. The gang manage to hide from the vamp in the sewers, and he walks past oblivious. Tara and Willow show an obvious attraction to one another, but don't know why. Buffy and Spike are approaches by Shark-Head's vamps and manage to dust most of them. Anya and Giles argue about the spells and Anya hits him over the head with a book. He says there's little wonder he's leaving her, and shows her the one-way ticket to Heathrow he's found in his jacket. Down in the sewer, another vamp finds the gang and Xander fights with him. Giles finds the right spell to get rid of the bunnies and monsters Anya has summoned and they apologise to each other... and kiss. In the sewer, the vamp knocks Willow on top of Tara, her black crystal falling on the floor. Xander grabs the vamp's attention again and they fight. Dawn throws Xander a stake and as the vamp leaps for him, he's dusted. Tara and Willow look into each other's eyes, close to a kiss, as Xander gets up and steps on the crystal - it shatters and turns white again, the spell broken.

Tara pushes Willow up as she recalls her life; Anya and Giles are still mid-snog as their memories are restored. Buffy's so stunned by the return of her memory that she allows herself to get kicked in the head. In the sewer, all eyes are on Willow and her crystal - but Tara cannot look her in the eye. Spike dusts the last of the vamps and Shark-Head appears. He offers to waive Spike's debt, since he obviously doesn't have a problem standing up against his bailiffs. When he leaves, Spike hold out his hand to Buffy, who's still on the floor. She gets up without his help and walks off into the night. Tara packs her things away as Willow slumps dejectedly in another room, and when she leaves, Dawn will not hug her but runs off into the house. Giles sits lost in his thoughts on his plane to England. Spike finds Buffy some time later at the Bronze, and she turns away from him. He walks off, but they end the night kissing again, passionately, mentally miles away from their surroundings at the Bronze.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Spike's "Randy Giles" outburst is among the funniest moments the series has ever produced. Watching the gang's reaction to the vampires, having had their previous knowledge of vamps erased, is brilliant, particularly Xander, who flails his arms and screams like a girl, before actually praying and begging for his life.

It's an episode full to the brim with continuity references and in-jokes such as Anya's rabbit-fear, and Willow's recurring like "I think I'm kinda gay". The character interaction is interesting - Dawn refers to Xander as Alex. Pair-bonds appear to have survived the mental blackout, except for Xander's with Anya, who gets left at the Magic Box on the assumption that she's married to Giles, so the opportunity never rises for Xander and Anya's chemistry to mingle.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "SMASHED" "Buffy.guide: Smashed"

@{b}Smashed@{ub}
6ABB09

"How've you been?" - Buffy.
"Rat. You?" - Amy.
"Dead." - Buffy.

Out on patrol, Buffy stops what she thinks is a vampire attack, but turns out to be a robbery. She returns the stolen handbag to its owner and tells her and her male friend to run. The robbers attack Buffy but she holds them off and suddenly Spike dives in, thinking they're vamps. Buffy shouts "No!" and, distracted, lets go of the one robber she was holding, and they both get away. Buffy's her usual stand off-ish self and Spike tells her she's a tease. Meanwhile, Willow has nothing to do and plays with Amy Rat. Suddenly realising she has just the required spell to return Amy to her previous human self, Willow gets to work right away, and soon human Amy is sitting naked on the bed. Freaked out, having been a rat for three solid years, she can only scream.

The Trio steal a diamond from Sunnydale's museum. When the security guard approaches them, they freeze him with a freeze ray. Willow gets Amy some hot-chocolate, but she's still on-edge. To Willow's horror, Amy tells Willow she feels like she'd been in the cage for weeks - and Willow has to break it to her that she's missed the prom - and, in fact, high school finished two and a half years ago. Buffy gets home and asks Willow how she is. Amy's nowhere to be seen. Buffy tries to confide in Willow but doesn't get very far before Amy walks back into the room. Amy goes to the kitchen for some cookies - anything without cheese. Willow tells Buffy it will be nice to have another witch friend around. Downstairs, Amy says she was sorry to hear about Joyce. She and Buffy marvel at all the weird stuff that's happened since she's been away. Amy shows Buffy a news report about a guy being frozen solid at the museum, and Buffy decides she should investigate.

The security guard has to be wheeled out on a sack-cart. Buffy finds Spike at the scene and she tells him she only kissed him because she was depressed about Giles's departure for England. Spike tells her she should stop kidding herself, and reaches for her as she turns away, calling him a "thing". She hits him and he hits her back - and feels no pain! He quickly feigns migraine, and Buffy's taken in by it, before she walks off. Sure he is back to his old self, he goes out to get feeding. He follows a young woman into an alley and tries to bite her, but finds he can't. The next day, Tara takes Dawn out and tells her over a super-super-size milkshake that she'll always be there for her, even though she and Willow have split up. At the Magic Box, Willow uses magic to search through the internet at high speed for information on the frozen guy case. He'll live, but he's still unconscious. Willow tells the guys that a diamond was stolen last night.

Willow tells the guys she thinks this time apart from Tara will help them sort through their problems. The Trio are about to get into phase two of their secret plan involving the diamond, when Spike pays them a visit and threatens to snap their 5" Boba Fett limited edition statue if Warren doesn't take a look at his chip. Willow gets home and finds Amy, who's bored and restless. She wants to go out and party, and convinces Willow to join her. Warren assures Spike his chip is in full working order, and Spike realises there must be something wrong with Buffy if he can het her without his chip kicking in. Tara drops Dawn by her house and stays to watch her while the others get back. At the Bronze, two boys approach Amy and asks her to dance, leaving Willow alone. When she returns, they appear again and get pushy. The two witches decide if the boys must dance, then dance they will - in a flash, the guys are dancing semi-naked in cages at the side of the stage.

Buffy, Xander and Anya's research has proved fruitless. Conversation turns to Willow and her over-use of magic; they all agree to keep an eye on her. Anya doesn't think it will do Willow any good at all to have Amy around to do magic with. Spike calls Buffy and asks her to meet him at the cemetary, alone. She hangs up and tells the guys he just wanted to patrol, but she said no. They leave the shop a little later, and soon after Buffy splits away from Xander and Anya, Spike appears. He annoys her enuogh to hit him, and he hits back, and lets her see that there's no pain. He tells her she came back wrong. They fight, and Buffy tells him he's either wrong, or lying. Their fight moves into a disused, dusty building. At the Bronze, Willow and Amy get bored of the band playing and with a twitch of Willow's nose, suddenly it's an all-girl pop-punk band on stage. They make people shrink or grow, let sheep loose in the crowd... but are soon bored. But it's way too early to go home.

Buffy and Spike's fight gets increasingly brutal - as they throw each other around, chunks come out of brick walls. Spike says Buffy is screwed up, doesn't fit in anywhere, and Buffy tells him to take a look at himself - he can't be a vamp or a human, he just follows her round. Buffy pushes Spike up against a wall, and it cracks. They kiss again, as the building begins to collapse, and they fall through the floor into the cellar, where they spend a night of passion, as the building collapses around them.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Again a little flaw in the logic of the program shows up. In past episodes, it's been said that Spike's chip works like a lie detector, and is based on signals his brain sends out when he @{i}intends @{ui} to harm a human. So what happens if Spike jumps for a human in the full belief that it's a demon? He should be able to do it without feeling any pain. But here he can't. Likewise he shouldn't be able to hit Buffy, even if her death has somehow changed her. I apparently cannot help being pedantic, but what the heck.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "WRECKED" "Buffy.guide: Wrecked"

@{b}Wrecked@{ub}
6ABB10

"You're bent" - Buffy.
"Yeah, it made you scream, didn't it?" - Spike.

Tara and Dawn wake up to the morning cartoons - no-one's been home yet. Not Willow, Buffy or Amy. Buffy and Spike wake, and Buffy freaks out. For a start, she can't remember the building falling down. Spike tries to get her to stay a little longer, but she won't and needs to get home to see if Dawn was okay. She's close to staying anyway, when Spike tells her he knew the only thing better than killing a Slayer would be having sex with one. Buffy freaks out and then tells Spike he's just "convenient". She tells him that if he tells anyone about their night together, she will kill him. Willow and Amy get home before Buffy, and Amy tells Tara about how powerful Willow is, and about how she was messing with dimensions last night, to Tara's obvious disapproval. Tara leaves and meets Buffy on the way out.

Dawn sees Buffy's bruises and scrapes and asks if she's ok, and Buffy says there's nothing to worry about. Willow and Buffy feel bad tht they hadn't checked with each other to make sure Dawn wasn't alone in the house, but everyone's okay now so thay decide it's no big deal. Buffy and Willow go to bed, while Amy leaves for home; Dawn's left with nothing to do. Up in her room, Willow tries to close the curtains with magic but finds she's all magic'd out. Xander, Anya and Buffy still have no idea who froze the security guard at the museum, and are still assuming it's a demon. Buffy finds herself making excuses for Willow's behaviour because of guilt over her own strange Spike-doing behaviour.

In the evening, Amy and Willow walk through town and Amy tells Willow about a warlock called Wreck who can do spells with hardly any "burn-out factor". Amy takes Willow to his hide-out, a building cloaked so it can't be detected. Wreck says Willow gives off vibes - she's incredibly powerful. Willow says Amy told her he might be able to help her build her magic stamina, and Wreck asks Willow what she can do for him. She offers him money but he doesn't want that. He approaches her and promises he won't hurt her, he'll just take a little tour, then places his hand just above her heart. There's a flash of light and both Wreck and Willow appear to be in the throes of both pain and ecstacy. When he stops, he tells Willow she tastes like strawberries. Willow doesn't open her eyes, she's so blissed out. Later, she lies on the ceiling, looking down at the floor, watching as it changes and shifts into a park-like scene, and she sees a demon dragging a woman into the bushes. The demon re-emerges and roars at Willow and she falls back to the floor, screaming. On the floor, half-conscious, Willow has visions of the Bronze and the Magic Box, and when she finally gets up, she finds herself at home. She cries in the shower, and afterwards blows up one of Tara's dresses with magic, snuggling up with the imaginary Tara.

Later, Willow tells Dawn how sorry she is about the other night and asks her if she wants to see a movie tonight. Later on, after they've gone, Buffy arrives home and finds Amy stealing ingredients. Amy tells her she and Willow have a problem in that they can't get enough of magic, and Willow's probably at Wreck's right now. Sure enough, on the way to the movie with Dawn, Willow stops by Wreck's. Leaving Dawn in the waiting room, Willow heads in to see Wreck and promises she'll only be a minute. More than an hour later, Dawn's still waiting. Wreck has Willow suspended in the air. She sees herslef in space, and suddenly there's a big flash, and the demon appears again, with his female victim in his arms. Willow screams and Wreck laughs. Buffy stops by Spike's and tells him that Willow has gone to see Wreck with Dawn. Spike says the warlock is incredibly dangerous and they set out to find him. Having waited two hours for Willow to emerge, Dawn heads towards Wreck's room but Willow comes out before she reaches the door. Time for the movie! Dawn can't believe it and tells Willow they've missed the movie and she just wants to go home.

Spike and Buffy, meanwhile, argue as they continue their search. Spike insists things have changed since last night. Buffy says she's disgusted with herself, that's all. Spike knows Buffy needs him - like tonight. Willow and Dawn hear a noise, and the demon from Willow's visions appears in front of them. He says Willow summoned him, then takes a swipe at Dawn, cutting her face. Dawn kicks him and they run, but the demon gains on them. Willow spies a car and uses magic to open the locks and they jump in. Willow starts the car, and drives using magic. Willow looks behind to watch the demon, and misdirects the car, driving it straight into a pillar.

Dawn's the first to crawl from the wreck, clutching her arm. The demon appears and Dawn dives under the car to hide from him, but he drags her out, her knuckles scraping on the ground. She throws dust from the road in his eyes, and he in turn sends her flying along the road, landing a good few yards away. Buffy appears before the demon can do her any further harm, and fights the demon while Spike checks Dawn. The demon slams Buffy against the ceiling and she falls to the floor. Willow appears and manages to take the demon out with her magic. Willow asks if Dawn's okay and Buffy tels her to back off. Apologising desperately to Dawn, she gets a slap in return. Willow falls to the floor, crying and saying she's sorry as Buffy, Dawn and Spike look back.

Spike goes on ahead with Dawn and Buffy turns back to Willow and tells her to get up. Willow tells Buffy she can't stop - she's out of control. At home, Curled up in a blanket, Willow tells Buffy she's giving up magic - it drove Tara away and now Dawn's been hurt - her arm is fractured. Magic made Willow feel good, but it was dangerous and wrong, and hurts people. Buffy agrees, translating the words to her own predicament with Spike. Willow says it's not worth it, it has to stop. It's over. That night, Willow tosses and turns in bed, going cold-turkey, unable to calm herself down, as Buffy sits on her own bed, a cross in hands.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

I'm not actually sure Wreck is called Wreck, but that's what it sounds like, and it fits in with the episode's title. Wreck's scenes make good Giles's warning to Willow that there are people out there as powerful as she is, but they're not people she'd like to meet (see @{"Flooded" LINK "FLOODED"}).

Willow's addiction and its symptoms parallel those of heavy narcotics; it has taken over Willow's entire existance, and she's apparently powerless against it - witness her fairly pathetic display when she falls on the floor begging for forgiveness, and the second-to-last scene, in which she writhes and shakes through the night - scenes reminiscent of Trainspotting, only not as disturbing. Willow sums it up herself: "It took me away from myself. I was free."

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "GONE" "Buffy.guide: Gone"

@{b}Gone@{ub}
6ABB11

"You penis!" - Jonathan.

Buffy and Dawn are helping Willow pack away all her magic stuff so that she won't give in to temptation. Dawn's upset that they can't even keep candles, but Buffy insists it's necessary. Tara left a couple of crystals behind, and Buffy promises she'll make sure Tara gets them. Warren finally finishes working on a weapon of some sort and places the stolen crystal in its cradle on the gun. To test it, he fires at a swivel-chair nearby and the chair becomes invisible, then flips it into reverse and makes the chair visible once more, much to the horror of Jonathan, who's sitting on it at this moment in time.

It's nearly time for school and Dawn's running late, but she shows little concern. Still in a sling, she's pissed at Willow and Buffy for what happened. Spike bursts in looking for his cigarette lighter and Buffy pretends she hasn't seen it. When Willow leaves, Buffy tells him his excuse to see her is lame. He walks up to her and tells her how much he loves her hair, and she tries to hit him over the head with a kitchen utensil. He stops her and then touches her, and she tells him to stop even though she's enjoying it. Xander walks in, here to drop Dawn off for school, and laughs, telling Spike he's really never going to get with Buffy. Buffy leaves the room with Xander to fetch Dawn, telling Spike to let himself out. On the way out of the front door, Dawn meets a social worker, Doris Kroeger, who tells Buffy she's here for their appointment.

Inside, Buffy tries to get rid of Spike, but nothing works until she mentions her guest is from social services. Spike decalres Buffy a great mother, then leaves. Buffy fails to make a great impression on the lady - first she says there's just she and Dawn living here, before Willow calls from upstairs saying she's going to get some sleep. Then the lady finds some of Willow's magic ingredients, still in a box waiting to be moved out. It looks like skunk to her, and she leaves, saying she's seen enough - she's going to recommend immediate probation on her report today. If things don't improve, they'll take Dawn away from Buffy. After she leaves, Buffy finds Spike's still here. She tells him to go, and he puts his hand in her pocket, pulling out his lighter, then leaves. Buffy's left frustrated and pissed off, and in her bedroom, she chops off a few inches of her golden hair, then makes her way to the hairdresser's to get it fixed up.

The Trio are out on a mission - they're going to make themselves invisible and walk into a bikini-waxing shop. As they're about to go in, the notice Buffy across the street. Jonathan and Andrew fight over the inisibility gun and accidentally zap Buffy, along with a fire hydrant and a dumpster. Buffy walks into the Magic Box and confuses Anya and Xander for a while before telling them she's invisible. Buffy tells them what a horrible day she's had so far, and that she didn't see anything suspicious before she became invisible. Xander says they have to figure out how she became invisible to find out how to change her back, but Buffy's having way too much fun to concentrate on that, and leaves to "clear her head". Anya and Xander wonder if Willow had something to do with it, and Xander asks Willow, who gets upset that he thinks she would jump off the wagon so soon, and goes out for a walk. Warren meanwhile works on the gun to fix up the fried wiring, and the Trio wonder about the threat Buffy could be to them now she's invisible.

Buffy wreaks havoc on the streets of Sunnydale, stealing people's hats and driving off in patrolmen's vehicles. Buffy heads to the social services office to play some tricks on the social worker. She makes her coffee mug move and dance, then whispers "Kill! Kill them, Doris! Kill them all!" Doris goes to freshen up and when she gets back, her boss says he's got time to look through the Summers case with her now. When Doris hands him the file, he finds it's filled with sheet after sheet, each line saying "All work and no play make Doris a dull girl." Doris tells her boss it was "the voice" and he tells her to take the rest of the day off and see her doctor. He'll put someone else on the case. Buffy leaves, whistling to herself. Xander finds Willow downtown with a can of spaypaint, painting the invisible dumpster. Willow's also found tire marks, and black paint on the invisible fire hydrant; since it's not invisible, the scrape happened after the hydrant was made invisible. Xander guesses it's the same strange van Buffy's been seeing around. Xander finds something else on the ground. Willow sprays it and it turn out to be a traffic cone. She tells Xander to take it to the Magic Box so he and Anya can figure what kind of spell has been used, while she tracks down the van and its origins.

Spike's hungry and goes over to his fridge for a drink, when Buffy walks in, and spooks him. She throws him against the wall and rips open his shirt before doing something we can't see but makes him realise it's Buffy. At the Magic Box, Anya reaches out for the traffic cone and it disintegrates in her hands. On the assumption that what's happening to the traffic cone will happen to Buffy, Xander goes off in search of Buffy. Jonathan and Andrew convince Warren that they must reverse Buffy's invisibility before her molecular structure breaks down. Spike's having sex with the still-invisible Buffy when Xander walks in looking for her. Spike pretends he's doing exercises, but Xander's convinced he's just witnessed Spike masturbating. He tells Spike that Buffy's invisible and Spike pretends not to know where she is, although Buffy messes with Spike while Xander speaks. Xander tells Spike he should get a girlfriend and leaves.

Spike's annoyed at Buffy, who thinks it's perfect that she's invisible and no-one knows she's with Spike. He says the only reason she's here is because she's invisible and doesn't have to live by the rules - when her friends switch her back, she'll surely be gone. Spike tells her to leave, because he wants all of her. At a cyber-cafe, Willow searches through a database for information and comes dangerously close to using magic when the computer's progress bar stops - but before she does, it finishes and the information's up on-screen. Buffy gets home to find the house empty and goes for a snack. Dawn comes in and freaks out that Buffy isn't doing more to find out who did this to her. Buffy finds a message from Xander on her phone, telling her about the dangers of what she's been subjected to. When the message is finished, she can only say "Wow".

Willow tracks the mysterious van to a house and goes down into the basement - sure enough it's The Trio's hideout. She looks round and finds the crystal in the gun, but before she has time to think, the invisible Trio grab her and make her their hostage. Buffy's about to go out to find Xander when the phone rings and on the other end, a voice Buffy finds familiar but can't pinpoint (it's Jonathan) tells her she must come alone to meet them, if she doesn't want anything bad to happen to Willow. She meets them in a video arcade and they tell her they're going to make her visible again. Buffy lets them fire at her, but Willow realises the gun is on the wrong setting and that Warren is trying to kill her. Warren knocks Willow out with the gun and Buffy throws an air-hockey paddle at Warren. They fight, and Buffy realises one of them is Jonathan just as Willow gets up and fires the gun at them. She uncloaks Warren, and then Andrew, who Buffy doesn't recognise, although she remembers his brother Tucker. The Trio claim to be Buffy's "arch-nemesis-es-is" and make their getaway, Jonathan's smoke-bomb routine ruined by the fact that the door's locked and it takes them a few seconds to get through.

Willow tells Buffy how hard the day has been, without magic to aid in her research. Buffy's also realised something today - when she heard Xander's message, she was scared about dying. Not so long ago, she would have welcomed it.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Xander's line "Have you been feeling ignored lately?" is another ancient Buffy reference, to the episode @{"Invisible Girl / Out Of Sight, Out Of Mind" LINK "INVISIBLEGIRL"}. Buffy's line "I'm invisible girl" may also be a reference to the ambiguity of that episode and its actual title.

The tune Buffy whistles as she leaves the social services department is the opening number from the musical episode @{"Once More, With Feeling" LINK "ONCEMOREWITHFEELING"}.

Buffy's invisible antics are a little unimaginative, apart from the hillarious coffee-mug caper at the social services office. When she plays with Spike in Xander's presence, there was much more room for hilarity than was exploited. Now, imagine if you will, she had made Spike appear to have an erection because of Xander's presense. @{i}That @{ui} would have been funny. Oh my god. I apologise. Maybe the show's new-found sense of sexual innuendo is having a bad effect on me. And what's that about anyway? The show has become increasingly adult as time has passed. The original audience is growing older of course, so I guess that's the main reason. It's just - look back at the first season and how innocent they are! And now with the genitalia. Oh my god.

