@endnode

@node "ASYOUWERE" "Buffy.guide: As You Were"

@{b}As You Were@{ub}
6ABB15

"It's going to be our perfect, perfect day if I have to kill all our guests and half this town to do it!" - Anya.

After a shift cleaning down grills at the Double Meat Palace, Buffy fights a vamp in the graveyard. He tries to bite her and then suddenly recoils - what's that smell? Buffy explains she's been working and the vamp says, if it's all the same, he doesn't want to fight her tonight. For calling her stinky, he gets a long-distance staking. Outside her house, she meets Spike, who isn't put off in any way by the smell wants to get cosy with her. Buffy says she should get inside to see Dawn, but he talks her round and the bag of food Buffy's brought home is dropped on the floor while she kisses Spike against a nearby tree.

Inside, Dawn asks Buffy if she's had a rough night, and complains about having to eat Double Meat Palace food yet again. Willow asks Buffy if she had a rough night too - there's a grass stain on her back. Willow asks Buffy if she wants to hit the Bronze with her and Dawn but she says she's had enough "action" for the night. She tells them to go out and have fun. Xander and Anya's wedding is in one week! At the Bronze Xander's nervously wolfing down potato chips and generally just freaking out. Dawn notices Willow's extraordinarily happy and it's all because she's talking with Tara again. At home, Buffy scrubs the stain from her coat and then falls asleep in the living room. She's woken up by the sound of the garbage truck outside - and she's forgotten to leave their waste out for them. Inside, Buffy reads a letter from the college - her re-application has been rejected.

At work, Riley drops in for a burger. He's tracked down some big evil to Sunnydale and he needs her help - right now. Buffy takes off her hat and they walk out of the store together. Riley apologises for dropping in so suddenly and says the demons he's tracking - called Sovalti - are big breeders and incredibly fierce. If their numbers aren't kept down, they will breed and possibly wipe out human life. Just then, they find one, and try fighting it, but they stand no chance - it knocks them aside and escapes. They pursue and shoot it with a dart, but it still gets away. They jump into Riley's car and hit the road - Buffy changes on the way into a black-ops uniform. Meanwhile, Xander and Anya are stuck in traffic on their way to the airport to pick up several relatives from both sides. Buffy and Riley trace the Sovalti to a large dam and absail down together. They knock the demon out with difficulty and end up face to face, looking in each other's eyes. Just then a woman in combat gear appears and jokes: "What exactly are you doing with my husband?!"

Buffy's taken aback and Riley says he was going to tell her as soon as they got a minute. Riley introduces them - Riley's wife is called Sam. The demon gets up and Sam goes in first, followed by Riley. Then Buffy dives in and snaps the demon's neck. Only then do the agents tell her they didn't want the demon dead. Sam cuts the demon open and observes the insides, then says they're too late. They head to Buffy's house and Riley promises to fill Buffy in on everything. Xander and Willow greet Riley with warmth when they get to Buffy's, but Willow whispers in Buffy's ear that as her friend she's willing to hate Sam with all her might. Riley and Sam explain that they're been tracking the demon through central America, trying to catch it as it left a trail of destruction and death in its wake. It's come to the Hellmouth to spawn - and judging from Sam's peek at the dead demon's insides, they think it's already done so. But unfortunately they can't trace the demon to its nest now - since Buffy killed the demon. They believe the Sovalti offspring are going to be sold to a foreign military and that money has been exchanged. There's a dealer in town known only as The Doctor, and he may be involved.

Sam suggests Willow uses a locator spell, which upsets her and she leaves the room, explaining she got addicted. The gang decide Sam and Buffy will go and look for the nest, while Riley hits the crypts and Willy's bar. Xander will stay home with Dawn. Sam finds Willow and apologises, and tells her she's never met anyone with enough strength to quit magic before. Later, searching for the nest, Sam tells Buffy she feels a little intimidated by Buffy - she's legendary as the Slayer and as a person - it took Riley a year to get over Buffy. Buffy admits wishing things has turned out differently. They approach Spike's place and Buffy says she should go in alone, so Sam heads back to find Riley. Buffy goes to Spike for information, and they end up having sex. They fall asleep, and Buffy's just stirring when Riley bursts in. He look unimpressed, but he's here to attend to business - Spike is the doctor. Riley demands Spike show him where the eggs are, while Buffy comes to the conclusion that it can't be Spike - he's too incompetent.

Riley's determined, and he drops downstairs with Buffy and Riley following. Sure enough, they find the eggs. Spike hasn't kept them frozen like he should have, and they begin to hatch. Spike runs off, upset when Buffy tells him to stop playing games ("All you've ever done is play me!"). Buffy and Riley struggle against the hatchlings, which attack as soon as they're born. Unable to shoot them or fight against them, Buffy and Riley get back upstairs and throw a grenade down at the demons, wiping them out. Anya and Xander hide in the bathroom while their relatives cause a noise downstairs, and Anya's annoyed that Xander thinks Riley and Sam's marriage is better than theirs. Xander explains that he has no idea what Riley and Sam's actual wedding was like - the wedding is not the marriage. Anya understands. Riley tells Buffy that he and Sam are heading to Nepal next. Riley says that by mission parameter's he's done, but he has been authorized to execute the doctor, if Buffy wants. Buffy says no. Buffy compares Riley and Sam's wedded bliss to her current messy life, but Riley says it was hard for him too - seeing Buffy again. Buffy says she's sorry for what happened between them, but Riley already knew.

The gang come out with Sam, now all on good terms - Sam and Willow have swapped e-mail addresses, and Dawn gives Riley a hug goodbye. Xander salutes Riley and soon Riley and Sam are off in the helicopter. "What a bitch," Willow tells Buffy, then goes inside with the rest of the gang. Spike wanders through the charred remains of his crypt when Buffy arrives. She tells him she wants him, but she can't love him, she's just using him. She keeps being weak, but realises she has to be strong about this. For the first time, Buffy addresses Spike using his first name: "I'm sorry, William."

@{b}Notes@{ub}

The scenes with Buffy's domestic chores are well-dressed with plenty of awful looking mops and brushes and the like. I can only guess the scene with her cleaning her coat is in the basement; it's not the usual posh Summers kitchen, which underlines the point.

Does the scene where Buffy and Riley descend the dam seem familiar? It's a total 007 moment - quite literaly. Check out 'GoldenEye'.

Buffy's line about guns, "These things... never useful", is a deja-vu inducing moment - actually a continuity reference to @{"Flooded" LINK "FLOODED"}, where a security guard tries to shoot @{"M'Fashnik" LINK "ABOUTMFASHNIK"} during a bank robbery.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}

@endnode

@node "HELLSBELLS" "Buffy.guide: Hell's Bells"

@{b}Hell's Bells@{ub}
6ABB16

"They were supposed to be the light at the end of my tunnel. I guess they were a train." - Buffy

Willow and Buffy freak out about their bridesmaid dresses - they're frankly hideous - and Buffy says it's funny that Xander's relatives fell for their story that Anya's demon relatives were circus-freaks. Anya walks in and says how beautiful they look, calling this the happiest day of her life, as thunder booms outside. At Xander's place, Xander looks for his cuff-links while his asshole father insults one of Anya's guests. Xander eventually finds his cuff-links on his cousin Carol's ears. Meanwhile, downtown, an old man materialises out of nowhere and sets off walking, smiling to himself.

Buffy helps Xander into his tight clothes - too many potato chips! - and gets all teary as she does his bow-tie. Buffy tells Xander how happy she is for him and Anya, and they give her hope. Willow and Tara try and get Anya into her dress, laughing between themselves as she runs through her strange improvised vows. When they're done, Tara and Willow stand back and try to look impressed. Anya tells them how happy she is that she gets to be with her best friend forever. At the mariage venue, Dawn greets the arriving guests, including Halfrek, who she's less than pleased to see. Spike shows up with a date - some random girl he's brought along in the hope of making Buffy jealous. Clem, Rory, Xander's mother and another demon discuss the implications of raising children in a demonic or otherwise environment, while Mr. Harris gets increasingly drunk at the bar. Among the crowd, the old man we saw earlier is looking around for someone.

Buffy says Xander's ready, so he goes out to meet and greet. Buffy's taken aback to hear from Dawn that Spike's brought a date. In the lobby, Xander's overwhelmed by all the wellwishers and the old man pulls him aside, telling him he must listen - he cannot get married today. Xander asks the old man who he is and he identifies himself as Xander Harris - Xander from the future. He says he's come back to warn him but Xander is unconvinced. Old man Xander takes out a shiny sphere from his pocket and it lights up. "I'll prove it to you", he says, and takes Xander somewhere more quiet. Mr. Harris almost starts bar-fight before Buffy takes him away for a strong cup of coffee. Old man Xander asks Xander to look into the globe, so he can see and feel what his older self has experienced.

Xander stares into the ball and finds himself a few years older, sitting on the sofa watching a game, with a beer in his hand. He calls out for Anya. A young girl demon, Sarah, runs into the room, being chased by her brother, Josh, a human child, who's calling her a weirdo. His and Anya's children. Anya tells Xander she's going out to do a make-over party and earn some money. Xander can't work because his back is shot - from fighting demons with Buffy. "It didn't save her did it? All it did was ruin our lives." Anya leaves, and Xander shouts that he hopes she crashes in her stupid pink car. Xander next finds himself at a restaurant, the children now teenagers. He's drinking heavily again. Sarah complains about the place, Josh cals her a demonic freak, and she asks Xander to make him shut up. Xander says perhaps she should talk to her mother about it. Anya says Xander's had too much to drink, and Xander tells her she should talk to @{i}her @{ui} daughter. Sarah storms off.

Next, Xander and Anya are in their fifties, and Anya says she should have left him. Xander agrees - maybe he would have got some "touch" in the last twenty years. It transpires that Anya had an affair, and she says it happened because Xander wouldn't come near her after Buffy's death. Anya tells Xander he was born to be a bitter, angry old man, and if she hadn't married him she wouldn't have hated herself for the last thirty years. Xander picks up a frying pan and dives at Anya - and then suddenly he's back in our time, with Old Man Xander. Xander asks his older self what happened and if Anya is okay, and the old man replies simply that if Xander pulls out today, he'll hurt her less than he would in the future. Buffy finds Spike and admits to him that it hurts seeing him with someone else. Spike asks if he wants them to go, and Buffy says they can stay, that she deserves the pain. Spike says she doesn't, and decides they'll leave. Spike asks Buffy to wish Xander all the best and says how great it is to see her happy - even for someone else.

Xander paces up and down alone in the kitchen, and Willow finds him. They hug and she tells him she loves him - and Xander says only about half as much as he loves her. Xander says he needs a minute to work on his vows, and Willow leaves him, happily unaware of the fright Xander's had. The band starts playing, and Anya's still trying out her vows on Tara in her dressing room when Buffy pops her head in and asks if she's ready to go. Buffy's suddenly distracted by something outside and pops back out again, shutting the door. Outside, Willow tells Buffy that Xander's missing. Willow says she's going to find Xander, leaving Buffy to hold up the proceedings in the meantime. She tells Anya there's a slight delay - the minister has had to perform an emergency C-section. Anya buys it, miraculously, and when Buffy's gone, continues on her vows. "I, Anya, want to marry you Xander, because I love you and will always love you. Before I met you I was a completely different person - not even a person, really. I'd seen what love could do to people and it was hurt and sadness. Then there was you - you knew me and saw me, make me feel warm and safe. I finally get love." Outside, Xander walks alone in the rain.

The congregation waits impatiently, and Buffy goes to explain the problem to the minister. Mr. Harris heads for the bar. Carol tells Buffy she has to do something more to keep everyone occupied, and Buffy takes the microphone at the front of the room and plays charades with the congregation. Outside, Dawn talks to a teenage demon boy about how messed up their respective families are. Anya decides she's sick of waiting and heads down, walking past Dawn just as she confides to her new friend that Xander's missing. Anya freaks out, and the demons and Harrises begin to fight among themselves. Buffy looks on in a mixture of despair and bemusement as it becomes a full-scale brawl. Willow pulls Tara out of the melee and find themselves holding hands. Carol tells Anya she saw Xander go into the trophy room with an old man. She points him out, and Anya goes over to asks him what he said to Xander. He says what's done is done, and Anya demands he tells her why he left. He says Xander left because of her - and she hasn't changed a bit. The old man transforms into a demon and explains that she punished him when she was a vengeance demon, and now he's here to ruin her life, like she ruined his by turning him into a demon. The images weren't real - just Xander's nightmare vision of the future.

The demon attacks Anya and Buffy fights him, grabbing the attention of the congrergation, while Xander arrives, and Anya explains that the images weren't real. Xander holds her hands and says it doesn't matter now. Xander puts the final blow in, killing the demon with a pillar. The brawl gets underway again before Anya calls a halt. "This wedding will go on, so get back in your seats!" Anya tells Xander it's okay, the demon's dead and they can go on with the wedding. But Xander doesn't want to. The old man's antics notwithstanding, Xander simply doesn't feel ready to get married. Xander says he's had fears but never said anything. Anya says everyone gets scared - it doesn't mean their marriage is wrong. Xander looks over at his parents inside, still bickering even now. Xander says he's sorry, but if this is a mistake, it will be forever and he can't go through with it. Anya walks inside to inform the minister as Xander leaves; and as Anya walks down the aisle, the congregation stands and the band plays the march. At home, Buffy, Dawn and Willow wonder aloud what they can do to help Anya, and where Xander is. They can't believe it's all gone so wrong. Xander's alone in a hotel room, feeling diconnected. D'Hoffryn tells Anya he's sorry for damning her to life as a mortal, and says it's time she was returned to her former power.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

My dad says "Hell's bells" a lot for some reason.

Xander's famed Uncle Rory finally makes an appearance alongside his parents (we've heard them before) who turn out to be as obnoxious as has been suggested in the past.

Punks may notice that in Xander's kitchen someone has drawn a Dead Kenneys logo on the noticeboard during Xander's getting-ready scene.

The nightmare future glimpses see Xander dependant on drink the same way most of his family became. It's interesting to watch, although i dont think you necessarily drink a lot if your family does - I don't drink at all (anymore) and my family certainly do.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}

@endnode

@node "NORMALAGAIN" "Buffy.guide: Normal Again"

@{b}Normal Again@{ub}
6ABB17

"She believes she is some type of hero. In her mind, she is the central figure in a fantastic world beyond imagination. She's surrounded herself with friends, most with their own super-powers, who are as real to her as you or me. More so, unfortunately."

In search of The Trio, Buffy works her way through a list of newly rented housing. When she approaches The Trio's hideout, Andrew summons a grey-ish, almost extra-terrestrial looking demon to fight Buffy. During the fight, the demon stabs Buffy with a retractable spike that comes from his middle knuckle. As he does, Buffy believes she's in a hospital room, being injected by two interns, who're having trouble keeping her still. When Buffy comes round, the demon is gone. At college, Willow watches as Tara comes out of a lecture and tries to "accidentally" meet up with her. However, another girl walks up to Tara, kisses her on the lips and they look very friendly. Upset, Willow turns just before Tara looks in her direction, to see her walking away.

At work, the manager Lorraine calls Buffy, and suddenly Buffy finds herself in the institution, being told she needs to take her drugs. Then she's back at work again and Lorraine looks at her worriedly. At home, Willow checks the net for any sign of Xander, to no avail. She tells Buffy about the girl she saw with Tara earlier, but Buffy tells her surely they're just friends. Xander calls by to say he's back and the three friends hug. Xander asks where Anya is and they say she left two days ago. Xander's filled with self-loathing at how much he's messed up, and says he didn't want to break up with Anya, he just wasn't ready for marriage. Later, Spike finds Buffy in the cemetary, and Buffy tells him the wedding didn't happen. Xander and Willow arrive, and Xander tells him to "run along", which Spike takes as his cue to have a go at Xander for bailing. They start to fight as Willow tries to break it up, and Buffy has a sudden headache and drops to the bench, holding her head.

The doctor asks Buffy if she can hear him. He tells her Sunnydale doesn't exist - she's in a mental institution and has been there for six years. Joyce and (###todo-buffdad) come in to see her and welcome her home. The doctor tells them to keep talking, as this will ground her. However, they see her retreat once more into fantasy. Willow and Xander take Buffy home, where she explains that she's been having hallucinations about being in an institution ever since the waxy demon stabbed her. Willow decides to get researching right away and asks Xander to check the demon bars. In the doctor's office, Buffy and her parents are told by the doctor that there's a possibility for recovery.	Buffy calls out Dawn's name and from her parents' reaction, we see Dawn doesn't exist in the "real world". The doctor explains that by making up Dawn, Buffy created inconsistencies in her delusion, and it's coming apart - even the foes she creates in her mind are becoming more impotent.

Andrew and Warren get back to The Trio's hideout with a load of boxes and Jonathan gets upset that they're keeping something from him. He goes to leave but Warren stops him. Willow identifies the demon who stabbed Buffy, Glarghk Guhl Kashmas 'Nik, and tells her that the demon carries an antidote to the mind-altering poison, within its own body. Xander and Spike are out hunting as they speak. Buffy tells Willow how detatched and lost she feels, and Willow tells Buffy she is not in an institution, and never has been. Buffy says she has - when she first saw a vampire, she was so scared, she told her parents, and they sent her to a clinic. Buffy was released two weeks later, when she realised no-one would believe her and she stopped talking about it. "What if I'm still there?" she asks her best friend. "What if I never left the clinic?"

Spike and Xander find the demon - it finds them, rather. They take him down with a mixture of punches and tranquilizer darts. Dawn visits Buffy in her room with some tea. Buffy says they have to deal with the problems she's having with her grades and stealing. In the institution, Joyce tells Buffy she doesn't have a sister, and makes her repeat it. Back in Buffy's room, tears stream down Dawn's face as she realises she doesn't exist in Buffy's alternate reality. Spike and Xander take the Glarghk Guhl Kashmas 'Nik demon to Buffy's basement and chain him up, then Willow extracts the spike from the demon's knuckle and heads to college to cook up the antidote. In the morning, Willow brings the resulting formula to Buffy and she thanks her. Spike comes in and asks how she is. Willow leaves, telling Spike to make sure she drinks the antidote. Buffy tells him he should stay away from her, and he accuses her of playing the martyr - she's addicted to misery. He tells her to let herself live, and that he'll tell her friends about them if she doesn't. He leaves, and Buffy pours the antidote away.

In her hospital room, Buffy tells her parents and the doctor that she wants to be healthy again, and asks what she'll have to do. The doctor tells Buffy she will have to break her ties with her friends in Sunnydale, since they keep her going back. Willow makes Buffy some food, then Xander arrives some time later and Buffy knocks him in the face with a frying pan. She throws him down into the basement, where sees finds Willow bound up and gagged, before lapsing out of consciousness. Buffy locks them in the basement with the still chained-up demon, then goes to fetch Dawn. Dawn gets freaked out as Buffy tells her she has to "get healthy" and approaches her. Dawn runs as Buffy dives at her, and hides in the bathroom. She tries to tell Buffy the asylum isn't real, but Buffy says it's easier to believe in a sick girl being in an institution than a Vampire Slayer. Buffy chases Dawn into Joyce's old room, where she grabs her, then takes her to the basement and gags her.

The doctor tells Buffy to make it easy on herself, so to avoid killing her own friends, Buffy sets the demon loose to do her work. Tara arrives upstairs just as the demon starts to attack Xander. Buffy huddles in the corner of her hospital room as Joyce tries to reassure her. Tara goes into Buffy's basement and, using magic from the safety of the stairs, sets the gang free and knocks the demon over with a large wooden rack. As Tara comes down the stairs, Buffy grabs her ankle and trips her, and Willow runs to Tara's side. Joyce tells Buffy she's a survivor and she can do it, make it out, but back in Sunnydale Buffy sees her friends struggling against the demons and has no idea where her loyalties should lie. Joyce speaks, her words coming like a beacon from beyond the grave to Buffy: "Believe in yourself." Buffy says she's right and thanks her. And then says goodbye.

Back in her basement again, Buffy springs into action and kills the demon. Buffy tells her friends how sorry she is, and insists Willow makes up another antidote straight away. Back in the institution, the doctor shines a light into Buffy's eyes and finds no reaction. He turns to Mr. and Mrs. Summers and apologises. "We lost her."

@{b}Notes@{ub}

The idea that none of Buffy's reality exists is heartbreaking. This would presumably mean none of Angel's adventures in Los Angeles have happened either. If our idea of reality depends on our perception of normality and abnormality, you could say that a show like Buffy actually @{i}is @{ui} an alternate reality. It's not one that you or I have any control over, but at some point you become immersed in it, albeit as a spectator. The doctor makes an interesting point about how Buffy originally fought great monsters but now fights three "pathetic little men who like playing with toys".

Having Buffy turn on her own friends is an unbelievable sight, in fact this is an inspired episode. The writers have always made little jokes in the script about how ludicrous the ideas in the show are - one girl in the whole world who's powerful enough to slay vampires... I mean, come on! This all adds to Buffy's delusion, but we, of course still believe in the fantasy. It's like a weird, recursive irony. Buffy's assertion that her parents simply "forgot" she'd spent two weeks in an institution doesn't ring true at all.

The episode has been left open-ended quite beautifully. What do you mean?! She's cured! If Buffy really was in an institution and temporarily returned to reality, only to once again lapse into madness, she would make something up in order to repair the hole in her delusion - the demon and its poison. Even the fact that it carries the cure in its body seems too good to be true. So... is she mad? Heh heh heh, cackle the producers. Heh heh heh, and a heh heh heh.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "ENTROPY" "Buffy.guide: Entropy"

@{b}Entropy@{ub}
6ABB18

"Xander?!" Let's not waste any more breath on that wanker!" - Spike

Warren, Andrew and Jonathan pursue two vampires who have a small disc of metal they need, on quad bikes. All three come off their bikes and watch as the vamps run off, only to be accosted by Buffy. One vamp drops the disc, and while Buffy's busy with the vamps, Warren sneaks up undetected and retrieves it. Spike holds one of the vamps and says he'll let him go if she won't tell her friends about their relationship. After dusting the first vamp, Buffy says she won't and Spike lets the second vamp free. Spike asks Buffy why she won't sleep with him again, and the vamp turns around, puzzled. Buffy takes the opportunity to stake him, and tells Spike it's because she doesn't love him. "Like hell," he replies.

Xander nurses a beer at his apartment for a while until he gets fed up and goes out for a walk. As he leaves, we see Anya watching from behind the hedge. Willow finds Tara coming out of class again, but this time they talk. Tara tells Willow the girl she saw he with is just a friend, and they arrange to have coffee tomorrow. Buffy takes Dawn shopping, but Dawn can't go in most of the shops because of her criminal record. Warren and Andrew watch as Jonathan works on some chemical project. Jonathan wants to break The Trio up after this next mission, and Warren tells him to cheer up - they're about to get everything they'd ever want. Andrew tells Warren in private that he feels sorry for Jonathan - and he's not sure he trusts him. Warren says he doesn't have to much longer. "It" will happen soon.

Xander gets home to find Anya in the living room. He tries to explain that he still wants to be with her, since he loves her so much. But when Anya hears he still doesn't want to get married now, she gets pissed at him, sarcastically congratulating him on his honesty. She turns from him and puts on her demon face. She tries to wish that Xander was never born, but it doesn't work. She tries more wishes, but they don't work. Anya tells @{"Halfrek" LINK "ABOUTHALFREK"} the next day, and she tells her she can't make a wish for herself - she'll have to get someone else to make it for her. Buffy makes breakfast for Dawn and asks her what she wants to do tonight. Dawn tells Buffy she doesn't need to feel guilty about locking her and the gang in the basement - it wasn't her fault. Buffy says she just wants to spend time with her, and Dawn suggests she patrols with Buffy. Buffy gives her a predicable "no way", despite Dawn protesting that Buffy and her friends, patrolled at her age.

Anya turns up at the coffee shop and Willow and Tara tell her they're sorry about what happened, and asks if there's anything they can do to help her. Anya attempts to get them to make a wish about Xander, then tries Dawn and Buffy. Xander comes round to Buffy's house and Anya walks off. Buffy stops Xander from following, because they're both upset and it won't help for them to have a confrontation. Xander gets pissed and kicks over Buffy's garden gnome. Only Buffy doesn't have a garden gnome. On closer inspection, there's a camera hidden inside the gnome, and Xander suggests it's Spike. Buffy pays him a visit, and he can't believe she really thinks he's watching her. He doesn't hurt her, he says, and their love is real. Buffy says it's real for him and she's sorry that's not what he wants. She tells him he has to move on, and he tells her to get out.

Halfrek, talking to Anya at the Magic Box, tells her she needs to find someone who doesn't like Xander to make a wish. Just then, Spike walks in, asking for a spell or potion to ease his hurt. Anya comes up with a bottle of whiskey. Willow uses her laptop to break into The Trio's webcam network, and meanwhile Jonathan uses the disc in a spell, which casts a beam of light on a specific spot, on a map of Sunnydale. Jonathan says that's where they have to go. Anya and Spike get increasingly drunk while she tries to get Spike to make a wish, and they share in their relationship woes. Willow finds there are scores of cameras around town - the Double Meat Palace, the Bronze, college, Xander's construction site. She says there are more camera, but she'll take a while to find them. Anya thanks Spike for listening, and they end up kissing. Willow finds a feed to the Magic Box and sees Spike and Anya having sex as The Trio realise someone's in the system and start shutting it down - until they see what Willow's seeing and stop to watch.

Xander and Buffy go to see what Willow's so freaked out about on the laptop, and then Dawn comes in, and Willow shields her eyes. Willow notices Buffy looks hurt too, but before anyone has the chance to really say anything, Buffy storms out the back door, followed by Dawn, and Xander takes an axe from Buffy's weapons chest, heading to the Magic Box. Buffy tells Dawn about her and Spike, and says it's over. Willow comes out and tells Buffy Xander's gone, along with her axe. At the Magic Box, Anya and Spike get dressed, and then Spike leaves. As soon as he's out of the door, he finds an axe heading for his head and has to duck. Xander beats Spike up and then goes to stake him, but Anya stops him. Buffy arrives and Anya and Xander argue - she says it's nothing to do with him because he left her, and calls him an insecure little boy. Xander says he feels sick to think she had sex with Spike, and Spike retorts that it's good enough for Buffy. Xander's aghast and makes his exit, unable to get his head around everything.

Tara visits Willow and tells her when things fall apart, you can't just put them back the way they were - it takes time. There's so much to work through. Willow says she knows that. "It's a long important process," Tara continues. "Can't we just skip it? Can you just be kissing me now?" And so, Tara and Willow kiss, finally re-united.

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Doesn't it make you happy to see Tara and Willow patching it up? It just makes you clap your hands together an make a squeaky noise - actually much like Dawn does in the next episode. Anya's attempts at making the Scooby Gang wish against Xander are nice and funny: sample quotes being "Wish his penis would explode?", "What kind of lesbians are you?" and "Squish, squish, squish!"

It's difficult to believe Buffy would jump to the conclusion that Spike's the one spying on her, and it's fairly obvious that her visit to Spike was contrived to bring Spike and Anya together at the Magic Box.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "SEEINGRED" "Buffy.guide: Seeing Red"

@{b}Seeing Red@{ub}
6ABB19

"He lied and lied and lied some more, because hey, who's gonna notice with all the other lies flying around like little monkeys?" - Anya.

Tara and Willow wake up together, and Willow tells Tara she thinks there's something going on with Buffy and Spike. Buffy didn't come home last night, and she looked really hurt when she saw Spike and Anya together. Tara tells her she already knows - Buffy and Spike have been sleeping together. She probably didn't say anything because of the look she'd give her. Willow gets up to check if Buffy's back, but her room's still empty. Dawn pops her head out of her room and Willow says Buffy's not back yet, and she should go back to sleep. Dawn says it's ten in the morning, and Willow can't believe it's that late - she and Tara haven't had a wink of sleep. Tara comes out and Dawn realises they're back together, and says she'll go into the basement to watch TV where she can't hear a thing - her joy at their reconciliation is more than evident. Buffy finds The Trio's hideout, and although their equipment and action figures have been left behind, it's apparently deserted. She finds a note scrawled on a board - "Too late" - and all of a sudden, several giant circular saws start to swing through the air. Buffy runs to the exit, grabbing a few papers and information, only just escaping serious injury - her coat has a massive tear across the front.

Tara, Willow, Dawn and Buffy sift through the information Buffy salvaged from the Trio's old hideout, while Anya talks to a girl in a bar about cheating men. Anya's so wrapped up in her own anger, she fails to notice the young woman is making wishes almost willy-nilly. The Trio bring down a demon with the help of a cattle-prod, then Warren passes Jonathan a knife. Dawn stops by Spike's place and asks if this means he won't be coming round any more. Spike says it's complicated. Dawn asks Spike if he really loves Buffy, but he doesn't even need to answer. Dawn asks how he could hurt Buffy so much if he loves her, and he says maybe there's still some evil left in him. The Trio find a cave with a strange forcefield across the entrance, where demons like the one they've slain walk through un-scathed. Everything else thrown at the barrier gets fried. Warren sends Jonathan through the barrier wearing the demon's skin to retrieve something from the other side. Warren and Andrew talk about Jonathan behind his back and it's obvious they're plotting against him. Warren wasn't even sure Jonathan would make it through the barrier.

Jonathan brings a box back from behind the barrier and hands it to Warren, who uses a strange gadget to open it up. Inside are two orbs - the Orbs of Nesluchan(###todo-spelling). Warren says they offer strength and invulnerability - and as he holds them in his hands, a flash of power encompasses him - and when another demon approaches, he snaps its neck with the kind of ease even Buffy only sees on a very good day. Buffy calls on Xander and he offers her a beer although it's still morning. There's rubbish and dirty dishes around - he hasn't been cleaning. Buffy tells him Anya loves him. Xander says he understands Anya havnig sex with Spike, but not Buffy. Buffy says it's been hard just existing having been brought back from heaven. Xander says he may have fought side by side with Spike during Buffy's absense, but he never forgot who Spike really is, and asks Buffy what she was thinking - he doesn't have a soul, and if the chip stopped working, he wouldn't be the same. Xander leaves angrily to go for a walk. He stops by the Magic Box and watches through the window at Anya cleaning up inside.

Willow and Tara are in bed, Willow checking through a CD-ROM Buffy found at the hideout. It's full of blueprints and schematics, but there's no indication of where they're from. Xander's drinking at the Bronze, when Warren & co walk in, looking to cause some trouble. Buffy 's out patrolling and dusts a vampire - with his last action he manages to knock Buffy through a tomb-stone. Aching from her fight, Buffy goes to take a shower when she returns home, and Spike appears at the bathroom door. He asks if she's hurt, and she tells him to get out. Spike tells her he's sorry and didn't want to hurt her - he only went to the Magic Box for a spell to ease his pain. Spike asks her why she keep lying to herself about her love for him, and she says she could never trust him enough to love him. Spike goes to grab her, and tells her to "let herself feel" the love. They struggle and Spike becomes more violent, forcing himself on top of her. He holds her down in spite of her pleas for him to stop, repeating that she'll "feel it again." Buffy manages to get a good kick in and sends him flying across the room. "Ask me again why I could never love you."

Warren hits on the girlfriend of one of the jocks from high-school. When he returns, Warren tells him to go away so he can "fool around" with his girl. The jock guy tries to push Warren but he doesn't move. Warren pushes him back and the guy flies through the air like a polystyrene glider. A few other guys try to take him on, but they recieve similar punishment. Xander come out of the toilet and confronts him. Warren asks Xander if he can put a good word in for him with Anya, and Xander swings for him. Warren returns the favour and sends Xander a good hundred feet through the air. Jonathan tells Warren he's giong to be late if they don't go now, so they do. Xander finds his way to Buffy's, blood streaming out of his nose. When he gets in, he finds Spike's coat on the bannister, and goes into the bathroom to confront Buffy about seeing Spike again. He finds her in the bathroom, bruised, and makes for the door, intent on payback. Buffy stops him. Willow arrives and asks what happened; Buffy says nothing.

Downstairs, Willow and Tara tell Buffy the Trio's CD-ROM's are full of layouts and blueprints for banks and corporate vaults, etc. Willow and Tara think they know what they'll be doing tonight - one of their tasks is time-sensitive. Spike's at home, attempting to drown his sorrows when Clem drops by - there's a Knight-Rider marathon on TV. Spike asks Clem why he feels so messed up - Clem says love is a funny thing. Spike misses the simplicity of being a monster, before his chip was fitted. Spike wants to make things change. Warren attempts to rob a bank truck, turning it on its side. Buffy finds him and they fight, Buffy having trouble keeping up. However, she sends him crashing into a stones pillar and he falls under a pile of rubble. Buffy approaches Andrew and Jonathan, but before she can do anything, Warren picks himself up out of the rubble like nothing's happened. Warren proves himself a match for the Slayer, and they trade blows for a while, until Jonathan leaps on Buffy's back and whispers into her ear, "Smash his orbs."

Warren knocks Buffy to the ground, and as he goes to puch her, she sees the orbs in a leather pouch on his belt, rips them off and slams them to the ground. Without his strength, Warren decides the best plan is to escape, and he takes off his jacket to reveal a jet-pack. He blasts off into the sky. Andrew follows suit, but forgets to check above and smashes his head against the canopy of a nearby building. Jonathan wasn't given a jet-pack, and stands helplessly as the cops arrive and take them both in. At the police-station, Andrew cries about Warren having left him, leaving Jonathan wondering if Andrew's gay. Spike, meanwhile, leaves Sunnydale on a Yamaha motorcycle, mentally promising the Slayer that he'll be back.

Next morning, Willow and Tara look out of their bedroom window to see Xander and Buffy down in the garden. Buffy's looking for cameras. Buffy and Xander wonder how they've made it through the past through weeks and they apologise to each other. Xander says he doesn't know what he'd do without Willow and Buffy, and they hug. Warren appears out of nowhere and calls Buffy's name. "You think you can just do that to me? Thank again!" Warren pulls a gun and starts firing. Buffy and Xander dive to the floor. One bullet hits Buffy and Xander runs to her side. Another goes through Tara and Willow's bedroom window, and punctures Tara's chest. Willow picks up Tara and pleads with her to get up, and Xander does the same with Buffy outside on the lawn. Her lover dead, Willow seeks solace in the strongest power she's ever known - magic. She raises her head to the heaven, and her eyes glow red...

@{b}Notes@{ub}

I can't say I have seen anything much more disturbing than the scene in the bathroom when Spike tries to rape Buffy. I watch a lot of trashy horror movies like the stuff Vipco release and the one thing I've learned from them is that blood and guts alone is not that frightening once you've seen it a few times. The emotional impact of this scene is intense. Part of it's the direction: it's mostly shot with handheld cameras, giving an added sense of reality, with quick cuts to keep the momentum of the scene up. There's also a shot from the ceiling of the bathroom that gives it a horrific crime-scene feeling that I haven't felt since I watched The Last Broadcast (which is basically The Blair Witch Project for people with taste).

What really sets you up for a shock is a sort of psychological build-up over the last few episodes. We've been in Buffy shoes - liking him almost against our own free will. Knowing he's evil, we feel for him because he's obviously in love with Buffy. But - a gigantic but, this one - he @{b}is@{ub} evil, his love for Buffy does not override that fact, and he would not have stopped if Buffy hadn't got a good kick in. That's what the audience isn't ready for. That's what makes you drop your tea and mouth "What the fuck?" at the T.V. It's a scene quite unlike anything else in Buffy. It's a struggle between two people of roughly equal strength (Spike gains the upper hand because Buffy is weak from an earlier fight). In this sense, it's a very "human" scene as opposed to most other violent scenes in Buffy - it's not a scene about strength or casting spells, but the complete breakdown of trust between two people who we might have assumed were physically normal humans had we switched the channel at that point.

That's not to mention the carnage Warren causes at the end of the episode, of course. (It's always been at the back of my mind, why don't more demons carry guns? They have fantastic aim.) Just when you think you've had your shock for the night, two of the main characters get shot! In this highly-censored world it's a surprise this really passed as a cert-15 video release. Thankfully the censors seem to have relaxed a bit after all the hubub surrounding films like 'Child's Play 3' (maybe they actually watched that film and realised it should have been banned for being shit, if anything).

The demon whose skin the Trio use to pass through the forcefield at the cave is refreshingly imaginative looks-wise.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "VILLAINS" "Buffy.guide: Villains"

@{b}Villains@{ub}
6ABB20

"Funny isn't it? One tiny piece of metal destroys everything... Now the one person who should be here is gone, and a waste like you gets to live." - Willow.

Xander calls an ambulance for Buffy, unaware that Tara has also been hit. Willow tries an incantation to bring back Tara, as the paramedics work on Buffy below. Osiris refuses to bring Tara back for Willow and she screams at him, the grief in her scream causing him pain. Willow comes out of the house and Xander says Warren's responsible. She sets off in search of him, not telling Xander that Tara's been shot, and Xander gets into the ambulance with Buffy.  While Jonathan and Warren wait in their cell, Warren goes to a demon bar in town to gloat about killing the Slayer - only to have the barman tell him it's just been on the news - Buffy's survived and she's in hospital. Slayers heal fast and she'll be coming for him "big time."

However, Buffy is the least of Warren's problems - Willow bursts into the Magic Box, her rage busting the lightbulbs as she walks under them. She asks Anya where the black arts books are, and Anya refuses to help, so Willow uses magic to make her back off, and fetches the books herself. Using magic to pull every book she can find onto the table, she then absorbs the information in the books, leaving the pages blank. Dawn arrives home, unaware of the shooting, and calls out for Buffy. She finds Tara's body in the bedroom. Meanwhile, Warren visits @{"Wreck" LINK "ABOUTRACK"} hoping he'll be able to help him - he's got the Slayer on his back. Wreck tells him he shoul be worrying about the witch, not the Slayer. Wreck can feel that while Buffy's alive, someone else is dead, and that's why Willow wants Warren's head. Warren gives Wreck a large wad of cash in the hope he'll be able to prtect him, but Wreck says he can't promise anything - Willow's "running on pure fury."

Xander watches on through the window as the doctors operate on Buffy. There's a power surge and Willow appears in the room, telling the doctors to leave. They do, and Xander tells Willow Buffy will die if she isn't operated on. Willow begs to differ, and stands over Buffy, where she pulls the bullet out using telekinesis. Buffy stirs and asks what happened, then sees Willow and can tell something's wrong. Willow says they have to go and find Warren, then leaves the room. Warren's trying to leaave town, and boards an outgoing coach. Willow, Buffy and Xander pursue in Xander's car, and to Xander's annoyance, Willow keep taking over the controls. After a little cross-country jaunt, Willow stops the car by the side of the road as Warren's coach approaches. She uses magic to keep her friends back, then stands in the caches path and makes it accelerate as the driver struggles with the controls. Willow stops the coach within an inch of herself and orders Warren to get out. She strangles him, his eye pops out and sparks fly - it's one of Warren's robots.

Unsure just how Warren tricked her, Willow sets off again in search of Warren, promising to kill him. Buffy tries to stop her, and Willow tells her friends that Tara got hit too. Buffy tells Willow she loved Tara but she can't allow her to kill a human being. Willow won't hear it, and pushes her friends back before vanishing into thin air. Buffy and Xander drop by Buffy's house to find Dawn crying next to Tara's body. Xander signs the papers as Tara is stretchered out of the house. Dawn says Warren should die - she'd do it herself if she could. Xander agrees - Warren's as bad as any vampire Buffy's slain. Buffy promises Warren will get his just deserts, but she won't be involved in killing a human being - this shooting was a human, real-world murder, and Warren should be dealt with the way humans deal with murderers. Buffy suggests a locating spell to find Willow - they'll drop Dawn by Spike's. Xander's not happy about leaving Dawn in Spike's care, but they have little choice.

Willow works an incantation on her blood-splatered shirt. The blood shifts around to make a map of Sunnydale, and a light appears showing Warren's location - in the woods. Buffy takes Dawn to Spike's and finds Clem there, but no Spike. Clem tells Buffy that Spike left town and he's house-sitting. Clem has proven himself trust-worthy so far, so Buffy leaves Dawn with him. Spike visits a tribal cave with wall-paintings of supernatural death, including a vampire slayer. A sillhouette with cold, glowing eyes appears and knows what Spike is after. He mocks Spike for allowing himself to be "castrated" and tells him he'd never endure the trials required to grant his wish - to return to his former self. Spike tells him to bring it on.

Anya's paralysis is just about wearing off, and she's able to tell Xander that Willow pretty much sucked all the books dry. However, they don't need a spell to find Willow - Anya can feel her. She explains to Xander that she's become a vengeance demon once again. Anya says she'll help, but it's Willow she's helping, not Xander and Buffy. She's near to Warren, in the woods. As Willow walks through the woods, the trees bend back to let her pass. Warren manages to circle her and put an axe in her back, but it doesn't kill her. He runs, and then sends a flying bomb after her, but she freezes the explosion before it affects her. Willow knocks him over with a blot of magic, and he uses a spell to hold her back in a forcefield. It takes Willow just seconds to break it, but Warren at least manages to get ahead a little. Willow uses vines to tie Warren up by the hands and feet, and she finally has him - he can't move. Willow senses that Tara isn't the first girl Warren killed, and brings forth an image of @{"Katrina" LINK "ABOUTKATRINA"} who asks him why he killed her if he loved her so much.

Buffy, Anya and Xander are closing in, as Warren begins to scream out for help. Willow produces the bullet she pulled out of Buffy's chest and lets in hover in front of Warren, asking him if he wants to know what a bullet feels like? She pushes the bullet into him in excruciating slow motion, stitching up his mouth when she becomes sick of his whining. "Can you feel it now?" She releases his mouth to allow him to answer and he begs her to stop as Buffy, Anya and Xander arrive. They're here just in time to watch in horror as Willow, with the sweep of an arm, rips Warren's skin clean off, before he burns away. "One down."

@{b}Notes@{ub}

Jeeeeesus christ.

The integration of magic into Buffy has been slow. At first, it was slightly clumsy - episodes like @{"The Witch" LINK "THEWITCH"} seemed like major departures from what was then the usual Buffy fare - vampire this, demon that. The entire series now seems grounded in magics and there we were complaining about the impotent season badies - the trio - when it turns out Willow's our real baddie!

The song playing in the demon bar is 'Die, Die My Darling' by goth-punk band The Misfits. The song has also been covered by Metallica.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "TWOTOGO" "Buffy.guide: Two To Go"

@{b}Two To Go@{ub}
6ABB21

"Killing people changes you - believe me, I know." - Buffy.
"Signals? Who from, your probe-happy alien friends?!" - Jonathan.

Xander, Buffy and Anya runs through the woods, Xander in particular having trouble dealing with what he's just seen and the fact that his best friend did it. Based on Willow's words, "one down", they figure she's going for Andrew and Jonathan next. Anya uses her power as a vengeance demon to teleport ahead, while Buffy and Xander search for the car. When they find it, it's a wreck - Willow must have sabotaged it. Buffy decides she'll run ahead, leaving a frustrated Xander to catch up. At the County Jail, Jonathan mocks Andrew for still keeping faith in Warren ("You are sadness personified!"). They fight for a second before Anya materialises in their cell. Anya explains that Willow will be here soon, looking for payback. She calls a guard over, who's shocked to find her in the cell. She explains that something's coming that he won't be able to deal with, and that the boys need to be released.

Willow appears outside and begins breaking down the exterior wall of the first-floor cell. She wards off the police with with her magic, as Buffy sneaks into the station via a fire door. Willow flies up to the hole in the wall and finds the cell empty and the bars bend out of shape - Buffy has released Andrew and Jonathan. Anya attempts to talk her out of her mission of revenge, but Willow won't listen and knocks Anya out with magic, then opens her mouth and fills the air with a deafening scream. Xander pulls up outside in a stolen cop car and Buffy, Andrew and Jonathan get in. As they speed off, Jonathan wonders aloud why Willow doesn't just make them dead with a spell - Buffy says Willow wants to do it D.I.Y. style. Xander asks, if that's the case, why Willow isn't here, right now. Just then, the car jolts and Xander looks in his mirror - Willow is commanding a massive Peterbilt goods vehicle, standing on the roof of the cab while the driver attempts to regain control of the wagon.

Willow repeatedly rams their car, and Jonathan notices Willow's power is draining. He tells Xander to keep driving, and the driver of the truck manages finally to bring it to a halt. Clem entertains Dawn with a nachos taste-tester ("You think this is dumb don't you?"). He offers to take her to a movie, and then tells her how sorry he is. He says if he can do anything to help her, he will - but soon regrets saying that. Dawn says she needs him to help her - she's going to Wreck's to find Willow. The Cave demon pits Spike against an incredibly strong human-looking demon who uses the power of fire - and it looks like he doesn't stand a chance. Meanwhile, Clem's twitchy because apparently Wreck doesn't like floppy ears - and this whole thing is dangerous, he was supposed to be keeping Dawn safe. At the Magic Box, Anya says she can no longer sense Willow - so her feelings have gone "way beyond simple vengeance." Buffy decides magic is the best way to stop Willow, but Xander despairs - she took everything.

Anya says not everything was taken - and reveals a hidden chest with protection spells in it. Unfortunately, she can't read the language. Xander asks Buffy what they'll do even if they do manage to stop Willow or slow her down. Buffy says she'll talk to her. If Willow kills Jonathan or Andrew, she's crossed the line, and Buffy loses her friend. Willow drops by Wreck's. He tells her how much she's bloomed and generally acts like a creep, stroking her face. "You came because you want something, don't you?" Willow says yes, and he asks what. "Just to take a little tour..." Willow repeats on Wreck the mojo he worked on her the first time they met - she's feeding off his power. Clem and Dawn find Wreck's place, and Dawn goes into the room alone, because Clem's too scared to go in. Dawn calls for Willow, but finds only Wreck's dead body hanging from the ceiling. Willow appears, her face all flushed, and Dawn tries to tell her that this is the wrong way to go, but Willow appears unconcerned, and then taunts Dawn about how she doesn't belong here.

Willow offers to turn Dawn back into a "little energy ball", saying it would make everyone happier. Meanwhile, Buffy has found her way to Wreck's, deciding that if Willow's running out of juice like Jonathan says, she'll be there. She walks in and tells her to get away from Dawn. At the Magic Box, Anya's busy trying to translate the protection spell but getting nowhere. Jonathan tries to help them and Andrew asks him why - together they could take Anya and Xander, and then they could become the duo. Andrew says he'll take orders and Jonathan tells him to grow up. Xander tells them to shut up, and Andrew says Willow will probably come after her friends too. Xander says she wouldn't, but Anya says Andrew has a point - Willow doesn't care if he lives or dies. Xander's worried Anya will turn on him and take vengeance but she says she can't hurt him, so she's going to settle for hating him. Anya says none of this would be happening if it wasn't for Xander and he says it's true - he saw Warren's gun and feels like he could have done more to stop him - but he couldn't move. He was useless. Anya says she was talking about their relationship.

Buffy tries to talk to Willow, and remind her of who she is, but she says Willow is a loser. The only thing she ever had was Tara - and she'll never have her again. Buffy tells Willow that if she lets the magic get out of hand, she'll lose everything - the world, and everyone in it. Willow laughs at this - wasn't it Buffy who was so much happier in the ground? They find themselves in the Magic Box - courtesy of Willow's magic - and Willow attempts to fry Jonathan and Andrew with her magic, but Anya's protection spell is apparently working. In the cave, Spike's taking a brutal beating from his foe, until he gains the upper hand and snaps the opponent's neck. The cave demon tells Spike he's succesfully completed the first part of his trial. Willow, thwarted by Anya's protection spell, does a spell on herself to gain physical strength so she can fight them without magic. Buffy stands in the way as Willow approaches the boys, and Willow punches her, sending her flying into a literature rack. Buffy gets up and hits Willow back, the wiccan smashing straight through a glass display case. Xander, Dawn, Jonathan and Andrew head for cover, while Anya stays and keeps the spell going. The two friends-cum-mortal enemies stand face to face. "Oh Buffy, you really need to have every square inch of your arse kicked." "Then show me what you've got."

Willow and Buffy trade blows, but Buffy still takes the defensive, and tells Willow she can help her stop the magic. Xander, Dawn, Jonathan and Andrew carry on running, trying to think on their feet. Jonathan and Andrew still carrying swords for protection. Andrew says they should go to Mexico, and Xander says they just need a place to hide until Buffy talks Willow round. Andrew's sick of Xander calling all the shots, and takes Jonathan's sword, holding it at Xander's throat. Willow finds Anya, and realises she's the one working the spell. Xander tries to calm Andrew down, and Jonathan holds his sword at Andrew's neck to make him drop the sword. He does, and Jonathan says that as soon as this is over, he and Andrew should do their time. Willow knocks Tara out so she can't chant, and now able to perform magic again, she knocks Buffy across the room and says that no-one can stop her now. Just then, a flash fills the room and knocks Willow over. Giles stands in the doorway. "I'd like to test that theory."

@{b}Notes@{ub}

The show's reference points are becoming a little obvious at this stage. Doesn't this whole scenario remind you of Carrie? Also, those teleports, with the lightning effects, owe more than a little to James Cameron's action masterpiece 'Terminator 2: Judgement Day', as does the car and truck chase. Even the music during the chase sequence is so much like Brad Fiedel's score, it could have been lifted straight from 'T2'.

It's hard to feel much pity for the snivelling Andrew, but Jonathan proves here that he at least has a conscience. His humanity and timidity is what eventually led to him being at the bottom of the chain of command in The Trio - Andrew was too easily lead to ever find himself questioning Warren's orders, and thus found himself more in favour with Warren.

Spike's line "Here we are now... entertain us" is of course lifted from Nirvana's best-known song 'Smells Like Teen Spirit', from their 1991 DGC album 'Nevermind'.

This episode again explores Xander's feelings of inferiority given his lack of special powers. This was an issue first pointed out by Cordy in @{"The Zeppo" LINK "THEZEPPO"}.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "GRAVE" "Buffy.guide: Grave"

@{b}Grave@{ub}
6ABB22

"Mexico, huh?" - Jonathan.

Buffy gets up to see Giles at the door. Willow can tell Giles' power is borrowed, and says it won't be strong enough to defeat her. Giles says he's here to help, and she must stop or else she'll end up dead. Buffy tells Willow to listen to Giles - she doesn't want to fight with her anymore. Willow says she doesn't want to fight with Buffy either - she wants to fight Giles. Before she can do anything, Giles puts her in a binding field, buying them at least some time. Giles tells Willow he's sorry about Tara, and she tells him that the spell won't hold her forever. Buffy and Giles go into the training room and laugh at the insanity of the situation, and everything that's happened since he left. On the shop floor, Willow attempts to talk Anya into releasing the binding spell, and despite Anya's best efforts, Willow has a lot of influence over her. Giles apologises to Buffy for leaving, but Buffy says he was right in a way to leave. Giles says the coven who gave him his powers are also working on a way to take away Willow's power without harming her - but she's killed a human being and may not ever be the same. Willow appears at the door with Anya's lifeless body. "I wouldn't worry about that. Willow doesn't live here anymore."

Buffy runs at Willow but she throws her back with ease. Giles attempts to re-cast his binding spell, but Willow shrugs it off. She flings the weapons hung up on the wall straight at Giles, who moves the dummy in front of himself just in time to shield himself, then uses his power to knock Willow straight through the wall behind her. Xander and Dawn have no idea where they're going and Dawn says they should go back and fight like Spike would have. Xander lets slip to Dawn that Spike attempted to rape Buffy but she won't believe him. Meaanwhile, an even bloodier Spike slays another demon, before his next trial starts. He finds bugs crawling on his skin in their hundreds, some into his nose and mouth. At the Nagic Box, Giles stands wearily while Willow appears unscathed. She attempts to finish Giles off, but Buffy knocks him out of the way in time. Willow decides she must get rid of Buffy and sends a ball of flame to seek out Jonathan and Andrew - along with anyone helping them - and kill them all. Maybe someone will get there in time to stop it, suggests Willow, and Giles tells Buffy to go quickly.

Willow plays with Giles like a cat would with a mouse, holding him to the ceiling of the room and then letting him drop. Giles tells Willow she'll burn out and needs to stop - Willow disagrees. "What I need is a little pick-me-up." She puts her hand to Giles' chest and absorbs his powers and energy, before he falls to the floor unconscious. Willow gets a headrush from the power and tells Giles she's connected to everything - and can feel everything. All the pain and emotion in the world is too much for her to bear. Giles tells her she can stop it - stop all the pain and suffering. Xander, Dawn, Jonathan and Andrew attempt to break into a crypt at the cemetary to hide out in, when they spy the fireball coming this way. Buffy's running towards them too and pushes them out of the way just before it strikes. Xander's knocked out against a tomb-stone, and when Buffy sees Dawn near the gigantic crater caused by the impact, she goes over to grab her and both sisters fall into the hole, followed by two swords. Jonathan and Andrew seize the opportunity and make a run for it.

Anya, thankfully, is alive and finds Giles among the wreck. He tells Anya that Willow took his magic, and he can feel where she is - and knows what she plans to do. She's going to end the world. Morning breaks and Buffy and Dawn try in vain to get up out of the hole in the ground. Dawn asks Buffy why she didn't tell her what Spike tried to do to her. It's time to stop trying to protect her - it's just not working. Xander wakes and calls down, and Buffy sends him to get some rope. Before he goes, Anya teleports into the crater and tells Buffy and Dawn that Willow's going to end the world at a buried Satanic temple on King Men's Bluff. Meanwhile, Willow is raising said temple from the ground. Anya explains that followers of Prosopeksa(###todo-spelling), a powerful she-demon, intended to use her effigy to estroy the world, but died in the temple during an earthquake which swallowed it whole in 1932. Willow intends to finish what they started and end the world. Giles has told Anya that there's no way that Buffy or anyone can stop her. Buffy asks if Giles is okay, and Anya says she doesn't think he's going to make it. She teleports away, and Dawn's close to giving up, but Buffy says she's not going out without her fight. It's her duty and her calling to fight right until the end.

Willow contacts Buffy telepathically and tells her the only way she can stop the world's pain is to end it. Willow recognises Buffy's unwillingness to give up, but doesn't want to fight her herself. She makes demons materialise from the soil and dirt around Buffy and Dawn, all with large crab-like claws. Buffy tries to ward them off, but they just keep coming - Buffy needs Dawn's help and passes her the spare sword. "I've got your back." Willow begins her incantations at the temple and the ground shakes, as Anya thanks Giles for soming to try and help - even if it means he's made Willow more powerful. Xander finds Willow at the temple and she tells him to get out of the way. He refuses, so she uses magic to blast him out of the way. He falls to the floor and Willow flinches - Giles feels Willow's sympathy for Xander and tells Anya it's not over. Dawn's close to getting seriously shredded and Buffy tells her she'll be there to help soon - but Dawn impresses her sister with a somersault over to her weapon followed by a swift demon-beheading. "What, you think I never watched you?" More demons crawl from the dirt and the sisters continue to fight, side by side.

Xander stands up again. Willow tells him he can't stop it, but Xander asks where else he'd want to go - the world's going to end, and naturally he'd want to be with his lifetime friend. Willow mocks Xander's plan to stop her by declaring his love, but Xander continues. She's going to end the world, but he still wants to hang - he loves her. If he's going to die, it's by her side, and if she's going to end the world, she should start with him. "You think I won't?" she asks. "It doesn't matter," he replies. "I'll still love you." Willow lashes out at him, causing nasty red gashes on his face. "I love you." She lashes out again, cutting his chest, and we see a tear roll down her cheek. "I love you." Willow tells him to shut up, and attempts to hurt him but her magic is failing her, and she's breaking. "I love you, Willow." She tries again, but a few mere sparks fly. "I love you." Willow's power has run dry and he walks up to her. She beats at his chest, collapsing into tears, then falls to the ground where Xander embraces her. @{i}"I love you." @{ui}

Buffy and Dawn's soil-demons disintegrate and Giles manages to get up, despite his pain. He says Willow's been stopped - and she's alive. Giles explains that he intended for Willow to take his magic - the "true essence of magic" - in the hope that it would tap into what little humanity she had left. And it worked - giving Xander the opportunity to talk her round and save them all. Dawn says it's over - the world didn't end - and Buffy bursts into tears. Dawn asks if that's happy crying and Buffy says of course it is. "Do you think I wanted the world to end?" Dawn's not so sure, and Buffy tells her she's sorry for ever wanting to be gone. It's going to be okay now, it hasn't been, but it will be. Buffy admits she was wrong to protect Dawn from the world - now she wants to show it to her. As Willow cries in Xander's arms, Anya helps Giles out of the wreck of the Magic Box, and Jonathan and Andrew leave the country, Buffy and Dawn climb out of the crater and walk together in the sun.

Spike, having endured the trials, is now entitled to his reward - to be returned to his former self. "Very well," replies the demon. "We will return... your soul!"

@{b}Notes@{ub}

I always knew Xander would save the world. Didn't expect it to be Willow trying to end it though.

The emotional balance of this episode's conclusion is slightly awkward - Giles' "my plan worked all along" speech is little too cheesy for my liking, as is Buffy's "I got it all wrong" line. On the flipside, Willow and Xander's final scene is brilliantly acted and shot, and Buffy and Dawn's walk in the sun, looking at the beauty of the world says way more than Buffy's cheesy lines, and could have done the job without them. Finally, the scene showing Spike's near-lifeless body at the end is well-shot, making us believe for a second of sadness that Spike has died. The prospect of Spike returning to Sunnydale with a soul is interesting - will he and Buffy be able to re-kindle their relationship, and if so, will it be any healthier this time around? Only time will tell.

Finally, did the magic-fight between Giles and Willow remind anyone else of Pokémon?

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "LESSONS" "Buffy.guide: Lessons"

@{b}Lessons@{ub}
7ABB01

Istanbul: a girl runs through the night, chased by two robed, unknown assailants. She puts up a good fight, but they overtake her. One of the men raises a glinting knife above her, and stabs.

Meanwhile, in Sunnydale, Buffy </shows/buffy/bios/characters/buffy.shtml> is teaching Dawn </shows/buffy/bios/characters/dawn.shtml> the tricks of the slaying trade. Dawn fumbles and nearly gets chomped, but her sister backs her up. They lament the return of something they both dread: Sunnydale High School, rebuilt on its original site. Right over the Hellmouth.

Halfway around the world, Giles </shows/buffy/bios/characters/giles.shtml> has brought Willow </shows/buffy/bios/characters/willow.shtml> to England to help her recover. She's being schooled in a coven to control her power, and is learning how everything in the universe is connected. She struggles in her understanding and yearns to be the Willow she once was, but Giles reassures her by saying, "We all are who we are, no matter how much we may appear to have changed."

The next morning at the Summers house, Dawn gets ready for the first day of school, and a well-dressed Xander </shows/buffy/bios/characters/xander.shtml> arrives with the architectural plan for the new building. He assures Buffy there are no nasties lurking, and he would know, since he's involved in the construction at the site. Buffy accompanies Dawn to school and they meet the new principal, Robin Wood. Dawn takes off for class, and Buffy wanders around her old stomping ground.

In the bathroom, Buffy spies a small, curious-looking charm. Thinking nothing of it, Buffy looks up in the mirror. Surprise! There's a dead girl behind her who doesn't look happy. Another dead guy leaps out at Buffy shouting, "Get out, get out, get out!" There's definitely something fishy going on. The Slayer busts into Dawn's classroom just as the girl is awkwardly introducing herself to the class, then embarrasses her even further by declaring she's in danger. When Buff's unable to back up her claim, she slinks out of the classroom.

At a café, Anya </shows/buffy/bios/characters/anya.shtml> and her demon pal Halfrek drink coffee and insult the lovestruck couple singing in the corner. Halfrek tries to be kind to Anya, but she makes it known that gossip among the demon community says Anya's gone soft, ever since Xander. But more importantly, there's also talk that there's something brewing lately. Something bad.

Back at the school, Buffy finds Xander and fills him in on the ghosties in the bathroom, while across campus, Dawn is attacked by a pencil-wielding dead guy. After excusing herself to the bathroom (bad choice), Dawn hears crying in one of the stalls and discovers a frightened girl. Suddenly, familiar ghosts appear, and the two are dragged through the floor, leaving a rather large hole in the brand new tile.

Dawn awakens with her new friend in the basement of the school, and they find another lost student who was just looking for a place to smoke. But Dawn is armed with a gift Buffy gave her that morning: a cell phone. When Buffy locates the zombies, a fight ensues, and it becomes clear they're spirits of the dead killed on school grounds angry that the Slayer failed to protect them. Buffy gets past them and throws open a door expecting to see Dawn, only to discover a disheveled and scarred Spike </shows/buffy/bios/characters/_.shtml>, who speaks in riddles. He manages to tell Buffy that the dead guys are manifestations from a spell and a talisman for the spell has to be destroyed.

After another call from Dawn, Buffy phones Xander to fill him in on the talisman deal. Buffy locates Dawn and fends off the zombies, while Xander storms the hole-y bathroom to locate and destroy the charm. When he does, the dead guys disappear, but it remains unclear who cast the spell.

Out of the school basement, Buffy comforts Dawn and her new friends as the principal looks on. After seeing the connection she made with the kids, he offers Buffy a part-time position mentoring troubled students. She jumps at the chance.

Spike's still below, and he's confronted with a being unlike any other in Sunnydale. Well, sort of. First it appears to be Warren. Then it morphs into Glory, then Adam, the Mayor, Drusilla, the Master. All dead, but maybe not so much. As the Master talks of the wild ride coming to Sunnydale, he adds, "It's not about right. It's not about wrong." The being morphs into a final image -- Buffy -- and concludes, "It's about power."

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "BENEATHYOU" "Buffy.guide: Beneath You"

@{b}Beneath You@{ub}
7ABB02

Frankfurt: a young punkish girl sprints frantically through the city, chased by two robed baddies whose gleaming daggers look familiar. They catch her, killing her instantly. They depart, but the girl opens deadened, vacant eyes and says, "From beneath you, it devours." At that moment, Buffy awakens from a nightmare about the dead girl, and echoes her final words. She knows there are other girls out there like her, dying, doomed.

The next morning on their way to Sunnydale High, Xander, Buffy and Dawn discuss Buffy's new gig. When the Slayer asks her new employer how she got the job without college credentials, he responds that the students need someone they can relate to, and she is it. She sets off in an unsuccessful search for Spike, who earlier that morning had been ranting and raving in the school basement, terrified of something he couldn't see. 

Willow prepares to leave England, and while she's afraid of screwing up again, she's more frightened that her friends will reject her. Giles does his best to convince her it's time, and she goes on her way.

That night, a young woman, Nancy, walks her dog, only to have it unceremoniously sucked into the ground by a big and growly worm. Screaming, Nancy takes off running and literally bumps into Xander, who brings her to Buffy's. They make a plan to go after the thing, and Spike appears in the doorway, prepared to lend a hand. It's strange--he looks totally normal, well dressed, good hair, the works. He lets it slip that Buffy has already seen him back in town, and Xander and Dawn are livid.

Buffy knows she needs Spike's help, so she hesitantly accepts, and sends Xander to take Nancy home. Buff and Spike check out the hole where the dog got munched, and Buffy is clearly spooked, remembering Spike's attempted rape. She can't forgive him, but senses something different about him. He doesn't fill her in on the whole soul thing, but does say that whatever ate the dog is long gone.

After Xander walks Nancy home, the two start making eyes at each other when that pesky worm returns and rips open the floor to attack. They make a break for it, running high enough up some stairs so the worm can't get to them. Nancy starts to crack, complaining that things can't get much worse, especially after her recent breakup with an abusive boyfriend, Ronnie.

Xander has a thought, and asks if Nancy has done any wishing lately about the guy. Turns out she did, and Anya's to blame for turning Ronnie into a worm. The gang (plus Nancy) confronts the demon at the Bronze, but she is unapologetic for having turned him not just into a teeny tiny worm, but a giant Sluggoth Demon.

When Anya looks at Spike, she sees something new: a soul. To keep her from revealing his secret, Spike hauls off and punches Anya more than once, and both their demon faces are revealed. Buffy breaks in and pummels Spike in return as he taunts her for taking out her repressed anger on him. Before she can do any real damage to the Vamp, Xander realizes Nancy is gone, and Buffy takes off after her.

On the street, Nancy is going home when the worm comes tearing after her, and Buffy (with Spike following) literally swings to her rescue. Spike prepares to spear the worm, but there's only one problem: at the moment he stabs the thing, Anya reverses the spell and the worm turns back into a very human Ronnie. Since his chip is still in place, Spike cries out in pain after harming the human. He loses it, practically switching personalities as Buffy calls for an ambulance to tend to Ronnie's injury. Spike warns of the Big Bad coming, repeating, "From beneath you, it devours." He takes off, and Buffy trails him wondering what's up.

She finds him at a church and, through his ravings, deduces he's gotten his soul back, all for her. Now Spike is dealing with the guilt from his past, compounded by voices in his head, and the voice of the demon that's coming. He wants to rest and slumps against a cross. Buffy watches as the smoke rises from his burning skin. 

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "SAMETIMESAMEPLACE" "Buffy.guide: Same Time, Same Place"

@{b}Same Time, Same Place@{ub}
7ABB03

Buffy, Xander and Dawn wait at the airport for Willow to return from England. Buffy is a little nervous about what to say, but Xander isn't concerned, even after Buffy mentions that Willow left her training early. They continue to wait until everyone has left the plane, but Willow doesn't show up.

Literally.

Seems that Willow did leave the plane, hoping for a reunion with her pals, but she walked right by them--they were invisible to her. And vice versa.

That night, a boy tags a wall with spray paint, until his work is cut short by a long-nailed, shadowy figure that jumps out at him with an unearthly scream. Apparently, he should have found a more constructive use for his artistic talent.

Willow goes home to an empty house. She reacquaints herself with the room she shared with Tara, briefly reliving the moment she lost her. There's no one around to comfort her, so she lies on the couch, despondent. During those same moments, Buffy, Xander and Dawn get home to an equally empty house. They commune on the couch, not realizing they're sharing space with Willow, who's there, but not.

The next day, a solitary Willow heads over to the dilapidated Magic Box. Anya is still cleaning the debris out of the store, and she's not exactly thrilled to see the woman who destroyed it in the first place. Ultimately sympathetic, Anya sends Will in the direction of the new high school, since Buffy's got "some kind of job helping junior deviants." Willow doesn't find them on school grounds, but she does find something particularly gross: a dead body.

Of course, Xander and Buffy are there, checking out the very same body of the dead spray-painting boy. One detail spooks them: the body is flayed. Their first thought: Willow's back.

At the school, Willow finds Spike talking nonsense in the basement (surprise!). He's no help to her after she explains about the murdered boy, but it turns out he's actually having two conversations: one with Willow, and one with Buffy and Xander. Buffy incorrectly infers from Spike's confused chatter that Willow is involved in the boy's death.

Willow goes back to Anya, who reluctantly agrees to help with a locator spell to find demons in the area. After the spell indicates a powerful demon in the woods, Anya confides that wreaking vengeance all over the place isn't as fun as it once was. Willow relates completely, and the two come to an understanding.

At the Summers house, the gang researches demons that flay skin. Though Buffy still suspects Willow, Dawn finds a demon called Gnarl that sounds about right: it flays, and eats, the skin of its victims. Charming. They enlist Spike to track the demon, since it seems the baddie will have left a trail of blood to its abode. Spike leads them to a cave not realizing Willow is there as well. Willow crawls in the cave at the same time the gang does, and when Gnarl takes a swipe at Dawn, the Scoobies bolt and seal the cave, trapping Willow inside. Gnarl taunts the witch for being left behind by her friends, then lashes out at her, paralyzing her with his poison.

Back at home, Dawn is paralyzed from the poison as well, and Buffy learns that the paralysis lasts until Gnarl is killed. When Anya arrives to stay with Dawn, she reveals that Willow is probably still at the cave, fighting the demon on her own. Suddenly Anya's demon expertise is in demand, and her friends drag her off to the cave to help Willow.

Gnarl is enjoying carefully peeling strips of skin from Willow's stomach when the gang bursts in. They still can't see Willow, but Anya can. At the vengeance demon's instruction, Buffy gouges out the eyes of Gnarl and kills him, releasing both Willow and Dawn from their paralysis. Soon, an injured Willow reappears before their eyes, incredibly grateful that her friends haven't left her alone.

In the morning, Buffy interrupts Willow as she's meditating, using magic to heal herself. Willow reveals that she inadvertently made herself invisible by thinking she wasn't ready to see her friends. Buffy regretfully admits she suspected Willow was the killer, but her friend understands. Weakly, Willow continues to meditate, but Buffy reaches out her hands to help, and they begin to heal her injuries together.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "HELP7ABB04" "Buffy.guide: Help"

@{b}Help@{ub}
7ABB04

Buffy and the gang scout out a funeral home, looking for a potential vampire. They are all stressing lately, especially Buffy, who is gearing up for her first official day as a counselor. Her stress level doesn't stop her, however, from easily dusting a matronly vamp as she rises from her coffin.

The next day, Xander and Willow stroll in the sun, catching up, and Willow is still insecure over her ability to control her powers. She knows the Big Bad everyone's going on about is coming, but she wonders if she'll be able to help. It becomes clear that they are in a cemetery, and Willow makes her first visit to Tara's grave. She lays stones atop the headstone, then kneels and traces Tara's name tenderly.

At Sunnydale High, Buffy faces her first victims--uh, students. She handles varied issues with good advice, but one student stands out: Cassie. She is troubled, and lets it slip that on Friday she's going to die. At first, Buffy believes the girl is suicidal, but soon suspects that Cassie's a psychic. Quickly, Buff takes advantage of her secret weapon, Dawn, who gently insinuates herself into a library conversation between Cassie and her friend Mike. Mike bugs his pal to go to the Winter Formal, but Cassie refuses time and again, convinced she won't be around for the dance.

Worried that Cassie may be the subject of parental abuse, Buffy and Xander make an ill-conceived visit to the girl's home. Though her father is obviously three sheets to the wind, he appears to genuinely love his daughter. As the pair leave, they encounter Cassie, who thanks them for trying to help, but is eerily resigned to die.

Meanwhile, in the school's library, sinister-looking red-robed figures circle a burning tray. In the tray's center is a photo of Cassie.

Friday comes, and the Scooby gang is still scouring for clues. Buffy hunts down Spike to see if he knows anything, and while he's definitely disturbed about something (as usual), he has nothing new to offer. Buffy checks out Cassie's friend Mike, but he seems totally harmless. She does spy some strange coins tumbling out of a locker during a search by the principal, and connects the coins to something Cassie mentioned during their first meeting. She corners the locker's owner, who spills that some guys are planning to mess with Cassie. Bingo.

That night, the red-robed figures are back, and their leader is Peter, one of the arrogant boys Buffy counseled earlier in the week. The guys are scamming to get rich quick, and Peter figures calling up a demon and offering a human sacrifice might be a good idea. Yeah, right.

Peter starts the ritual, but Buffy tears off a red robe--the guy she grilled earlier finally told her the whole deal. She knocks Peter down easily, but he's already called up a nasty-looking demon, and it wants blood. Buffy's in trouble, but Spike comes to the rescue, brandishing a flaming torch. Buff grabs the torch and goes after the demon while Peter takes a walloping from Spike, who flinches from the chip in his head with every punch. Buffy defeats the demon and Spike frees Cassie, who whispers to a confused Spike, "She'll tell you. Someday, she'll tell you."

Buffy leads Cassie to the library door and saves her a second time from a booby trap. However, all her efforts are for naught: Cassie's eyes soon go blank, and she crumples to the floor. Turns out the end was inevitable: there was a hole in her heart.

The group gathers to mourn, and Dawn takes the death of her new friend hard. Buffy wonders about the futility of trying to lend a hand to students when sometimes there's nothing she can do. But still she returns to the school, and does her best to prepare to help the next troubled teen that comes her way.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "SELFLESS" "Buffy.guide: Selfless"

@{b}Selfless@{ub}
7ABB05

Willow unpacks and settles back in her old room with the gang's help. As they set things up, the subject turns to Anya, and how she's eased up on the whole vengeance thing.

Little do they know Anya's responsible for the deaths of twelve frat boys -- looks like her latest vengeance spell wreaked a little more havoc than she may have intended. "What have I done?" she asks herself before trying to scrub her hands clean of blood. Thinking back, she recalls her life in...

Sjornjost, circa 880. Anya, originally called Aud, plays with -- gasp -- bunnies! She's a bit jealous that Olaf, her sweetheart, might be running around on her with a bar matron. Anya was kind and generous in those days, but according to Olaf, seemed to still have the annoying characteristic of always speaking her mind and taking things literally. Some things never change.

On the UC Sunnydale campus, Willow successfully begs her way back into classes with a professor. Over the prof's shoulder, she sees Anya stumbling out of the frat house, looking freaked. Despite Anya's claims of a new and sexually virile fraternity boyfriend, Willow knows something's up. She investigates the frat house and is horrified by the discovery of the dead boys. She hears a cry, and finds a girl sobbing in the closet mumbling, "I take it back" over and over. Apparently the girl's boyfriend had broken up with her in front of his friends, and she'd made a wish that they'd all know what it felt like to have their hearts ripped out. A demonic spider conjured up by Anya appeared and took care of the wish. The very same spider attacks Willow, but she uses magic to toss it through a window. For a moment, though, there's an eerie glimpse of Dark Willow as she fights the demon, which unnerves her.

Back in 880, the townspeople chase after a huge troll -- it's Olaf! Aud cast a little spell on him after discovering his little infidelity with the bar matron. The demon D'Hoffryn appears, impressed by Aud's magical ingenuity, and asks Aud to join his demonic family. He calls her Anyanka, and says if she'll join with him, she will realize her true self.

In Anya's apartment (current day), Hallie visits a guilt-ridden Anya. She's reeling from the deaths of the frat boys, and Hallie does her best to console her. Anya is relieved, until an extremely pissed off Willow arrives. The witch demands an explanation of the bloodshed, and though Anya declares, "They got what they deserved," she still seems unsure of herself.

Meanwhile, Buffy and Xander are on the hunt for the spider, but it finds them first. It attacks Buffy, but she fights it off and chops it with a well-aimed ax. After they return home, Willow fills them in on Anya. Xander is furious that Willow didn't tell them about Anya's evil deeds earlier, but he falters when Buffy reveals that she has to kill Anya. Xander argues against it -- he still loves his ex. But Buffy must draw the line somewhere. It's her duty as the Slayer. Xander leaves to warn Anya, and when Buffy asks Willow to help her, Will turns her down. After Buffy leaves, the witch calls on D'Hoffryn for a little chat.

Xander finds Anya at the frat house, but Buffy's right behind him. The Slayer is armed with a sword, and she uses it with force when Anya goes all demon-y. Buffy stabs Anya in the heart, but that's not enough to fell a vengeance demon. Buffy is about to finish her off when Xander intervenes, much to Anya's dismay. D'Hoffryn appears in a cloud of smoke at Willow's behest, and Anya pleads with him to take back what she did to the frat boys. She's willing to sacrifice herself. D'Hoffryn goes for the throat -- he takes back the spell and revives the boys, but ends the life of Anya's dearest friend Hallie instead. Anya is devastated, and Xander tries to offer comfort. However, the former demon needs to find out who she really is on her own, and with tears streaming down her cheeks, she walks off into the night.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "HIM" "Buffy.guide: Him"

@{b}Him@{ub}
7ABB06

On the Sunnydale high football field, the Summers sisters discuss the complexities of love and relationships. Dawn wonders why on earth people spend so much time driving each other insane by getting involved in tempestuous relationships, but gets distracted when her gaze suddenly slo-mo's upon R.J., a handsome young buck of a football player. Dawn's irrational affection spurs her to make a total fool of herself, more than once, in front of R.J. and his pals. It's painful. When Buffy tries to comfort her devastated sister, Dawn won't have it: she lashes out at her sister, saying that no one so dysfunctional as Buffy would understand what she's going through. Ouch.

In school, Dawn overhears R.J.'s friend O'Donnell gloating about how he's replaced R.J. as starting quarterback in the upcoming football game. Dawn goes after O'Donnell to confront him, and in the heat of the moment shoves the kid down a flight of stairs. He ends up in the hospital, and Dawn ends up in Principal Wood's office to explain the "accident." Wood and Buffy believe Dawn when she lies that O'Donnell slipped, until the girl mentions how R.J. will now be replacing the injured boy as quarterback. After Dawn leaves the office, R.J. approaches her and asks if she'd want to meet up with him after football practice. Of course she jumps at the chance.

That night at the Bronze, Buffy, Xander and Willow see R.J. dancing with a sleazy girl dressed in a revealing outfit, and Buffy is relieved Dawn isn't there to witness the object of her affection getting down with a ho. That is, until the ho reveals herself to be none other than Dawn. When Buffy confronts her, Dawn leaves in a huff, declaring that Buffy's jealous because someone's finally paying her some attention. In the alley, Dawn gets attacked by R.J.'s ex-girlfriend and they end up in a screaming, hair-pulling catfight. Buffy breaks it up, but both girls have definitely lost it over the guy.

At school the next day, R.J. gets a talking-to from Wood over getting girls to do his homework for him, then gets another talking-to from Buffy over Dawn. But when R.J. slips his on letterman's jacket, Buffy's eyes glaze over and she's smitten. Later that evening, Buffy lies to Dawn that R.J. felt that Dawn came on too strong with him. For some reason, she's scheming to get the guy for herself.

Back at school, Buffy calls R.J. out of class and drags him into an empty classroom. Soon, she's got him in a liplock atop a desk, and he's not complaining. Dawn sees them, and stumbles out of the school crying. Xander finds her, and walks in on Buffy and her young stud still making out. He puts the kibosh on that fast.

It's a love spell, and Xander gets Willow to check out R.J.'s family online. While Buff and Dawnie have a yelling match over who R.J. loves more, the gang finds a listing for R.J.'s older brother, a bullying jock and former classmate of Xander's. The brother, a no-longer-bullying pizza delivery guy, says that the jacket was a simple hand-me-down from his dad, and he passed it on to R.J.

That jacket is mighty powerful, since when R.J. shows up at the Summers house to see Buffy, both Anya and Willow get bitten by the love bug. When the four women convene, they go all Witches of Eastwick as they shout about how they will each get R.J. to love them the most. Willow prepares to cast a spell on him (turning him into a girl), Anya sets out to rob a bank, Buffy gets ready to kill Wood so he'll leave R.J. alone, and Dawn, seeing no way to compete with her sister, lies down on some railroad tracks. Spike and Xander interrupt all their efforts, and Buffy rescues Dawn from the tracks, assuring her that no guy, even one as hot as R.J., is worth dying for.

Tentative allies Spike and Xander construct and execute a complex plan: they tackle R.J., rip his jacket off, and burn it. The spell is broken. The girls are back to normal, embarrassed about their crazy behavior. Except Anya, who seems to have some extra cash on her hands and offers to spring for ice cream.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "CONVERSATIONS" "Buffy.guide: Conversations With Dead People"

@{b}Conversations With Dead People@{ub}
7ABB07

Nighttime in Sunnydale. Buffy's on patrol, Spike's at the Bronze, Willow's studying at the campus library and Dawn's home alone. A familiar duo heads for town: Jonathan and Andrew. What's left of the Evil Trio has a plan to fix what went wrong last year, and in the process, end the demonic nightmares they've been having while on the run.

With the house to herself, Dawn lives it up, eating anchovy (why, Dawn, why?) pizza and dancing around the house. She hears banging noises once in a while, but at first she's able to brush them off. While watching television, she realizes there's something wiggy going on. Her TV won't change channels or even shut off when unplugged. The banging gets worse, and when Dawn checks outside, wind practically blows her across the room. It's clear she's in trouble. All the appliances in the house come to life, and once she smashes them, she hears her mother's voice in the silence.

Buffy stakes out (so to speak) a fresh grave in the local cemetery, and starts to fight with a new Vamp. They go at it until the bloodsucker, Holden, recognizes Buffy from high school, and they spend a few minutes catching up. A former psych major and lover of tae kwon do, Holden doesn't know much about being a Vampire, so Buffy fills him in on his new status, as well as on her role as the Slayer. They have an oddly therapeutic chat, discussing Buffy's fear of commitment and slew of bad relationships. She confides that her last relationship was incredibly complex and confusing, and the aftermath has left her emotionally decimated. It's intense. Holden and Buffy agree not to take their inevitable fight to the death personally, but shortly thereafter Holden sucker-punches Buffy with a Virgin Mary statue and their duel starts up again.

Meanwhile, Willow's having some weirdness of her own at the library when she's confronted with the specter of Cassie Newton. Cassie says she's in contact with Tara and suggests that Tara cannot be there herself because of Willow's destructive behavior following her death. Foreseeing Willow's path, Cassie warns Willow never to use magic again. Willow assures her black magic is off her list, but Cassie insists that any magic will only lead to darkness. Though Will is sure she'll be okay, Cassie says no, "You're going to kill everybody." Yikes.

Jonathan and Andrew break into Sunnydale High, excavation equipment and architectural plans in hand. Their plan: find the Seal of Danzalthar, tell Buffy about it, and help her save Sunnydale. They'll find redemption, then maybe Buffy will invite them to join the Scooby gang (yeah, right). There's only one problem: Andrew's being coerced by the ghost of Warren, whose plan doesn't sound anything like Jonathan's. Andrew's looking to become a god, which doesn't bode well for the whole "saving Sunnydale" thing. Warren's ghost points Andrew in the direction of the Seal, and the guys start digging in the place they believe it's buried.

Dawn calls out for her mother, but something seems to be preventing Joyce from speaking. Something bad. Dawn sees flashes of her mother in the pose she died in, but something menacing is hovering over her. Frantic and hysterical, Dawn tries to phone Buffy but canŐt get through. Finally, she begins a spell (learned from Willow) to cast out the evil. It fights back, but ultimately she defeats it. Joyce materializes in a bright light, but delivers some disturbing news: "When it's very bad, Buffy won't choose you. She'll be against you." Dawn doesn't know how to react, and Joyce fades away into the darkness.

Horrified by Cassie's revelation, Willow begs for a solution. Cassie says if she can't stop using magic, another choice remains: eternal rest. Willow becomes suspicious, especially when Cassie adds that she'll get to be with Tara again in the afterlife, and her friends will all be safe. When Will demands to know what's really going on, Cassie reveals that she's the Big Bad that's been foretold. "From beneath you, it devours," repeats Willow, and the Big Bad replies, "Not it. Me." It morphs, then vanishes.

In the cemetery, Buffy and Holden continue fighting, talking, fighting, talking. Holden draws it out of her that her last relationship was with a Vamp, and that subconsciously she wanted to be punished for feeling superior to her friends and the rest of the world. When Buffy lets it slip that her last boyfriend was Spike, Holden recognizes the name.

Andrew and Jonathan unearth the Seal of Danzalthar, discussing what they want once they complete their task. Jonathan misses his old life, his friends, the real world. Andrew, however, is bitter over his past, and his anger no doubt helps him as he stabs Jonathan once the Seal is uncovered. Jonathan's body falls upon the Seal, which illuminates when his blood spills onto it.

Spike, meanwhile, has been wooing a young lady in the Bronze, and after he walks her home, he Vamps up and takes a bite out of her. Across town, Holden reveals that Spike is the Vampire that sired him. Buffy dusts Holden, then reels in shocked disbelief over the news about Spike.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "SLEEPER" "Buffy.guide: Sleeper"

@{b}Sleeper@{ub}
7ABB08

Buffy anxiously awakens Xander in the middle of the night following her discovery that Spike sired Holden. Spike has been staying with Xander, but the Vamp is out for the evening. In fact, Spike is burying his latest kill in a shallow grave as he hums a jaunty tune.

In London, a man bursts into a home to find the body of a dead girl on the floor. Though he makes a valiant effort to defend himself, he takes a knife in the back from a now-familiar black robed figure.

Xander and Buffy argue over Spike's current status: killer (Xander's opinion) versus non-killer (Buffy's). Spike gets home, and when Buffy subtly questions him about his late-night doings, she's surprised he doesn't flinch at a mention of Holden. Spike heads off to bed, and Buffy decides someone needs to keep an eye on him. Anya's enlisted, and though she's nervous, she agrees to stay at Xander's and keep watch.

Buffy gets home to find Willow putting Dawn to bed. The girl was freaked, and Buffy is devastated to learn she saw the ghost (maybe) of their mother. Buffy doesn't know whom to trust about recent events, and determines she needs proof of Spike's misdeeds either way.

Outside Spike's room, Anya is nervous. Twitchy. She's convinced that if Spike is killing, he's keeping trophies of his victims in his room (like drinking their blood isn't enough). She enters his lair carefully and searches, but he awakens and grabs her. She fumbles a bit till she comes up with an explanation: sex. She wants sex, with Spike! The Vamp is flattered (sort of) but turns her down, and Anya escapes unscathed. When Spike departs for the night, Anya calls Buffy.

The Slayer trails Spike through a crowded town square and spots him chatting up a young woman. She loses the two of them in the crowd, and Spike pulls his willing target into a dark alley. He's set to dig in when he sees Buffy over his shoulder, but Spike's getting duped by the Big Bad too. The vision of Buffy seductively encourages him to make the kill, and he eagerly complies.

The real Buffy catches up with Spike later that night, demanding to know the truth. Spike denies he's been killing, and accuses his ex of being jealous. He's very convincing, and is actually shocked when Buffy throws the subject of Holden in his face. Confused, Spike again denies it, but his memory is a little fuzzy.

The next night, Xander tries to keep Spike at home, but gets knocked out for his trouble. At the Bronze, Spike asks around about the woman he'd been there with the other night. A woman approaches and flirts with him; she turns Vamp on him and offers to pick off the crowd. He refuses and she attacks, insisting that since he sired her, he ought to give her a hand. Horrified, he stakes her.

Outside the Bronze, Buffy questions the bouncer, who recalls a Billy Idol wannabe leaving with a different girl every night. Her phone rings; it's Spike, wanting to see her. He's starting to remember doing very bad things.

They meet in the basement of a creepy abandoned house, and Buffy is edgy (and armed). Spike points to the dirt floor of the basement: he's been burying his kills there. The morphing First demon lurks in the background in the guise of Spike, humming. Real Spike hears the tune and flips out, attacking Buffy as the dead rise from the ground. The new Vamps grab Buffy and offer her to Spike, and he takes a lick of blood from a cut on her arm.

In a flash, all SpikeŐs recent crimes come flooding back into his memory, and he jerks away in horror. With that, Buffy makes quick work of the new Vampires. The First whispers to Spike that since he failed, Buffy will kill him. Spike's ready to die to escape the demon haunting him, but instead Buffy sits with him. The Vamp breaks down in tears, begging her for help. Reluctantly she agrees, as the First looks on in disgust. Buff takes Spike home, wanting to keep him close so the gang can learn everything they can about the Big Bad.

In London, Giles bursts into the home of the dead girl, and finds the other man stabbed. The man's eyes fly open. "It's started," he gurgles, just as a ghoulish robed figure swings an axe at Giles' head. Hello, cliffhanger.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "NEVERLEAVEME" "Buffy.guide: Never Leave Me"

@{b}Never Leave Me@{ub}
7ABB09

Andrew struts through town in a long black leather duster, doing his darndest to look tough. Warren needs him to kill again, since the Seal of Danzalthar needs more blood than the dead Jonathan had to offer. Warren morphs into Jonathan and tells Andrew that being dead is pretty cool. But he needs Andrew to make another kill, and soon.

Buffy's got Spike tied up in her room (to a chair, alas), and he's hungry. Buffy sends Willow out for some animal blood to tide him over and dials up the Watcher's Council looking for Giles. They are uncooperative, but with good reason: they have no idea where Giles is either, and they are desperate to locate him.

Andrew tries to complete his killing task with a teeny, tiny pig. Even the pig is too wily for him, though, and escapes, so Andrew heads to the butcher shop for some blood: a serious tactical error. As he's leaving, Willow bumps into him and chases him down an alley. Despite his false bravado (and leather jacket), he's no match for an angry Willow. She drags him home with her and demands to know why he needs the blood.

Buffy feeds Spike some of the animal blood to slake his thirst. The Vamp confesses he can't remember killing, but he knows he's been blacking out. He explains the mechanics of how he got his soul back to be with Buffy again, but finally realizes that when they were together last year, Buffy was only using him. "You hated yourself and took it out on me," he laments.

Anya and Xander convincingly play Good Cop/Bad Cop on Andrew. Anya hauls off and backhands the pipsqueak (she's really into her role), and after a bit more pushing, he breaks. In the other room, however, Spike is alone, and the morphing First Spike appears and hums a little tune. Upon returning to Spike, Buffy can sense something off, but is still taken by surprise when the Vamp breaks free of his bonds and smashes through the wall to get to Andrew. He manages to take a bite of the guy before Buffy knocks him unconscious.

The gang regroups downstairs, and oddly, Xander is the one who figures out what may be going on with Spike. He links him with sleeper agents that are triggered by a certain word or event, transforming them into something completely different from their normal personalities. The tune the First is humming triggers the change in Spike.

Spike ends up chained in the basement, and Buff goes to him to explain their theory. He doesn't care, and tries to scare her into killing him. It doesn't work; Buffy honestly believes he can find redemption, and she won't let him throw that chance away. Just then, black-robed guys storm the house, breaking windows and coming through walls. It's an ambush.

Meanwhile, in an empty field Principal Wood is digging a grave. As he was leaving work that night, something drew him to the basement of the school. He found Jonathan's body, and brought him to the field. Whoa.

The Scoobies are nearly overpowered by the bad guys, also called the Bringers. Buffy and Dawn find some measure of success, and eventually they are able to fight off the baddies. Their eyes are finally visible, eerily replaced with symbols. Buffy suddenly recalls seeing the men before, the Christmas it snowed in Sunnydale, years ago. She knows now: it's the First that's coming. Suddenly she remembers Spike. She races to the basement, but he's gone. He's the one they wanted all along.

In London, the Watchers' Council makes plans to mobilize against the coming demon. They've been hit from all sides, but decide to head for the Hellmouth. Sounds like a good idea, but there's one problem: the building explodes in a ball of flame. No more Watchers' Council.

The Bringers have Spike at the Hellmouth, and they nail him to a huge carved symbol as he screams. They carve figures into his skin as the First morphs into Buffy, and she taunts him mercilessly. Finally, they hang him over the Seal of Danzalthar and watch his blood fall upon it. The Seal illuminates, then finally breaks open, delivering a huge, freaky-looking and very gross, uh, thing. It's a Vampirish, demony something-or-other, and it definitely looks pissed.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "BRINGONTHENIGHT" "Buffy.guide: Bring On The Night"

@{b}Bring On The Night@{ub}
7ABB10

The gang is having zero luck finding any information on the First, "the original evil, the one that came before anything else." Buffy's worried about Spike, and runs herself ragged. Her mother comes to her in a dream and begs her to rest. When Buffy awakens, she's seriously wigged. Should she trust the dream?

Andrew finally wakes up and leads everyone to the bloodied Seal of Danzalthar. They decide to cover it, and as they're leaving with shovels in hand, they run into Principal Wood. He's also carrying a shovel, coming up with an excuse as lame as the one Buffy and Dawn offer him (Burying a time capsule? Please.) There is definitely something weird going on with him.

At home, Willow tries to find the Biggest Bad with a locator spell, but it backfires. The evil possesses her momentarily, exploding out of her and terrifying everyone in the process. When it departs, Willow is horrified and devastated, realizing that any time she uses her power, she is liable to hurt someone. Buffy cradles Will, then hastily decides to hunt down the First for harming her friends. At the door, she's startled to find her former Watcher alive and well, flanked by three would-be Slayers. Giles dryly explains, "We have a slight Apocalypse."

He gives the Scoobies the rundown on the situation: the WatchersŐ Council has been destroyed, and most of the potential Slayers have been picked off over the past few months. The First's plan is to kill off all the future Slayers and their Watchers, then annihilate the current ones, leaving nothing to fight the coming evil. The only plus is that Giles was able to save a few Council records by stealing them prior to the explosion. He lays the responsibility of saving the world squarely on Buffy's shoulders. Great.

Meanwhile, the Ubervamp from the Seal has been kicking Spike around for some time. The First observes in the guise of Drusilla, taunting Spike continuously. Beating, drowning, you name it, they do it to Spike. Dru wants to bring poor Spikey over to the dark side, but he will have none of it. He continues to fight back because of Buffy's faith in him.

While Dawn and Willow set up the Slayettes with food and beds for the night, Giles and Buffy go looking for the place where she first saw the Bringers years before. It was underground near a Christmas tree lot, and (of course) she finds it by falling through some dusty, tattered boards covering a hole in the ground. Immediately, she's pounced on by the Ubervamp. They fight, then fight some more, till Buffy stakes it. Large problem: it doesn't die. More fighting, until Buffy manages to crawl out the hole she fell in. The thing follows her, but luckily, the sun has just risen, and it crawls back into its lair. But it's clear it will come after her again, and soon.

Back home, Buff and Giles fill the newbies in on the whole "end of the world" thing. Giles reveals that the Ubervampire is an ancient, sort of like the Neanderthal of bloodsuckers. Buffy doesn't have much else to go on, so later at work, she does a little computer searching on, of all topics, "evil." Principal Wood hovers, his creep factor skyrocketing when the conversation turns to the long-term effect evil has on those who witness it. Very unnerving.

Joyce makes another dreamscape visit to Buffy, pleading with her to rest. Her message is that evil is everywhere, a part of life, and no one can stop it. Buff jerks awake at her desk, while a neglected student looks on. Oops. Though exhausted, she keeps pushing herself. At home, she arms the junior Slayers so they'll be more prepared.

When the sun goes down, the pressure on the Slayer mounts. Everyone's feeling it, especially Annabelle, one of the Slayers-in-training. She bolts from the house into town, alone and vulnerable. She doesn't get far before the Ubervamp takes her out. Buffy finds her body, and the momentary distraction is enough to give the UV an opening to knock her around. More fighting. They end up in an industrial building, and Buffy's booty gets seriously kicked. She ends up buried under a pile of debris, badly injured.

The gang is at a loss, and Giles has no answers. However, even with her painful injuries, Buffy seems to have embraced the fear and chaos. She's realized there's only one thing to do: instead of waiting for evil to come to her, she must start the war herself. "There's only one thing on this earth more powerful than evil. And that's us."

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "SHOWTIME" "Buffy.guide: Showtime"

@{b}Showtime@{ub}
7ABB11

A new girl, Rona, arrives in town at the bus stop, and a welcoming committee surprises her. Okay, maybe not welcoming: it's the Bringers, ready to attack. Luckily, Buffy saves the day, putting the dudes out of commission fast.

Back home, Will and Kennedy get to know each other upstairs while the rest of the girls worry about the Ubervamp, a.k.a. Turok-Han, undoubtedly headed their way. After Buffy gets back with the new recruit, she's frustrated to discover the gang has no new information on how to defeat the First or to rescue Spike. Giles has one idea, but Anya balks; it involves an oracle called Beljoxa's Eye. The catch is that Anya will have to grovel and beg some of her old demon pals to open up the vortex to get to the oracle. Buffy pleads for her help, for Spike's sake.

Speaking of Spike, he's still strung up underground with the First, who enjoys parading around as Buffy, taunting the Vamp. Spike still believes "she will come for me."

Across town, Anya and Giles try to con the owner of a demon bar into opening the portal so they can have a visit with Beljoxa's Eye. When Anya's offer of sex doesn't tempt the demon (apparently humans aren't a turn-on), Giles dangles the prospect of Buffy killing all of his patrons. That does it. He summons the vortex, and Giles and Anya stumble through.

Willow hears from the Coven in England that another Potential is holed up in a nearby motel, so Buff and Xander set out to retrieve her. In the basement, the girls are training with various weapons and equipment. However, there's one problem: they suck. Big time. None of them are up for the job, so they spend most of the time worrying over their own mortality. One in particular, Eve, nearly has the rest of them convinced that nothing they do can save them. Her attitude is that they'll all get knocked off by the Big Bad, so why bother?

Eve's attitude makes sense when Buffy and Xander find her body in the motel room. She's been dead for days, meaning the First has been wearing her face, hanging around Buffy's house, gathering information. Buff rushes home to confront the First, who has learned all about the Potentials' weaknesses masquerading as Eve. It vanishes, leaving everyone shaken.

Anya and Giles have a chat with Beljoxa's Eye, and it informs them that something has disrupted the line of the Chosen, giving the First a chance to wreak havoc. The Slayer herself is the source of the disruption, and Anya believes that she and the rest of the Scoobies are at fault for bringing Buffy back from the dead last year. Whoops.

Back at the house, Buffy asks Willow to work her mojo to protect the house as the Bringers and the Turok-Han arrive after sundown. Though extremely nervous about practicing her dark craft, Willow does a spell to hold the UV off. The evil is too strong, though, and the gang plus junior Slayers fight through the Bringers and bolt away from the house. While she prepares for a showdown with the Ubervamp, Buffy sends everyone in another direction. But the Turok-Han, determined to pick off the Potentials, follows them instead of fighting Buffy.

The gang arrives at a huge construction site (soon to be the new public library), and they're terrified. Buffy arrives on the heels of the Ubervamp and announces, "Welcome to Thunderdome." Turns out Buffy, Will and Xander planned this turn of events to lure the Turok-Han away from Spike's prison and, with a little luck, kill it. The big fight ensues with a little crossbow action here, a little pickaxe-swinging there. Buffy gets in a few final blows before wrapping a piece of wire around the Vamp's neck and pulling, hard. Poof, it's dead. "Dust, just like the rest of them." There's another reason Buffy put on the performance: to prove to the Junior Slayers that she can fight against evil and win. It seems to do the trick.

The First is a little peeved.

Underground, Spike hangs from his chains, bruised and beaten. He sees Buffy approach with a big knife and tells her, "You can't hurt me," but when he looks into her eyes, he tearfully realizes she's the real thing. She cuts him down and he nearly falls, but she holds him up and leads him home.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "POTENTIAL" "Buffy.guide: Potential"

@{b}Potential@{ub}
7ABB12

In the cemetery, some nervous Slayerettes are on the hunt. From the shadows, a dark figure leaps out and moves in for the kill, knocking down Rona and grabbing Vi around the throat. They'd be dead in a heartbeat except...the Vamp is Spike, and he's helping Buffy train the girls to use their instincts in combating the bad guys. Since the First is in temporary retreat, they need to use this time to learn how to kill. Buff and her ex demonstrate some supposed fighting techniques, but even the girls can sense the heat still simmering between them.

The next day, Buffy is back at her school job, counseling a student, Amanda, who feels like she's weirder than normal when it comes to relationships. Buffy can relate, and ends up going off on a tangent of her own on the subject. It's clear there's one thing on her mind: Spike.

There's a training outing planned for the potentials, to Dawn's dismay. Buff nearly cancels when she hears from Willow that there's another possible Slayer in town, living right under their noses. But Willow talks her into going through with the outing, deciding to do a locator spell while Buffy and the girls are practicing.

Dawn's got a serious inferiority complex going on; apparently the novelty of being the Key has finally worn off. She's always being left out of the loop these days, and it's weighing heavily on her self-esteem. Dawn, Xander, Anya and Andrew hover around Willow during her exceptionally stinky locator spell. When the spell is complete, Dawn is thrown against the front door and is surrounded by a glow, indicating that SHE is the potential Slayer. She's shocked, and so is everyone else. Emotions run high, and no one seems to know what to do with the new information, especially Dawn. She goes to her room to be alone, and overhears the gang debating pros and cons of her new Chosen status. Confused, she climbs out her window and slips away from the house.

The Slayerette outing is a trip to a Demon Bar so the girls can get used to places teeming with inside information. Buffy warns them, "There's not a being in here who wouldn't gladly rip out your throat." However, there's one exception present: Clem! He and Buffy enthusiastically catch up, much to the girls' amusement. At Buffy's request, Clem makes some big monster googly eyes at them and reminds them that despite his friendly appearance, he's still a demon.

While out walking the neighborhood, Dawn runs into Amanda, who's had a bizarre night. She stayed late at Swing choir practice and got jumped by some guy with a crinkled-up face, and somehow she locked the guy in a classroom. Dawn, Future Slayer, decides she's the girl to take on this job. They arrive at the room with the Vamp inside, and are surprised when he leaps down from the ceiling to attack. Dawn gets some good licks in, then grabs Amanda and runs.

Meanwhile, Buffy has the Slayerettes in a crypt, looking for bad guys. They find a body that turns out to be a fresh Vamp, and Buffy takes it on. She's totally in control, unlike Dawn, who's fumbling in her attempts to kill the Vampire at the school. Buffy plays cat-and-mouse with her prey, until she and Spike leave the girls in the crypt with the bloodsucker for a trial by fire. Meanwhile, Dawn and Amanda are about to be taken out by the Vamp when the Bringers inadvertently save the day, bursting through the windows to get to their target. Only the target isn't Dawn; it's Amanda. She's the real potential Slayer.

Luckily, Dawn knows her way around a science lab and turns a big flame on them to escape with Amanda. The rest of the posse shows up just in time (thank goodness for cell phones) and takes on the Bringers. Amanda somehow calls on her instincts and wields a mean stake, dusting the Vampire and doing some damage to a Bringer. Buffy reveals her Slayerness to Amanda, and the student is comically irritated with her. She'd gone to see Buffy earlier that night, since the counselor had said to come to her with her problems. At the front door, she got hit with a strange orange light that made her feel all woozy--Willow's locator spell. Dawn just got caught in the magical crossfire, then later met up with Amanda on the street.

The next morning, the girls (who were obviously successful getting rid of their Vamp the night before), embrace a new understanding of their powers, as well as their new inductee. Dawn's feeling alone and dejected, but Xander comes to the rescue. He knows how she feels, since he's been in the same boat for years. Through his understanding and kindness, he makes Dawn realize that even though she's not a Chosen, she's still special.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "THEKILLERINME" "Buffy.guide: The Killer In Me"

@{b}The Killer In Me@{ub}
7ABB13

To help the Potentials understand their powers, Giles is taking them on a little camping trip for some meditation and visionquesting. After they leave, Buffy greets a chained-up (by choice) Spike downstairs, but is horrified when the Vamp screams out in pain, blood dripping from his nose.

While Buffy worries over the possibility of Spike's chip malfunctioning, Willow brews some tea for Kennedy, who's upstairs nursing a cold. Upon delivering the tea, Will finds Kennedy looking "surprisingly robust and casually dressy" for someone who is ill. Kennedy faked sickness to pursue her own mission: to take Willow on a date. At the Bronze, Kennedy seriously flirts with an off-kilter Will. The Slayerette turns on the charm full throttle as they discuss their histories, and soon Willow is quietly receptive to the attention.

Meanwhile, Spike's in almost constant pain, and he's pretty sure it's related to the chip. Buffy tries to contact Riley to see if the former Initiative operative can help, but when she's only able to reach a flower shop, she quips, "It's either a wrong number or a giant government conspiracy."

Back in Willow's room after their date, Kennedy leans in and kisses Willow. Kennedy's got a dreamy look on her face until she opens her eyes to see the face of Warren staring back at her. Kennedy freaks, and Willow is horror-stricken to see the image of her dead nemesis in the mirror instead of her own face. She races downstairs and is confronted by the gang, including Buffy, who takes a swing at her. Him. Whatever. It's only once Buffy makes physical contact that they realize Willow/Warren isn't the First (since the First can only take non-corporeal form.) Willow takes off to fix the enchantment herself, convinced it's her own guilt that has brought it on. She has no luck, but Kennedy shows up to help, and Willow grudgingly allows her to come along.

At the Summers house, the Scoobies get a call from England that arouses their suspicions. They hear about how Giles had been on the wrong end of an axe swing, but no one knows how he could have escaped. Worried that they've left the Slayerettes in the hands of the First, everyone (including Andrew) sets out to find them.

Willow and Kennedy show up at a UC Sunnydale coven meeting seeking help, and Will is shocked to find Amy there. The former rat has been attending meetings, trying to sort out her own problems, and is sympathetic to Willow's plight. She offers to help by performing a chant, but when she does, Willow hauls off and slaps her. Warren has surfaced briefly and is trying to take over Willow's personality. Willow takes off, throwing a spell to keep Kennedy from following her.

Willow--uh--Warren ends up at a gun shop. S/he makes a purchase, which can only mean one thing: trouble.

Buffy and Spike locate the old Initiative's underground caverns, hoping to find a solution to the chip problem. When they break in, they find dozens of demon corpses left to rot when the military sealed the place. Unfortunately, the demons aren't all dead, and one of them attacks and drags Spike away. Buffy chases him, and ends up killing the demon just as the lights come up. It's the military! Riley apparently got the message and instructed them to do whatever Buffy needed. "I knew it," she cries, "a giant government conspiracy!" They offer assistance to Spike about the chip, which they can either repair or remove. It's up to Buffy.

After a long car trip into the wilderness, the gang attacks Giles, feeling him up in a rather suggestive manner. Fortunately, he's as corporeal as they come, and the girls are all safe. Crisis averted.

However, another crisis arises for Kennedy, who realizes that Amy's not nearly as sympathetic towards Willow as she pretended. Evidently, Amy's at fault for the Willow/Warren transformation. Envious of her enormous power, Amy placed a hex on Willow that allowed her to choose her own punishment. Out of guilt, Willow is now losing her identity. Kennedy is not about to let that happen, but Amy snaps her fingers and sends her to the Summers backyard just as Willow comes roaring in, gun in hand. It's a reenactment of the day Tara was killed, only this time, Willow's the would-be shooter. She raves at Kennedy, who's confused by Willow's ramblings. Turns out Willow isn't feeling guilty for killing Warren, but for forgetting, even for a moment, Tara. It's killing her to let go of her dead lover, but Kennedy realizes the spell can be broken, just like in fairytales, with a kiss. When she pulls away, Willow is herself again, and arms wrapped around each other, they go quietly into the house.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "FIRSTDATE" "Buffy.guide: First Date"

@{b}First Date@{ub}
7ABB14

Giles finally explains how he managed to escape the ax-wielding Bringer all those months ago: his "exceptional instincts and years of training" saved his life. Or maybe it was luck, and a pair of squeaky Bringer shoes. He soon realizes that Spike is now chipless, since Buffy had the Initiative remove it and not repair it. Giles isn't pleased at all, worrying over the safety of the Slayerettes as well as Buffy herself. Buff trusts that Spike can be a good person, but he needs to be given the opportunity. Giles still senses the connection between them, and though Buffy denies any physical relationship, she can't write it off altogether.

As Xander woos a woman, Lissa, over rope at a construction demonstration, Buffy decides to do some snooping in Principal Wood's office. His skeevy behavior of late (like the shovel incident in the basement) has her a little concerned. Robin catches her in his office, and Buffy comes up with a bad, yet somehow acceptable excuse. To her surprise, Wood asks her out on a date, and she agrees. After Buffy leaves, Wood lifts a wipe board to reveal a vast and very shiny collection of knives. Sharp knives.

Buffy talks with Willow about her upcoming date with her boss, and comes up with three possibilities for his motivation. 1) He thinks she's hot. 2) He wants to promote her. Yeah, right. 3) He wants to kill her. Buffy waffles about her own intentions towards the Woodster, but decides that she could really like him.

Andrew's trying to set up the new microwave when he's approached by the First in the guise of Jonathan. Playing on Andrew's guilt over having killed Jonathan, the First urges him to get Willow's new gun and kill the Potentials. After all, the First points out, Buffy's making Andrew pay for committing murder, but she doesn't give the same treatment to her other formerly murderous friends.

Xander is proud he has a date with Lissa, and Anya's jealous as hell. Buffy's excited about her date, but Spike is...less jealous. In fact, he seems perfectly okay with it when he runs into Buffy as she's getting ready, but he still very obviously cares for her, and vice versa. Downstairs, Willow and the Potentials do some Googling on the Principal and are surprised to find absolutely no record of him at all. Spooky.

That night, Robin is taking Buffy down a seamy back alley to a restaurant she's never heard of when they're jumped by a pile of Vamps. Buffy's convinced Wood set her up, but as she's kicking booty, she notices he's helping her out. When the Vamps are defeated, Robin leads a stunned Buffy into the restaurant. Buff is awestruck to learn that not only does he know she's the Slayer, but that his mother was the Slayer as well. Robin was four when she was killed, and he was raised by her watcher. He's been looking for revenge ever since, fighting evil and killing Vampires whenever he gets the chance.

Back at the house, Andrew presents the gun to the First, then starts to clumsily grill it for information about its weaknesses. "Are you wearing a wire?" a suspicious Jonathan/First asks. Oops. Apparently Andrew IS wearing one so Willow can listen in from the basement. Andrew's afraid, but he stands against the First, even though it's verrrrry angry with him now.

Poor Xander: he's fallen into a familiar trap of dating demonic chicks. His date, Lissa, is a baddie, and she hangs him up over the recently uncovered Seal of Danthalzar in the school. She's going to drain his blood till the seal opens and releases another Ubervamp. Terrific. Somehow, Xander manages to send a text message to Willow, and Spike heads out to retrieve Buffy from her date to rescue him.

Spike finds Buffy at the restaurant and drags both her and Robin to save Xander. Robin's stash of very sharp knives comes in handy, and they all attack Lissa. During the fight, Wood recognizes Spike's undeadness as the Vamp valiantly tries to defeat Xander's demon date. Xander's blood starts the Seal opening, but when Wood cuts him down, the Seal slams shut just in time. They defeat Lissa, and as they regroup, Wood notices the romantic tension simmering between Buffy and Spike.

At home, Giles berates the gang for focusing on romantic interludes instead of Evil. Later, Spike decides he's going to leave town, so as not to put Buffy in danger. However, Buff stops him, saying, "I'm not ready for you to not be here."

Wood recovers from the fight at his own home, and is approached by the First in the guise of his dead mother. The Principal isn't even remotely willing to switch sides, until the First reveals that he met his mother's killer that night. It's Spike.
	
@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "GETITDONE" "Buffy.guide: Get It Done"

@{b}Get It Done@{ub}
7ABB15

Buffy dreams of walking through the house, checking out the small army of girls taking up every inch of the house in sleep. In the corner, she spies Chloe crying, then is jumped by the First Slayer, who tells her, "It's not enough." She awakens spooked.

Anya and Spike, meanwhile, have taken off for a semi-date of drinking and debauchery when they are attacked by a demon sent by D'Hoffryn to kill Anya. Instead of killing it, Spike just beats it up and takes off with Anya in tow. He's gone pretty soft lately.

The next morning, Buffy and Robin Wood discuss the rise in bad behavior happening at Sunnydale High. Buffy's pretty sure that the typical Hellmouth-induced negativity is coming a little early. To help Buffy, Wood has brought an old emergency kit of his mother's that should have been handed down to the next Slayer, but Robin kept it.

Buff decides it's time for Wood to see where she does her real work, at home, with the baby Slayers. They meet Andrew, who's cooking, Kennedy, who's training the Slayerettes in fighting technique, and Willow, who's hauling weaponry. Wood has a run-in with Spike in the basement, and the animosity between them is palpable. Robin clearly wants to know all about Spike, but the Vamp can't figure out why.

Later that night, Dawn and Buffy check in on the Potentials, only to find that Chloe has hanged herself. As they stare at the body, the First appears as the dead girl, going on about how it's going to win no matter what they do, blah blah blah. When it disappears, Buffy has Chloe cut down and goes out to bury her body, alone.

Upon her return, all the girls are mourning. The Slayer is angry, declaring that Chloe was weak, and that the rest of them will be useless until they start really dedicating themselves to the fight. Buffy even complains that Spike's softer side isn't helping them at all. In Anya's words, it's an "everybody sucks but me" speech.

Buffy opens a locked box inside the emergency kit, and it contains a collection of shadow casters. According to the accompanying book, when viewed in order the shadows tell the story of how the first Slayer was created. The gang sets up the items, then watches as Dawn reads from an ancient, cryptic text. First there was the earth, demons, men, a girl. The men chained the girl to the earth to fight the demons, but to really understand what happened in the past, the Scoobies must make an "exchange": a portal opens, Buffy dives through it, and a giant demon with tusks appears and takes Buffy's place. The demon kicks their butts and takes off into the night. Since Willow's the one with the magic, it's up to her to reopen the portal and retrieve Buffy. But they need to get that demon back to make the exchange and bring Buffy back home.

Buffy arrives on a desert plain, alone. She finds a group of men, who explain she is the last (not the latest) guardian of the Hellmouth, and they can give her the power to fight evil. They knock her out and chain her, revealing that they are the source of her power. The men created the First Slayer by giving her the heart of a demon, and they want to do the same to Buffy. They release an evil mist to merge with Buffy.

While Willow unleashes her own power trying to recreate the portal, Spike finds his old leather jacket (which Wood seems to recognize) and, with his old swagger back in place, he takes off after the demon and kills it. That'll show Buffy he hasn't gone soft! Meanwhile, Willow gets the portal open, but only after taking power from both Anya and Kennedy, leaving them collapsed on the floor.

Finally, Buffy defies the evil mist swirling about her, breaking free of the chains and knocking the men down one by one. Although the last man declares that everything will be disrupted by her behavior, the Slayer doesn't really care. He wonders how she'll save the world without the power they had to offer, then touches her face for a moment, giving her a vision.

At that moment, the portal opens, and Spike tosses the demon through it. Buffy is home, surrounded by her friends.

Later, Kennedy is weirded out by Willow's earlier actions: it hurt when she took the power. Will is apologetic, but wants Kennedy to understand the truth of magic, that it's not always pleasant. The situation between them remains unresolved, and Kennedy walks off, alone.

Will goes to Buffy, who is grateful for being brought back. However, Buffy thinks she may regret rejecting the power the men offered, because the vision they gave her was of an enormous army of ferocious Ubervamps, armed and ready to attack.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "STORYTELLER" "Buffy.guide: Storyteller"

@{b}Storyteller@{ub}
7ABB16

In the vein of Masterpiece Theatre, Andrew enjoys a quiet evening by the fire, and he's ready tell us a heroic tale that he likes to call "Buffy, the Slayer of the Vampires." However, his surroundings are only an illusion, broken by Anya pounding on the bathroom door. He's videotaping himself telling Buffy's story, so he takes his camera elsewhere.

Andrew has decided to preserve Buffy's history and heroism for all time, and the only person not interested is Buffy, who's more worried about Ubervamps than which camera angle works. To assist in his storytelling, Andrew gets out his Big White Board, an excellent visual aid in explaining the players in his story. His imagination tends to run away with him, since he envisions Buffy with the wind in her hair as she pours cereal, while a shirtless Spike canoodles with the Slayer over bran flakes. Ahem.

As Buffy fills in the gang on her vision of the Ubervamps, Andrew reviews his "history" as "leader" of the Evil Trio. He also spies Willow and Kennedy making eyes at each other (as well as making out), which is a relief after their little tiff over Willow's magical power. Andrew is reminded of his own run-in with Dark Willow last year, and in his own mind he was easily able to deflect her powers. Sure.

At Sunnydale High, all hell is breaking loose, literally. People are disappearing, mirrors are talking, heads are exploding. Something's building up inside the school, and it's about to blow.

Andrew sits Anya and Xander down for a chat, and brings up the fact that today would have been their wedding anniversary. Xander's paid his dues as the bad guy, but Anya still has feelings for him. Later, the two realize they still love one another, but neither knows exactly what that means. Andrew has set up his camera to tape them clandestinely, and later, he lovingly rewinds the sappiest parts of their conversation over and over.

Back at the school, Buffy and Wood investigate the source of the problem: the Seal. Robin gets a closer look, but he's too close, He becomes possessed momentarily, and his anger over Buffy and Spike's relationship emerges. He almost spills it about Spike having killed his mother, but he breaks out of his trance just in time.

Spike, meanwhile, is performing his tough-guy act for Andrew in the laundry room.

When Wood and Buffy get home, they grab Andy and demand that he help them shut down the Seal, since he's the one that opened it in the first place. But it looks like Buffy and Wood left the school too soon, because back in the Sunnydale High basement five students circle the Seal, and it starts to glow.

Willow uses a crystal to pull out of Andrew memories of how he learned about the Seal. He flashes back to his time in Mexico with Jonathan, when he was first approached by Warren/First. Godhood was to be his reward (if you call visions of carousing and singing in a field of flowers god-like). In Mexico, Andrew located a knife somehow connected to the Seal, and used it to kill Jonathan. He stored the knife in Buffy's kitchen, and after they find it, they head for Sunnydale High.

When Buffy, Wood, Spike and Andrew arrive, the school is a complete wreck. Fires have broken out, spray paint is everywhere, and what students remain are wreaking havoc. A mob of kids attack, and after overpowering them, Wood and Spike stay at the door to the basement to keep everyone away from the Seal. Taking advantage of the situation, Wood tries, but fails, to kill Spike.

The Slayer attempts to get the truth out of Andrew about killing Jonathan. It's virtually impossible, since Andrew constantly changes his story. When they arrive at the Seal, five Bringers (formerly students) await them.

Meanwhile, at home, Anya and Xander bask in the afterglow on Spike's cot. For Anya, it seemed like "one more time," but Xander isn't so sure. Whatever he was hoping for, "one more time" isn't it.

Buffy defeats the Bringers, but the real fight--getting Andrew speak the truth for once in his life--has just begun. The Slayer says she's learned that the blood of the one who opened the Seal will close it, and she threatens Andrew with the knife. Buffy forces him to recognize his action for what it really was: a murder, an act that he deserves to be punished for. Andrew bursts into tears, deeply regretting his crimes. A lone tear falls on the Seal, and suddenly, the Seal stops glowing. Buffy had hoped the plan would work, and doesn't answer when Andy asks what would have happened if it hadn't.

Back home, Andrew tells his real story to the camera. He killed Jonathan, and he probably won't make it through the next fight. Maybe he doesn't deserve to. It's his most honest moment, and he shuts the camera off.

