@node "ABOUTSPIKE" "Buffy.guide: About Spike"

@{b}Spike (William the Bloody)@{ub}
(James Marsters)

1997 - present

Originally Buffy's arch-nemesis, Spike was rendered impotent by the Initiative with a behaviour modifying chip implant in his brain. Becoming as much a part of the Scooby Gang as a soul-free creature can be, Spike falls in love with Buffy during the fifth season. ###todo

Nicknamed as "Spike" because of his fondness for torturing his victims with railroad spikes, William the Bloody once hunted side-by-side with Angel. Since then, Angel has had a change of heart about killing humans. Spike on the other hand, will kill anyone who gets in his way. The Anointed One found that out the hard way when Spike became angry and hoisted him up into the sunlight, burning him to nothing. Two hundred year-old Spike was formerly known as William the Bloody, and earned his new nickname from his habit of torturing his victims with railway spikes. He will be a formidable opponent for Buffy and the gang: he's already killed two Slayers. Appears in many Buffy episodes.

James Marsters, who has appeared on "Buffy the Vampire Slayer" as the goth-decked vampire Spike for the past two seasons, joins the cast as a series regular for the show's fourth season.

Born in the remote northern logging town of Greenville, CA, and raised in Modesto, CA, Marsters always knew he wanted to be an actor. From his debut as Eyeore in a fourth grade production of "Winnie the Pooh," he went on to study acting at New York's prestigious Juilliard. He began his professional career in the theater, performing in stage productions including "The Tempest" and "Red Roses" at Chicago's renowned Goodman Theatre.

Marsters made his onscreen debut guest-starring on the television series "Northern Exposure." He landed the prominent role of an ill-at-ease priest, which was cast locally in Seattle, soon after moving to the Pacific Northwest. He was inspired by the success to move to Los Angeles and within months was sinking his proverbial teeth into the role of Spike on "Buffy the Vampire Slayer."

Marsters made his feature film debut in October 1999 in "The House on Haunted Hill," a psychological horror film which also stars Geoffrey rush, Famke Janssen, Taye Diggs and Lisa Loeb.

When he's not working, Marsters enjoys playing the guitar, watching football and spending time with friends at the beach. He currently lives in Los Angeles.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "ABOUTSUNDAY" "Buffy.guide: About Sunday"

@{b}Sunday@{ub}
()

Appears in @{"The Freshman" LINK "THEFRESHMAN"}.

Sunday was the head of a gang of misfit vampires that hole up in the abandoned Psi Theta fraternity house, preying on unwitting freshmen. They then stole their belongings to furnish their own lair. Sunday was one of the few vampires actually able to defeat Buffy in their first encounter, nearly breaking the Slayer's arm.

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "ABOUTTARA" "Buffy.guide: About Tara"

@{b}Tara McClay@{ub}
(Amber Benson)

2000 - 2002

Often considered the latecomer and outsider of the group, Tara was invaluable to the Scooby Gang. She always lifted her girlfriend Willow's spirits, and also unfortunately was the catalyst for Willow's over-reliance on magic, leading to their split. After Willow ended up nearly getting Dawn killed, she went "cold turkey" and eventually won Tara back.

Soon after Tara and Willow got together again (much to everyone's delight), Tara was tragically shot dead when Warren made an attempt on Buffy's life. Buffy also took a bullet but survived... Warren however, boy did Willow make him pay for it (see @{"Villains" LINK "VILLAINS"}).

When the BBC asked Amber Benson who the oddest member of her family was, she replied: "Probably my sister. She shaved her head and she'll do anything for a dare."

@{b}Goto:@{ub}   @{" String Search " SYSTEM "newcli WINDOW=CON:20/20/400//Buffy from Buffy.guide.cli"}@{"?" LINK "SEARCHREADME"}  @{" Major Events " LINK "EVENTS"}  @{" Characters " LINK "CHARACTERPROFILES"}  @{" Vocabulary " LINK "VAMPVOC"}  @{" Main Page " LINK "MAIN"}
@endnode

@node "ABOUTTRIO" "Buffy.guide: About The Trio"

@{b}The Trio@{ub}

2001 - 200?###todo

The Trio consisted of @{"Warren ###todo" LINK "ABOUTWARREN"}, @{"Jonathan Levinson" LINK "ABOUTJONATHAN"} and @{"Andrew Wells" LINK "ABOUTANDREW"}.



Following the success of their BBC web chat last Friday, Danny Strong, Tom Lenk and Adam Busch wowed audiences at a special Buffy geeks convention this weekend.
The South convention at Heathrow's Radisson Edwardian hotel saw the terrible troika sending up themselves and each other in a series of hilarious talks.
Danny revealed that soap star Morgan Fairchild is a huge Buffy fan, Tom admitted his love for BBC comedy - in particular The Kumars at No. 42 - and Adam discussed his musical career with folk rock band Common Rotation.
Saturday evening's entertainment included a superb acoustic set from Adam and fellow Common Rotation band member Eric before Danny and Tom joined fans on the dance floor. The pair dancing to The Timewarp and The Locomotion isn't something you see every day.
Filming commitments (for what, we wonder?) meant the trio had to fly back to L.A. on Sunday afternoon, but everyone involved still seemed to enjoy this intimate gathering.
Organisers Sector 14 would like to offer attendees an apology, however. Despite their best efforts, everything ran almost completely to schedule. Apparently it's never happened before!
Danny, Tom and Adam will be back in the UK next weekend for the North <http://www.sector14.co.uk/> event in Glasgow.


